<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Velasquez     06-16 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Velasquez,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hispanic Organizer Dead Of Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie Velasquez, who dedicated his
career to increasing Hispanic political power, died Wednesday after
a bout with cancer, officials said. He was 44.
   Velasquez, 44, president of the non-profit Southwest Voter
Registration Education Project he helped found in 1972, died at
12:55 a.m. at Santa Rosa Hospital, said spokeswoman Terrie Carter.
   SVREP initially focused on voter registration and later, with
other organizations, sued local governments to convert from
at-large voting systems to single-member districts to assure equal
Hispanic representation.
   Velasquez, who was diagnosed with a cancerous left kidney, was
admitted to the hospital Monday. He had received treatment at M.D.
Anderson Hospital in Houston last month and was to begin
chemotherapy within weeks.
   Velasquez' nonpartisan efforts helped to increase Hispanic voter
registration, which has increased from 2.5 million in 1976 to an
expected 5 million for the general election in November.
   Velasquez was a founder of the activist Mexican-American Youth
Organization and later became a coordinator of El Movimiento Social
de la Raza Unida, before it became the Chicano political party.
   While in his last semester of graduate school of economics at
St. Mary's University in 1968, Velasquez was recruited by the
United Farm Workers to organize a strike in the Rio Grande Valley.
   After the strike, he became director of the Mexican-American
Unity Council in San Antonio and in June 1970, field director in
Phoenix of the National Council of La Raza, parent organization of
the Mexican-American Unity Council.
   Velasquez is survived by his wife, Jane; two daughters and a son.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
