<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0852,0532</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Beach Palmer and Billings; Separates moved for AMs as
a0404 on Velasquez and as a0839 on Hoyman.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Willie Velasquez</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie Velasquez, whose 16-year effort
to increase Hispanic voter registration led to the ethnic group
becoming a viable political force, died Wednesday of cancer. He was
44.
   In 1972, Velasquez helped found the SVREP, a non-profit
organization that initially sought to register Hispanic voters and
later, with other organizations, sued local governments to convert
from at-large voting systems to single-member districts to assure
equal Hispanic representation.
   He gained politicians' respect for his unpartisan effort to
increase Hispanic voter registration, which has increased from 2.5
million in 1976 to an expected 5 million for the general election
in November.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Vincent Hoyman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLEVUE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vincent Hoyman, a veteran Associated
Press newsman who retired in 1968 after 38 years with the news
service, died Thursday at age 83.
   Hoyman worked at the Des Moines, Iowa., Tribune Capital before
joining the AP in Pierre. He transferred to the Seattle bureau in
1937. Hoyman was named news editor in Seattle in 1939, a post he
held until his retirement.
   After his retirement he was manager of the News Election Service
for Washington state for several years.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Frank Beach</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank A. Beach, a pioneer in animal
behavior research and a emeritus professor of psychology at the
University of California-Berkeley, died Wednesday. He was 77.
   Beach was a highly acclaimed researcher in the fields of
behavorial endocrinology and animal behavior for more than four
decades. He was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and
the American Philosophical Society.
   Beach joined the UC faculty in 1958, attaining emeritus status
in 1978. His major research had concentrated on the neural and
endocrinological controls of sexual behavior, resulting in a
crucial body of research results, books and articles.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Fred Palmer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Palmer, managing editor of the
Pensacola News Journal since 1986, died Wednesday at age 38.
   Palmer was a reporter for the Johnson City, Tenn.,
Press-Chronicle from 1969 to 1971. He left to work at The Roanoke
Times in Virginia for two years, then returned to the
Press-Chronicle.
   Palmer was Press-Chronicle wire editor for a year, then was
promoted to managing editor, a position he held for 10 years. In
1983 he joined the Rockford, Ill., Register Star, first as city
editor, then as assistant managing editor-news. He left the
Register Star for the position at the News Journal.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James Billings</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Hopkins Billings, whose career as
a journalist for Springfield newspapers spanned nearly five
decades, died Tuesday. He was 78.
   Billings worked for the Springfield Press and United Press in
Memphis, Tenn., before becoming a page editor with the Springfield
Leader & Press.
   Over the years he worked in public relations and for a local
weekly news magazine, The Bias. Billings was news editor of The
Daily Journal in Coffeyville, Kan., for two years before returning
to the Leader & Press in 1957.
</TEXT>
