<FILEID>AP-PX-06-16-88 0049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APArts:JasonPlots     06-16 1051</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Jason Plots,1071</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>You Can't Keep a Good Man Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-AP Arts: Friday the 13th</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What a groovy guy that Jason Voorhees is _ ahead
of his time with that goalie mask fashion look, and ever so
creative with axes, knives and spears.
   He's a real human slice-and-dice machine, but not not too many
people like him. Still, they flock to see his movies _ seven so far
_ and he doesn't even have a speaking part.
   Here's a look at Jason's life and death and life and death in
the ``Friday the 13th'' sagas:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _ ``Friday the 13th'' (1980):
   Six frisky camp counselors reopen Camp Crystal Lake, which has
been closed for over two decades after a rash of unsolved murders.
A seventh, who hitchhikes to the camp, never quite makes it: She's
turned into a forest pizza. The other college-age dimwits romp
about until they, too, are carved into human kindling. Alice, the
last of the lot, runs into Mrs. Voorhees who lives nearby. She
promises to drive the hysterical girl to safety but instead talks
about her son, Jason, who drowned years ago while his counselors
made love in the woods. She turns on Alice with a hatchet; Alice
finally decapitates the madwoman and makes her way to a canoe which
drifts to the middle of the lake. In a blink, the drowned Jason
reaches up from his watery hell and grabs her. Alice abruptly
awakens in a hospital room to be told by police that Jason's body
was never found. Alice says: ``Then he's still there.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _ ``Friday the 13th Part 2'' (1981):
   A new batch of hot-blooded morons begin counselor training at
Lake Region, near Camp Crystal Lake. The camp leader, Paul, talks
about Jason _ an icon by now _ and says he's really alive, living
off wild animals and waiting to avenge his mother's death. One by
one, and two by two the randy counselors-to-be encounter Jason, who
enthusiastically dispatches his victims with a curved machete, a
spear thrust through two bodies, a hammer. Finally, only Paul and
his girlfriend, Ginny, are left. Thinking Paul dead, Ginny tries to
flee. She ends up at Jason's cabin where she finds a shrine to his
dead mother containing her decapitated head. Paul shows up,
struggles with Jason, and Ginny slices up the ``dead'' boy's body
with the machete. Paul and Ginny return to the cabin, and Jason
crashes through the window. Ginny wakes up in an ambulance.
``Where's Paul?'' she asks.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _ ``Friday the 13th Part 3 _ 3-D'' (1982):
   Yet another group of idiots heads for the lake, amid newscasts
of mass murders. Three bikers show up to taunt them and are
promptly dispatched by our Jason, who picks off the vacationing
college kids with his usual finesse: He shoots an arrow through a
head, cleaves a body, electrocutes one guy, slits a neck, thrusts a
hot fireplace poker through a chest. As usual, one hysterical
female is left, Chris. After a struggle, she imbeds an ax in
Jason's head, runs to the lake and paddles a canoe to the center _
silly girl. When she awakens in the morning, Mrs. Vorhees' body,
dripping with rotted flesh, explodes from the water and pulls Chris
under. Police take a deranged Chris away and we catch one last (?)
glimpse of Jason, the ax still rooted in his skull, his fingers
twitching.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _ ``Friday the 13th _ The Final Chapter'' (1984):
   Ten people have been slaughtered at Crystal Lake. Jason also
lies dead. The bodies are taken to the morgue where Jason, perky as
ever, rises up, slits the throat of an attendant and guts a nurse.
Back at the lake, Mrs. Jarvis and her two children, Trish and
Tommy, are in their summer home. A group of teen-agers has moved in
next door. The party's soon over, though, as they're harpooned,
crucified, hacksawed and otherwise minced. But Tommy is a horror
freak who has a makeup collection, masks and clippings about Jason.
He saves his sister and himself by putting on a hockey mask,
confusing Jason and grabbing the machete. Tommy whacks his personal
hero again, and again and again.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _ ``Friday the 13th _ A New Beginning'' (1985):
   Tommy Jarvis is now 18 and has nightmares about Jason. He lives
at a halfway house after being released from a mental institution.
Then the murders begin with axes, hunting knives and hedge shears
as the weapons du jour. Finally, Tommy comes face to face with
Jason who falls from a hayloft onto the steel spike teeth of a
tractor harrow. Rain washes away makeup from the corpse's face and
reveals the killer as a paramedic pretending to be Jason. Tommy,
who still has nightmares, is back in the hospital. He smiles
knowingly, pulls a hockey mask from his bureau, hides behind the
door and waits.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _ ``Friday the 13th Part VI _ Jason Lives'' (1986):
   Crystal Lake has changed its name to Forest Green. Tommy Jarvis
is now an adult and still haunted. He believes that the only way he
ever have a normal life is to make sure Jason is REALLY dead. So he
returns to Crystal Lake to see Jason's grave. He pries open the
coffin during a storm, and a bolt of lightning hits the crowbar
he's used, sending a charge through the decayed corpse. The
rejuvenated Jason works his way back to the lake leaving a trail of
blood and guts. Tommy follows him, lures him to the lake and
somehow traps Jason in chains and rocks so that he sinks to his
original watery grave.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _ ``Friday the 13th Part VII _ The New Blood'' (1988):
   Tina Shepard is telekinetic. While at Crystal Lake, her father
dies and she tries to bring him back. Instead, she accidentally
brings back Jason, who sets about doing what he does best.
Ultimately, Jason and Tina face off. Only this time when she does
some fancy brain work, she brings back her dead father, who
struggles with Jason and pulls him back to the depths of the lake,
where they set up housekeeping together until the next time?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
