<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-MotherTeresa 1stLd-Writethru a0882 06-16 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Mother Teresa, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0882,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Teresa Tells U.N. Abortion Is Greatest Threat To Peace</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Mother Teresa ...,' to CORRECT Mother
Teresa's title. PICKS up 4th graf, `The small ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY49</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa on Wednesday gave her best
wishes to the U.N. conference on disarmament and gave delegates a
new issue to ponder by saying ``abortion has become the greatest
destroyer of peace.''
   ``I think the world has never needed so much tender love as
today,'' she told reporters after she met Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar for a courtesy call.
   Mother Teresa, 77, works with and is the founder of the
international Missionaries of Charity, a religious order in
Calcutta. She received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979 for her work
to ease the suffering of dying slum dwellers, and is known there as
the ``saint of the gutters.''
   The small, frail-looking woman, wearing a white cotton shawl and
blue-trimmed robe, spoke fiercely against ``the evil of abortion,
of destroying children, of neglecting children.''
   ``We're fighting abortion by adoption, and we have saved
thousands of children from being destroyed, because as you know
abortion has become the greatest destroyer of peace because it
destroys the child, the gift of God. And it destroys the conscience
of the mother, it is actually a double killing.''
   When asked if she discussed with Perez de Cuellar the U.N.
population control programs, she said she had not. Many
anti-abortion activists have criticized the programs, saying them
promote abortion as a possible option.
   ``I think we talked of other things, that we didn't say,'' she
replied.
   Another reporter asked her why the concept of non-violence does
not seem to work in South Africa, where Mohandas K. Gandhi lived
for 21 years and where Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, the 1984
Nobel Peace Prize winner, carries on the tradition of peaceful
civil disobedience today.
   Mother Teresa said ``non-violence begins at home,'' adding,
``Our government in India and the government of South Africa have
given us full permission to go to South Africa. And we have a
mixture of all nationalities, and I am going to take take with me
different nationalities, different colors, and bring there with me
the joy of loving.''
   She said she was in New York to try to open a center to care for
children infected with AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-06-16-88 0131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-Drought     06-16 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Drought,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Gets Much-Ballyhooed Drought Briefing; Says Rain Needed to
End It</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: stands for PM-Farm Scene</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the end, Vice President George Bush's
appearance at the Agriculture Department for a drought briefing was
outshone by a career federal meteorologist's description of the
trouble spots and how they could worsen.
   Reporters who had been herded into a room to look at the vice
president, then herded out, ended up only with a written statement
in which Bush declared that rain is needed to end the drought
plaguing large portions of the country.
   Bush, accompanied by Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole and a White
House entourage, met Wednesday for about half an hour in the office
of Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng.
   For a while, the placid atmosphere of the old USDA
administration building was charged by the swarming of security
forces assigned to protect the vice president, who is expected to
be the Republican presidential nominee.
   The main elevators were stopped, and employees were routed far
around the sensitized area where Bush was to enter and walk within
the building. The department's flock of public affairs specialists
scurried and fluttered about.
   It was an exciting time for almost everyone _ except for
reporters looking for news.
   Reporters, photographers and television technicians were herded
into a conference room, or a holding pen, where they were required
to put all tape recorders and cameras on the floor and then move
outside to a hallway.
   Dozens of Secret Service and USDA security people hovered close
while a large German Shepherd was taken into the abandoned holding
area to sniff the equipment for bombs or weapons. None was found.
   After more waiting, the two dozen or so news people were allowed
to walk up one flight to Lyng's outer office. The group was allowed
to enter for a ``photo opportunity'' at which the subjects are
often asked questions over the clicks and whirrs of cameras.
   But Norton Strommen, the USDA's chief meteorologist, was
explaining a set of yellow-and-red charts to his audience,
including Bush and Dole, who were seated on a couch, and Lyng and
others in the official party.
   No questions were shouted by reporters while Strommen talked.
After a few minutes, all news people were sternly ordered out of
Lyng's office. Those who tried to tarry in the area were finally
herded downstairs again and lodged behind a yellow tape that
represented a security boundary.
   Bush and Dole then zipped out USDA's front door without enduring
a single question from reporters about drought or anything else.
   In his wake, Bush left a single-page statement noting that if
relief doesn't come soon, the corn crop could be in jeopardy.
``Without rain there is the potential for this to be a
catastrophe,'' he said, echoing Lyng's congressional testimony of
the day before.
   Bush said farmers in 21 states are receiving some form of
emergency relief, ``but sad to say, nothing will take the place of
rainfall, and we have to be concerned about the plight of the
nation's farmers.''
   Strommen filled in the gaps later, gathering up his charts and
leading reporters back into the conference room where he summarized
his presentation to Bush and Dole.
   Strommen said the West is severely lacking in moisture from
reduced snowpack during the winter, which resulted in
``well-below-normal'' reservoir levels in much of the region,
including Idaho, Washington, Oregon and Nevada.
   Another major problem area is in the northern Great Plains,
notably in Montana and the Dakotas, he said. And dry areas still
persist in the Southeast, which has not yet fully recovered from
the 1986 drought.
   ``The best areas in terms of moisture are the Southwest, up into
the central Great Plains ... in Kansas and Nebraska,'' Strommen
said.
   Just in the last two weeks, the drought has expanded into the
eastern Corn Belt states of the Midwest, and ``this is a major
concern for us,'' he said.
   Without substantial rains soon, Strommen said the Corn Belt
drought has a ``potential for deterioration'' of crops.
   However, he said, ``it simply is too early in the growing season
to try to define what that potential is.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-06-16-88 0135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan'sFarewell Bjt   06-16 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan's Farewell, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Toronto Summit is Reagan's Final Bow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will be bidding farewell to
summitry next week in Toronto.
   Eight years ago, Reagan went to his first economic summit in
Montebello, Quebec, as an untried figure on the world scene, a
former movie actor reading his remarks from cue cards, on the
defensive about a huge budget deficit, and espousing economic
beliefs that some of his colleagues found dubious if not ridiculous.
   On Sunday, he leaves Washington for his last economic summit.
Once again, it will be in Canada. Reagan will still be reading from
cue cards. He still has the same conservative beliefs. The U.S.
budget deficit has zoomed from $78.9 billion in 1981 to an
estimated $146.7 billion.
   But this time, it's different.
   For one thing, Reagan has been in office longer than any of the
other summit leaders except his staunch ally from Britain, Margaret
Thatcher. She and France's Francois Mitterrand will be the only
leaders there who were on board in 1981.
   For another, the president's aides are confident this time of
the kind of reception Reagan will get from his colleagues as he
makes what will almost surely be his final bow on the global stage.
   ``I think they have learned what the rest of the world learned,
which was not to underestimate Ronald Reagan,'' the president's
chief spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, said.
   ``I'm told that at the first summit, he was regarded as a sort
of quaint, amusing character from the past, when he talked about
markets and private enterprise and entrepreneurship,'' said
Undersecretary of State Allen Wallis. ``Now, at the summits that's
all they do _ everybody talks in that framework.''
   ``I hope and believe that there is going to be a recognition on
the part of all of the countries there that reliance on free
markets and reliance on open societies is the best way to foster
economic growth and sound economic development,'' said Secretary of
the Treasury James A. Baker III.
   ``This is the message, if I may say so, that President Reagan
took to the first economic summit in 1981, a message at the time
that was greeted with a certain skepticism and perhaps even some
derision,'' Baker said. ``And now, it is not so greeted, and
everybody is pretty much in sync and on board with that concept and
I think, hope and believe there will be a further endorsement of
that at this summit.''
   A European official in Washington, speaking on condition he not
be identified, said there is still some skepticism abroad, however,
about such things as Reagan's tax reduction programs and the U.S.
budget and trade deficits.
   ``I am sure President Reagan has, since 1981, marked
cornerstones on a number of things, but I am also sure we could not
afford the kind of policies which President Reagan affords in the
United States,'' the official said.
   As Reagan headed for Montebello eight years ago, one White House
aide, asking that he not be further identified, said, ``There is a
push that we project him as leader of the free world.'' But the
aide also indicated a fear that other participants would snipe at
the president's economic programs and challenge his influence.
   A Canadian Press writer said then that the new American chief
executive would have to rely on ``his good humor and charm'' to
cope with ``the greater international experience and intellect'' of
such leaders as Canada's Pierre Trudeau and West Germany's Helmut
Schmidt.
   Now, as Reagan prepares to go to Toronto, Fitzwater said: ``I
think they will see that the man they see in 1988 is the same man
they saw in 1980. The difference is what he's done, that he's
changed the face of the world. In terms of military strength,
certainly the strength of focus and purpose of NATO has been
strengthened by the president's commitment to it.''
   Fitzwater added: ``East-West relations have changed dramatically
under the president's leadership. The world economy is so much
stronger now than it was in 1980 and 1981. Those three elements of
achievement have given Ronald Reagan a whole new stature.
   ``Because Reagan is leaving office after so many years,
undoubtedly there will be a tribute to him of some kind,''
Fitzwater said. ``I don't know any specifics planned in terms of
organization, but I am sure the discussions and the statements will
in some way recognize the leadership that the president has given
to the economic summits.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   W. Dale Nelson covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
