<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bolivia-Drugs     06-16 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bolivia-Drugs,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talk Show With Drug Trafficker Prompts Government To Close TV And
Radio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government closed a TV station and a
radio station after they ran an interview with a major drug dealer
who said the U.S. State Department and Bolivia traffic narcotics.
   Carlos Palenque, owner of Channel Four and Radio Metropolitana
in the Bolivian capital, said he will begin a hunger strike to
oppose the one-year ban imposed Wednesday.
   Palenque interviewed convicted cocaine trafficker Roberto Suarez
Gomez, his son, and three other guests on a talk show last week.
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency says Suarez Gomez is one of the
top cocaine traffickers in Bolivia.
   In the show, Suarez Gomez said the U.S. State Department was the
``king of cocaine.''
   ``The vice royalty is the government of Bolivia and the
president is a boss at the service of the U.S. government,'' he
said.
   On Monday, the country's conservative government announced it
would close the stations for a year and said President Victor Paz
Esstensoro and the government were slandered. The government also
ordered the arrest of participants in the show.
   Despite congressional approval of the act, several legislators
expressed concern over the precedent of closing a station through
government edict instead of through the courts.
   The Association of La Paz journalists issued a statement saying
``we strongly condemn the local media for having offered an apology
for criminal behavior in violation of legal codes of conduct for
journalists.''
   Channel Four and Radio Metropolitana have a wide audience among
residents of poor La Paz neighborhoods and in rural areas. Palenque
also publishes a magazine that depicts acts of violence, rape and
murder.
   Three of the five guests on the talk show appeared earlier in a
videotaped meeting with Suarez Gomez at his Santa Cruz home and
nearby ranch. The tape also showed a meeting between Suarez Gomez
and Congressman Alfredo Arce Carpio and retired Gen. Mario Vargas
Salinas.
   The tapes led to a heated political debate in Bolivia, with
accusations that those who met with Suarez Gomez were soliciting
funds for political campaigns.
   Arce Carpio, who took a leave of absence from Congress after the
tapes were shown, says he met with Suarez Gomez to arrange a
newspaper interview and denies any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
