<DOCNO> AP880616-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0237EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Eban     06-16 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Eban,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ousted Statesman Was Israel's Spokesman For Four Decades</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior Labor Party legislator Abba Eban,
a founding father of the Jewish state and its leading spokesman for
years, has been ousted from Israeli politics after a generation in
its vanguard.
   The 73-year-old Eban, a former deputy prime minister and foreign
minister, failed in his bid Wednesday to win a slot on the party
slate for the November elections to the Israeli Parliament.
   Under the Israeli system, each party makes a list of people to
fill the seats it wins in the 120-member Knesset. The number of
seats assigned to a party depends on its total vote.
   After the Labor Party vote, Eban wrote to party leader and
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres: ``For a generation I carried (the
party's) flag and stated its case throughout the country and the
world, and many listened to me.
   ``It's clear I cannot keep carrying the flag as I did in the
past because the party leadership took away my right to do so.''
   Eban said he would now dedicate his time to writing books and
participating in a television series on Israel's history.
   The tall, portly Eban is known for his sophisticated oratory,
and Israel's first prime minister, David Ben-Gurion, once described
him as ``the voice of the Hebrew nation.''
   In his 40-year political career, Eban also served as Israel's
ambassador to the United States and the United Nations.
   Referring to his appeal abroad, Eban once said: ``I could have
been elected prime minister if people abroad could vote in Israeli
elections.''
   In domestic party politics, Eban never played a central role,
partially because his upper-class mannerisms and love of academia
set him apart from many of his colleagues.
   Since 1984, Eban has served as chairman of Parliament's Defense
and Foreign Affairs Committee, a position of influence but with
little direct power.
   Eban was born Feb. 2, 1915, in Capetown, South Africa, and his
family moved to England when he was a child. He attended Queens'
College Cambridge, where he received first class honors in
classics, Hebrew, and Arabic and Persian.
   During World War II, he joined the British army. When the war
ended, he joined the Jewish Agency Political Department, the
forerunner of Israel's Foreign Ministry, and was sent to the United
Nations to help fight for a Jewish state.
   His skill as a speaker was instrumental in persuading the United
Nations to pass the Nov. 29, 1947 Palestine partition resolution
that granted the Jews a homeland. Israel was declared a state a
year later.
   Eban's ouster Wednesday was in part an apparent payback for his
criticism of party leaders for the Jonathan Jay Pollard spy case.
   Pollard, a 33-year-old American Jew, was sentenced to life in
prison in March 1987 for selling classified U.S. military documents
to Israel.
   Eban made waves in the party last year when a Knesset
investigating committee he headed blamed Peres and Defense Minister
Yitzhak Rabin, a party member, for not supervising those involved
in the Pollard operation.
   Peres was prime minister when Pollard was working for Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chile-Communists     06-16 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Communists,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communists To Participate in Single-Candidate Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outlawed Communist Party departed from its
previous radical stance and said it will participate in a
presidential election in which the only candidate will be nominated
by the military.
   The Communists were until now the only major opposition group
refusing to participate. They had called for ``all forms of
struggle,'' including violence, to put an end to the military
regime of President Augusto Pinochet.
   The Party's Central Committee said Wednesday that the new
position was prompted by ``a new social-political picture in the
country'' resulting from the opposition's ``social mobilization and
intense political battle.''
   But Patricio Aylwin, a Christian Democratic leader, said the
Communists still will remain excluded from a group of 14 moderate
opposition parties united for the vote.
   According to the 1980 military-drafted Constitution, the
election will take place at an unspecified date later this year or
early 1989.
   Citizens will only be able to vote ``yes'' or ``no'' on a
candidate to be nominated by the commanders of the three armed
services and the head of the national police.
   Pinochet, 72, who has ruled since a 1973 coup, is considered the
most likely candidate.
   Four Communist leaders said at a news conference that they still
think the government will try to win the plebiscite fraudulently
and called for labor unrest and street demonstrations.
   Jose Sanfuentes, a party leader, said, ``The victory of the `no'
in the plebiscite should mean an immediate end to the dictatorship
and its fascist legislation.'' He said it should lead to a
``transitional democratic government'' to call an early competitive
presidential election.
   The moderate opposition says a ``no'' victory should be followed
by negotiations with the military to ensure a peaceful and orderly
transition to full democracy.
   But the government insists that whatever the vote upcome, the
Constitution will remain unchanged. That means if the
military-picked candidate is rejected, Pinochet would remain in
office for an extra year, until 1990, when an open election would
be called.
</TEXT>
