<HEAD>Major Supermarket Suspends Sales Of South African Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ito-Yokado Co., a major Japanese supermarket
operator, has suspended sales of South African products because of
the country's apartheid policy, a company official said today.
   ``The decision not to deal in South African products was made in
view of the growing criticism in and outside the company'' of South
Africa's policy of racial segregation, said supermarket spokesman
Yasuo Takaha.
   Sales of canned yellow peaches and canned fruit cocktail
imported through a Japanese trading company were suspended at the
company's 133 shops across the country in April.
   Takaha said the decision was made during a company meeting in
March, but the supermarket chose not to make a formal announcement.
He said the products have been replaced with similar items from the
United States.
