<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0305EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-ForeignMedia     06-16 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Foreign Media,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Attacks Foreign Reports On Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese police today accused the foreign media of
``sheer fabrications'' in reporting a student sit-in. It was the
second attack in a week on foreign accounts of student unrest.
   The official Xinhua News Agency quoted Wang Jingrong, a
spokesman for the Ministry of Public Security, as saying foreign
journalists reported students were arrested or beaten by police at
sit-in Friday on academic issues.
   ``Such stories in some foreign media are sheer fabrications,''
Xinhua quoted Wang as saying.
   He confirmed that police broke up the protest outside
Zhongnanhai in Beijing, a walled compound that houses party
headquarters and residences for top leaders. The students were from
Changchun in northeast China's Jilin province.
   But in a telephone interview, Wang refused to give details of
how the protest was broken up.
   No Western reporters saw the brief sit-in. The French news
agency Agence France-Presse quoted a witness as saying police led
away about 60 protesters, and said police later confirmed the
students were taken away.
   But AFP said it did not report any police beatings of the
students, and the target of Wang's criticism was not immediately
clear.
   Last week, Xinhua accused the U.S. government Voice of America
radio of falsely reporting a student was arrested in a separate
sit-in June 8. VOA denied the charge, and said it only reported
that one person was led away by police.
   That sit-in involved about a dozen Beijing University students
who were trying to hold a pro-democracy protest in central
Beijing's Tiananmen Square. Hundreds of students had rallied on
campus and planned a march to the square, but police cordoned it
off and no march was held.
   The protest Friday involved students who attended an
unaccredited ``special training course'' in Changchun and wanted
government accreditation for their diplomas, the official China
Daily said.
   It quoted Wang as saying police stopped the sit-in because ``the
students violated the rules for maintaining social order by
interfering in the work of the government.''
   The incident prompted a State Education Commission announcement
Tuesday calling for a crackdown on unauthorized schools and
training classes that lack official accreditation.
   A growing number of such classes have been set up privately and
by work units in recent years, generally to teach English and
technical subjects, because of a shortage of places in accredited
schools. But their certificates or degrees are not recognized by
would-be employers.
   Officials have made it clear they will not tolerate a repeat of
the massive student protests of the winter of 1986-87, when
thousands of students in Beijing and other major cities marched
through the streets to demand democracy and freedom.
   Those protests ended with a crackdown on Western-style
liberalism and the ouster by conservatives of Communist Party chief
Hu Yaobang for failing to halt the protests quickly enough.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0306EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Haiti 1stLd-Writethru a0467 06-16 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0467,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New President Challenges The Generals Who Ensured His Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to restore dropped word. Picks up 3rd graf,
`Manigat on ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ President Leslie Manigat has
rejected the transfers of several high-ranking army officers,
publicly challenging for the first time the powerful military
command that ensured his election.
   The apparent power struggle began when Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy,
head of the three-man junta that ran Haiti until Manigat's election
in January, ordered the transfers or retirements.
   Manigat on Wednesday overruled the orders, claiming they were
unconstitutional since he had not been consulted.
   On Wednesday night, the Army General Staff issued a statement
pledging loyalty to Manigat and delaying the transfer orders.
   ``It has been decided after a meeting with ... the president and
the minister of defense to temporarily put off the above mentioned
steps,'' said the statement, broadcast on the private Radio Haiti
Inter.
   ``The transfer and retirement of certain high-ranking officers
and other officers decided Tuesday morning by the
commander-in-chief'' had been rescinded to ``avoid a major
crisis,'' said the statement from the national palace read on local
radio stations.
   It was unclear whether Manigat had prevailed.
   ``The situation is grave,'' said a Western diplomat, speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``Either the general submits to Manigat's
ultimatum, or there will be a stand-off between the government and
the army. There is fear of a clash.''
   One of the officers Namphy tried to reassign is Col. Jean-Claude
Paul, who heads the widely-feared Dessalines Battalion and was
indicted in the United States on drug trafficking charges in March.
   Haiti Inter, quoting an unidentified military source, said
Namphy ordered Paul relieved of his command of the 700-man
battalion and named assistant chief of staff, a largely
administrative position.
   Soldiers under Paul's command have been blamed for widespread
violence against voters that forced the cancellation of last
November's independently adminstrated general elections and left
more than 30 people dead.
   Manigat, the army's candidate in the Jan. 17 junta-run
elections, has always claimed that he could govern independent of
the army, which has controlled Haiti during most of its 184-year
history.
   A government spokeswoman said Wednesday that everyone was
waiting to see what would happen.
   ``This is certainly a moment of crisis,'' said Anaise Chavenet,
spokeswoman for the Ministry of Information.
   Manigat scheduled a news conference for this morning.
   The army's statement, signed by General Secretary of the General
Staff Col. Gary Leon also said the high command reaffirmed its
``unreserved loyalty to the government of the state within the
framework of constitutional and legal provisions.''
   Namphy was head of the three-man junta that ruled Haiti for two
years after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled into exile in France
in February 1986.
   Manigat, a former political science professor, was elected in
army-supervised balloting that was boycotted by the opposition that
foreign observers said was fraught with fraud.
   The United States cut off most of its aid to Haiti after the
aborted November balloting.
   Paul was indicted in March by a grand jury in Miami on charges
of conspiring to import 220 pounds of cocaine into the United
States from Latin America in December 1986. He has denied the
charges.
   Last week, Foreign Minister Gerard Latortue said in Washington
D.C, that his government is ready to open an investigation into
Paul's alleged drug connection as soon as it officially receives
the evidence from the United States.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Jeffrey Lite said details of the charges
were delivered to Haitian authorities last week.
   Manigat, a Social Democrat considered right-of-center and
staunchly anti-communist, has done little to alleviate Haiti's most
pressing problems.
   Haiti, which a population of 6 million, is the poorest country
in the Western Hemisphere. It shares the island of Hispaniola with
the Dominican Republic.
</TEXT>
