<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Espionage     06-16 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Espionage,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Told That U.S. Secrets Intended For Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian who lived for a time
in Hungary has been charged with espionage for allegedly gathering
secrets about U.S. submarine-monitoring operations for the Soviet
Union.
   Stephen Joseph Ratkai, 25, a native of Nova Scotia, was charged
with three counts of espionage under Canada's Official Secrets Act
during an appearance in St. John's provincial court on Wednesday.
   Officials have not said whether any information was actually
passed to the Soviets.
   Ratkai was ordered held without bail until June 28. He did not
have to enter a plea.
   The suspect said nothing when reporters shouted out questions as
he left the courthouse.
   Ratkai was accused of gathering classified U.S. military
documents about the U.S. Navy's submarine-tracking base in the
Argentia naval base during 1987 and 1988.
   The documents were intended for a foreign power, ``namely the
Union of Soviet Socialist Republics,'' the charges said.
   Ratkai was arrested last Saturday in St. John's following a
2{-year investigation by the Canadian Security Intelligence
Service, the Royal Canadian Mounted Police and the U.S. Naval
Investigative Service.
   Argentia base, on Newfoundland's foggy south coast, keeps an eye
on Soviet submarines by monitoring a network of underwater
listening devices in the North Atlantic near Greenland, Iceland and
Britain. The base is jointly operated by up to 400 U.S. military
personnel and 70 Canadians.
   The base commander, Capt. Brooks Chesser, said Tuesday that a
member of the base staff cooperated with Canadian security agents
in investigating Ratkai.
   Chesser would not say whether Ratkai approached the base member
to seek classified documents or whether he was given doctored
documents to pass to the Soviets.
   Ratkai's mother came from Nova Scotia. His father was a
Hungarian who emigrated to Canada after the Soviet Union cracked
down on an anti-Soviet uprising in 1956.
   After his mother committed suicide Ratkai lived in Hungary for a
while as a child. Later he returned to Canada.
   In 1983, he moved back to Hungary before again moving back to
Canada.
   Ratkai was the fourth person charged under Canada's Official
Secrets Act since 1950. Only one of the four has been convicted.
   That was in January 1986, when former Royal Canadian Mounted
Police officer James Morrison pleaded guilty to having passed
secrets to the Soviets in 1955. He was sentenced to 18 months in
jail.
</TEXT>
