<HEAD>Quotes From the Presidential Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments from the presidential
campaign trail:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   GEORGE BUSH, speaking Thursday about the drought in the midwest:
``While it is too early to fully assess any damage from the
drought, without rain there is the potential for this to be a
catastrophe ... Sad to say, nothing will take the place of
rainfall, and we have to be concerned about the plight of the
nation's farmers.''
   
   JESSE JACKSON, on prospects for floor fights at the Democratic
National Convention over issues important to his campaign:
``Sometimes you win, sometimes you lose. ... If you lose you will
at least have left your imprint.''
   
   REP. CHARLES RANGEL, D-N.Y., urging strong consideration for
Jesse Jackson as the Democrats' vice presidential nominee: ``We
come in with a candidate. ... It seems to me that Governor Dukakis
has to come up with a better candidate, or at least be prepared to
share with us why he does not believe that Reverend Jackson is the
best candidate.''
   
   LESLIE DACH, Michael Dukakis' spokesman, on the Democrat's plans
to campaign in the South: ``Mike Dukakis knows he can win states in
the South and he's going to campaign actively there. While George
Bush has a lot of homes, he has no secure political base and he's
going to have to campaign everywhere.''
</TEXT>
