<DOCNO> AP880616-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0452EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Reforms     06-16 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Reforms,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalist Advocates Sweeping Democratic Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent journalist has proposed radically
altering Soviet politics so the people elect their chief executive
by secret ballot and power is transferred from the Communist Party
to the government.
   Fyodor Burlatsky calls for the changes in this week's edition of
the literary newspaper Literaturnaya Gazeta.
   He says the Soviet Union's parliament, the Supreme Soviet,
should be given broad powers, including the right to allocate the
budget and impeach the president. The body now merely ratifies the
Communist leadership's decisions.
   The main thesis of Burlatsky, a former Kremlin adviser and
prominent Soviet political thinker, is that the government should
be strengthened to the detriment of the party, which now holds a
monopoly on political power.
   ``Russia had some elements of democracy before, but never had
liberal traditions ... the freedom of an individual from
interference by the state,'' Burlatsky wrote. ``Russia never had
any notion about basic human rights.''
   The far-reaching article in the weekly newspaper of the Writers'
Union is one of the most radical critiques of the system yet to
appear under the auspices of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's program of
liberalization.
   Burlatsky expands on points included in proposals to be
discussed at an extraordinariy Communist Party conference that
begins June 28.
   He says the country's leader should be elected ``by direct and
secret ballot by all the people'' rather than in a meeting of the
Politburo of the Communist Party Central Committee.
   Burlatsky suggests a candidate should first attain the post of
party general secretary, now the highest Soviet office, then run
for president.
   He does not say if more than one candidate should be allowed to
run for each office. The writer also calls for the creation of the
post of vice president.
   Supporters of the Gorbachev reforms say their efforts are
hampered by conservative officials in the party and government who
stand to lose power and privilege.
   Conservatives blocked Burlatsky and other outspoken reformers
from being included among the 5,000 delegates to the party
conference. The conference can debate and set party policy, but is
not expected to make leadership changes.
   Burlatsky is vice presdident of the Soviet Political Science
Association and a regular contributor to Literaturnaya Gazeta.
   He first gained prominence as an adviser to Nikita Khrushchev,
who was ousted as Soviet leader in 1964 by a group which included
Leonid I. Brezhnev, who lead the Soviet Union until his death in
1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
