<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Market Up, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands as 2nd Ld-Writethru to f0303</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed at a new
record high Thursday, while the dollar lost ground in trading
against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average finished the day's session at
28,147.32 points, up 53.80 points or 0.19 percent, surpassing its
previous record reached Wednesday, when the index gained 31.72
points.
   After opening the day lower at 126.22 yen, the dollar edeged
down further and closed at 125.98 yen, down 0.34 yen.
   ``The market is carrying on Wednesday's strength, which was
fueled by an overnight advance on Wall Street,'' said an official
of a major securities firm, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   On Wednesday, Tokyo's main economic barometer posted a record
28,093.52-point close, surpassing the previous closing high of
28,072.02 of last Thursday.
   The securities firm official said the market's buying mood
remained strong, and said activity in non-ferrous metals issues was
the key force behind the Nikkei rise early Wednesday.
   The dollar opened at 126.22 yen, down from Wednesday's close of
126.32 yen, and was trading at the 126.14-yen level by midmorning.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo said the
dollar ``has stayed at a high level'' following the release of
figures Tuesday showing the U.S. merchandise trade deficit for
April was much lower than expected.
   Financial markets have reacted strongly in recent months to U.S.
trade figures which are seen as providing signals for the likely
direction of stocks and the dollar.
</TEXT>
