<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     06-16 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit Record High Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo stock market's key indicator set another
record high closing today for the second consecutive trading day,
while the U.S. dollar weakened in trading against the Japanese yen.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues added 53.80 points, or 0.19 percent, to close the day's
session at 28,147.32. It surpassed the previous record reached a
day earlier, when the index rose 31.72 points.
   ``Share prices drifted lower on profit-taking selling in the
afternoon, mainly in export-related issues,'' said an official with
a major Tokyo securities firm.
   The Nikkei index had closed the morning session higher at
28,214.52, up 121.00 points.
   The market was led by large-capital steels and metal issues, the
brokerage official added.
   Trading was moderate, with volume in the first section reaching
an estimated 1.4 billion shares, down from 2.5 billion shares
Wednesday.
   Advancing issues included machineries, chemicals and papers.
Constructions, housings, drugs and financials were lower.
   The dollar ranged between 125.98 yen and 126.25 yen before
closing at 125.98 yen, the day's low, down 0.34 yen from
Wednesday's finish.
   The dollar maintained strength in the morning, but weakened
during afternoon trading because high Japanese gross national
product figures for January to March 1987 were expected to be
released later today, said a foreign exchange dealer, speaking
anonymously.
   ``Participants anticipating higher GNP went on buying yen and
selling dollars,'' he said.
</TEXT>
