<HEAD>Democratic Committee To Meet June 24</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic Platform Drafting Committee
will meet again in Denver on June 24, on the eve of a two-day
meeting of the full platform committee.
   The 16-member drafting committee, chaired by Rep. William Gray
III of Pennsylvania, spent three days at Mackinac Island, Mich.,
last weekend hammering out working papers on key issues.
   Gray promised the participants Sunday they would get a chance to
vote on a draft platform sometime before the full 186-member panel
takes up the document June 25-26 and the new meeting was announced
on Wednesday.
   Supporters of Michael Dukakis, the all-but-certain Democratic
nominee, and presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson were divided over
whether the platform should call for a freeze on Pentagon spending
and a tax increase on the wealthy.
   Jackson has enough delegates to force floor fights on any issues
he chooses at the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta. The
convention will take up the platform on July 19, its second night.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Democrats Plans to Serve Bologna at Bush's Houston Address</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Texas Democrats are planning to serve
bologna to fellow party members in the hotel suite that Vice
President George Bush lists as his legal residence.
   Democratic National Committee member Billie Carr and party
activist Ty Fain have rented the Houstonian Hotel suite that Bush
cites as his legal address.
   ``It's baloney for him to claim his residence is Texas,'' Carr
said.
   To illustrate their opinion, the two plan to serve bologna at
the suite to fellow Democrats Friday for the beginning of the Texas
Democratic Convention.
   Bush, who has wrapped up the GOP presidential nomination, lived
in Texas for years but hasn't owned a local residence since
becoming vice president in 1981. He was born in Massachusetts, grew
up in Connecticut, has a vacation home in Maine and votes in
Houston.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Simon Says Bush Has ``Credibility Problem'' on Education
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon says Vice President George
Bush's education proposals are ``cotton candy'' for schools that
need ``meat and potatoes.''
   Simon, an Illinois who lost his bid for the Democratic
presidential nomination, said Wednesday that Bush's ideas ``lack
vision about what has to be done to bring a first-rate education to
every American child.''
   Bush on Tuesday unveiled $600 million in new or expanded
education programs, including a $500 million National Merit Schools
plan that would furnish $100,000 awards to schools that make
strides in educating the disadvantaged.
   But Simon said Bush's statement that he wants to be the
``education president'' sounds like ``an election-year conversion.''
   ``After eight years of not lifting one finger while the White
House'' was seeking deep cuts in education, Simon said, ``Mr. Bush
has a great credibility problem with the claim that he intends to
be `the education president.'''
</TEXT>
