<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon     06-16 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Killed In Palestinian Faction Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas loyal to PLO chief Yasser
Arafat fought Syrian-backed mutineers with mortars and
rocket-propelled grenades in two refugee camps, killing seven
people and wounding 16, police said today.
   The overnight battle brought the toll to 26 killed and 117
wounded since fighting for control of Chatilla and Bourj
el-Barajneh broke out last week.
   The fighting pitted guerrillas of the Palestine Liberation
Organization's mainstream Fatah faction and adversaries of the
Fatah-Uprising, a group that rebelled against Arafat's leadership
in May 1983.
   The clashes raged all night and faded into sporadic exchanges of
sniper fire this morning, police said.
   A security committee comprising guerrilla officers from seven
other PLO factions not been involved in the fighting was trying to
arrange for observers to enforce a truce in the two shantytowns.
   A police spokesman said two Libyan observers would be stationed
at each of the two camps along with fighters from the seven neutral
factions.
   The disengagement force also will supervise the implementation
of a cease-fire reached in Damascus, Syria, on Monday.
   The Fatah rebels are led by Col. Saeed Mousa. They have been
based in Damascus since the mutiny began.
   Arafat's loyalists dislodged Mousa's fighters from the two camps
in previous rounds of fighting. But Mousa's guerrillas regrouped
and this week mounted new assaults seeking to regain their old
positions.
   Syria has about 40,000 troops in Lebanon. They are stationed in
east and north Lebanon, Moslem west Beirut and Beirut suburbs next
to the camps.
   A Palestinian source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the Libyan observers will be drawn from a 300-strong contingent
based in east Lebanon since 1982, when it came to Lebanon to help
fight the Israeli invasion.
   The independent Beirut daily newspaper An-Nahar reported Tuesday
that Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi has ordered the withdrawal
of his contingent from Lebanon.
</TEXT>
