<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-16 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dry Weather Continues Over Drought-Plagued U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms dampened sections of the
drought-plagued Midwest today, but dry weather prevailed elsewhere
after severe storms spawned damaging tornadoes in Colorado.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from east-central New Mexico
to southern Kansas, northern Oklahoma, southern Illinois and
southwestern Indiana.
   Skies were clear over the East, the Gulf Coast, the
north-central United States and the Southwest. Rainfall totals for
the six-hour period ending at 2 a.m. EDT were generally less than a
quarter of an inch.
   A major dry spell has been damaging crops and tightening water
supplies in the Midwest and Southeast.
   On Wednesday, thunderstorms brought much-needed rain to the
central High Plains, but also generated twisters and large hail.
   Five tornadoes were sighted in Colorado, four of them in the
Denver area. The twisters tossed vehicles and storage sheds through
the air, tore off several roofs and injured seven people, none
seriously.
   Hail up to baseball size was reported in Messex, Colo.; Albin
and Glenrock, Wyo.; and Merino, Colo., where windows and trees were
damaged.
   In southeastern Colorado, thunderstorms produced heavy rain,
washing out a county road bridge east of Caddoa. Showers and
thunderstorms also fell in sections of Kansas, Missouri and
Illinois.
   In Chicago, just a trace of precipitation has been measured for
the first half of June, the longest dry spell in 118 years of
record-keeping.
   The nation's high Wednesday was 109 degrees in Phoenix, Bullhead
City and Coolidge, Ariz.; and Laughlin, Nev.
   Today's forecast called for widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the Great Plains, Arkansas and southern Missouri
to the mid- and northern Atlantic Coast; isolated showers and
thunderstorms in the Rocky Mountains; and sunny, dry weather in the
rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were expected to climb into the 60s and 70s over
the Great Lakes area, western Washington state and along much of
the California Coast; the 90s from Montana to western New Mexico;
the 90s to near 115 degrees in the desert Southwest; and the 80s
elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 41
degrees at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., to 92 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 74 fair; Boston 78 hazy; Buffalo 71 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 64 fair; Cincinnati 68 hazy; Cleveland 71
thunderstorms; Detroit 66 fair; Miami 77 fair; New York 68 fair;
Philadelphia 74 hazy; Pittsburgh 72 hazy; Portland, Maine 71 fair;
Washington 75 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 50 fair; Chicago 70 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
77 partly cloudy; Denver 60 fair; Des Moines 61 fair; Indianapolis
73 hazy; Kansas City 66 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 62
fair; Nashville 69 fair; New Orleans 70 fair; St. Louis 73 partly
cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 66 fair; Anchorage 54 showers; Las Vegas 80
fair; Los Angeles 59 cloudy; Phoenix 92 fair; Salt Lake City 70
fair; San Diego 61 cloudy; San Francisco 58 fair; Seattle 60 partly
cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 75 cloudy; Toronto 64 fair.
</TEXT>
