<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0651EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-DalaiLama     06-16 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Dalai Lama,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Objects to Dalai Lama News Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese official today criticized the European
Parliament for allowing Tibet's spiritual leader, the Dalai Lama,
to hold a news conference at the parliament building in Strasbourg,
France.
   The parliament had invited the Dalai Lama to make a formal
address, but withdrew the invitation after China showed displeasure
by canceling its invitation to the parliament to send a delegation
to China.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing refused to comment on the
Dalai Lama's offer at his news conference Wednesday to accept
Chinese troops in Tibet and Chinese control over the region's
external affairs in exchange for greater autonomy in internal
matters.
   Li told a weekly news briefing that he could not answer
questions about Tibet because Tibet is not a foreign country.
   An official who answered the telephone at the Nationality
Affairs Commission, which has responsibility for Tibet and other
minority areas, said he could not immediately comment.
   Li said, ``We are opposed to the provision of a forum to the
Dalai Lama for his activities aimed at undermining the unification
of the motherland by any foreign organizations or individuals.''
   The Dalai Lama said Wednesday that complete independence for
Tibet ``is very difficult to achieve.''
   He suggested a ``middle way,'' in which China would make Tibet a
self-governing, democratic political entity while continuing to run
Tibet's foreign affairs.
   He also agreed to a ``restricted number of (Chinese) military
installations'' in the remote Himalayan region.
   The proposal was the most conciliatory yet by the Dalai Lama
since he fled Tibet in 1959 during a failed uprising by his
followers against Chinese rule.
   The Dalai Lama is the spiritual leader of Tibetan Buddhists.
Before the Chinese Red Army entered the remote Himalayan region in
1950, he also was head of its theocratic civil government.
   China claims to have had sovereignty over Tibet since the 13th
century, but periods of actual control have been sporadic.
   The Dalai Lama has lived since 1959 in India and has repeatedly
accused the Chinese government of systematically violating human
rights in Tibet and oppressing the people by stationing hundreds of
thousands of soldiers there.
   Pro-independence sentiment remains strong among many Tibetans,
especially young Buddhist monks. Monks led anti-Chinese protests in
October and March in which thousands of Tibetatns stoned police and
attacked official buildings and cars.
   At least 38 people were killed in the two protests, and hundreds
were arrested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
