<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0658EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraSuit     06-16 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Suit,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mercenary Witness Should Be Jailed, Magistrate Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal magistrate says a former mercenary should
be jailed for refusing to cooperate in a $24 million lawsuit
against an alleged guns-for-drugs smuggling conspiracy to aid the
Contras.
   Sam Hall refused to answer questions or turn over documents
Wednesday in the civil case filed against U.S. government
officials, Contra leaders and Medellin Cartel drug traffickers by
two journalists and the liberal Christic Institute.
   ``It has to do with principle,'' Hall told U.S. Magistrate
William Turnoff. ``My past would have been in vain.''
   But the magistrate said Hall's position had no legal basis and
ordered him held in civil contempt until he answered the questions
during depositions. Turnoff said he would make his recommendation
to the presiding judge in the case, Chief U.S. District Judge James
L. King, who is on vacation until next week.
   The suit was filed by Martha Honey and her husband, Tony
Avirgan. Avirgan was injured in a 1984 bombing in Nicaragua that he
blames on the alleged conspirators.
   The damage and racketeering suit charges that members of a
right-wing terror network tracing back to 1959 illegally
participated in assassination plots, gun running and drug
trafficking.
   Hall, who will remain free at least until King returns to the
bench, said he has been told he can be jailed indefinitely for
refusing to hand over the documents, and for up to six months for
not answering questions.
   ``I'm prepared to go to jail as long as the case takes,'' he
said.
   Hall is not considered a major witness in the case, but the
plaintiffs want to know who paid and directed Hall while he aided
the Contras inside Nicaragua. In 1986, Hall was caught by the
Sandinista government, which called him mentally unstable and later
kicked him out of the country.
   Hall has acknowledged receiving funds from anticommunist
militant and former Maj. Gen. John K. Singlaub, his boss in
Nicaragua and one of 29 defendants in the suit. The case is set for
trial June 27.
   However, he repeatedly refused to disclose where other funds
came from or who trained and directed him in the use of explosives.
   Asked whom he was protecting, Hall replied ``Singlaub and
above,'' indicating U.S. government officials. But he added his
information, while politically embarrassing, did not involve
illegal acts.
   Hall, who lives in Redington Shores, also said he has
connections with Iran-Contra figure Robert Owen, an assistant to
Oliver North and a defendant in the suit. He said Owen promised him
a presidential pardon for his activities in Nicaragua.
   Singlaub's attorney, Thomas Spencer, also attended the hearing,
and bitterly attacked the Washington-based Christic Institute and
the suit.
   ``This is a completely baseless lawsuit ... that has consumed
hundreds of thousands of dollars, indeed millions of dollars of the
defendants' money,'' he told Turnoff.
   Along with Singlaub and Owen, defendants in the suit include
Theodore Shackley, former deputy director of operations for the
CIA; Contra director Adolfo Calero; Medellin Cartel leaders Pablo
Escobar Gaviria and Jorge Ochoa Vasquez; Iran-Contra figures
Richard Secord and Albert Hakim, and others.
   The suit was filed in May 1986, six months before the
Iran-Contra affair became public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
