<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Wedtech-MeeseMemos 1stLd-Writethru a0536 06-16 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wedtech-Meese Memos, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0536,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allegations In Memos To Meese Parallel Charges Filed Against
Wedtech Rival</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Although many...,' to clarify who allegations
were made against</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Biaggi-Wedtech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army probe that allegedly forced a Wedtech
Corp. rival out of business included accusations echoing those
contained in memos sent to Attorney General Edwin Meese III by a
friend and Wedtech consultant, it was reported today.
   Allegations in memos sent to Meese by Wedtech consultant Robert
Wallach bear a striking similarity to language contained in a
highly critical Army report on the company later issued by the
Army, the Los Angeles Times reported in today's editions.
   However, no link between Meese and the investigation of
Houston-based Garcia Ordnance Corp. has been documented, the
newspaper said.
   Wallach was indicted on charges that he accepted hundreds of
thousands of dollars from Wedtech in an improper attempt to
influence Meese on behalf of the defunct New York defense
contractor. Wallach is scheduled to be tried with two associates
later this year.
   Garcia Ordnance is not mentioned in Wallach's indictment.
   Wedtech received a no-bid, $32-million Army engine contract in
1982 with strong backing from then-Meese aide James E. Jenkins,
according to testimony in federal court earlier this year and at
Senate hearings last fall.
   Although many of the allegations made against Garcia were never
proven, the newspaper reported, its executives were barred from
doing business with the government.
   Because the government was the company's only customer, Garcia
Ordnance was forced out of business when it was barred from
government work, company officers said.
   Attorneys for Meese, a presidential counselor during the time he
received the memos, and Wallach denied any involvement in
triggering the Garcia probe.
   The office of independent counsel James C. McKay, who is
investigating Meese, is aware of the Garcia case but refused to
comment on it, according to the Times.
   Army officials refused to disclose what sparked the probe by its
Criminal Investigation Division that came despite earlier favorable
reports about the company from military procurement officers.
   A dozen Garcia officers were indicted for alleged fraud after
the probe, but 11 were acquitted last year by a presiding judge who
said the case never should have been brought to criminal court.
   Garcia Ordnance President Ronald J.Bolden was convicted of
submitting five false documents to the Army but was cleared of
charges he conspired to defraud the government by substituting iron
for steel in an engine crankshaft.
   Acquitted Garcia executive Bill Parker said Army procurement
officers turned hostile in one month between 1983 and 1984.
   ``The model contractor in December was a bum in January,''
Parker said. ``Why? Because we were jumping up as a competitor to
Wedtech.''
   Garcia became a serious Wedtech competitor in December 1983,
when it was certified as a minority-operated firm eligible for
special government contracts. Wedtech also had the certification.
   Bolden blamed Wedtech and Meese for inspiring the case against
Garcia, saying Army officials told him Meese was aligned with
Wedtech and wanted an end to Garcia's competition.
   The 1981-82 memos from Wallach to Meese that were obtained by
the newspaper reportedly denounced Garcia as an inexperienced
company with insufficient resources to handle large government
contracts.
   And in the Army Criminal Investigation Division report dated
June 1, 1983, the same arguments were made, the newspaper said.
   However, Garcia was highly praised by Army engine specialists at
Ft. Belvoir, Va., in a 1982 report that said the firm was competent
and professional despite being in business only two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
