<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Survey     06-16 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Survey,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Popularity of U.S. And Japan Falling Among South
Koreans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The popularity of the United States among South
Koreans is falling drastically, and an increasing number of South
Koreans have negative feelings toward Japan, an international
survey said today.
   The poll was conducted by South Korea's Dong-A Ilbo daily,
Japan's Asahi Shimbun newspaper and Louis Harris and Associates,
Inc., of the United States.
   It said only 38 percent of the South Koreans polled said they
like the United States, compared with 70 percent four years ago.
   It said 51 percent of the 1,996 respondents in South Korea said
they dislike Japan, up from 39 percent four years ago.
   The number of South Koreans feeling friendly toward Japan fell
from 23 percent in a previous 1984 poll to 14 percent, the survey
said.
   The poll, carried out last month, was the second of its kind and
also queried Americans and Japanese on their perception of South
Korea.
   American opinion on ties with South Korea was split, with 43
percent of the 1,258 respondents saying they believe relations are
going well, while 40 percent answered in the negative.
   Seoul has come under fire from the United States to increase
access to its market to reduce a $10 billion trade imbalance it
registered last year.
   When asked what they most closely associated with their Asian
neighbor, a majority of the 2,292 Japanese respondents cited the
upcoming Olympic Games.
   But 30 percent of the South Koreans said they associate Japan
with its colonization of the Korean peninusula from 1910 to 1945.
   About 48 percent of the South Koreans also said relations with
Tokyo were negative, up 11 percentage points, and only 24 percent
said relations with Japan were positive.
</TEXT>
