<DOCNO> AP880616-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0752EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSWaste     06-16 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Waste,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blood Vials Tainted With AIDS Antibody Found on Beach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two vials of blood found on the New Jersey
shore earlier this month contained the AIDS antibody, the Health
Department said, but it stressed that the samples posed virtually
no risk to swimmers.
   ``There hasn't been any evidence of AIDS contamination with such
samples,'' Thomas Burke, acting health commissioner, said Wednesday.
   The samples, which have been turned over to the attorney
general's office for further investigation, were discovered June 3
or 4, Burke said at a news conference.
   One vial was found on Ortley Beach and the other on the north
side of Island Beach State Park, both in Ocean County. Burke said
officials didn't know how long they had been there.
   Beach patrols discovered five glass tubes, each about 5 inches
long and less than an inch in diameter, containing coagulated
blood, said Burke. Only two were found to have evidence of the AIDS
antibody, he said.
   Presence of the AIDS antibody means the blood came from
individuals who carry the AIDS virus and will probably develop the
fatal disease, said Burke.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome attacks the body's ability
to defend itself against disease.
   ``We do not have a threat of AIDS or AIDS contamination from
these samples,'' said Burke.
   The vials were found at about the same time as some syringes.
Health officials could not determine where the items came from,
except that they probably originated from a clinic or hospital.
   Burke is temporarily replacing Commissioner Dr. Molly J. Coye,
who is in Stockholm, Sweden, for an international AIDS conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
