<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DogDies     06-16 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dog Dies,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dog Dies As Owner Forced Out Of Public Housing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goodboy, an elderly Afghan hound, collapsed and
died in 90-plus degree heat as his 91-year-old owner was forced out
of her public housing home because of rules against pets.
   After a quarter-century in an apartment at Columbia Point, Alice
Stacy, her pet and her belongings were being moved to a new Boston
Housing Authority project in the Mattapan section in the humid heat
Wednesday.
   ``Goodboy never made it inside the house,'' she said. ``I was
sitting inside and I asked where Goodboy was. I went outside, and
he was laid out and he was breathing awfully hard.''
   The long-haired dog was moved to shade and given water, but he
failed to respond. Goodboy was taken to an animal clinic but could
not be revived.
   The dog probably died of a combination of age, heat and the
stress of moving, said Martha C. Armstrong of the Massachusetts
Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Animals.
   Stacy said the dog had been restless the night before the move.
``He was up and down and I didn't sleep, either,'' she added.
   Stacy, who had said she would never give up Goodboy, lost a
six-month fight after the housing authority and CMJ Management Co.
said she had to give away her pet or leave the project. CMJ is
renovating the housing buildings.
   Ironically, Goodboy's death will allow Stacy to return to a unit
at Columbia Point, where she has friends.
   ``I'm going back,'' she said. ``The problem child is returning.''
   Commissioner Diane Payne of the Department of Elderly Affairs
said Stacy would be moved back today to one of the renovated units.
Payne had accompanied the woman and her dog on the one-day move.
   Goodboy's memory may live on. Armstrong has been lobbying the
Massachusetts Legislature for a law to allow pets for residents of
state-financed public housing for seniors. She said she plans to
attach Goodboy's name to the bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
