<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GleasonRemembered     06-16 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gleason Remembered,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bus Depot in Brooklyn to be Named After Jackie Gleason</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Kramden would have been proud.
   The late Jackie Gleason, who played Kramden on ``The
Honeymooners'' and made him probably the best-known bus driver in
history, will be honored with his very own bus depot in Brooklyn.
   The Fifth Avenue depot on 36th Street is to be renamed the
``Jackie Gleason Depot'' on June 30.
   Gleason's widow, Marilyn, plans to attend the ceremony,
according to the Daily News. June Taylor, head of the June Taylor
Dancers who opened the old ``Jackie Gleason Show,'' will accompany
Mrs. Gleason, who is her sister.
   Members of ``The Honeymooners'' cast _ Audrey Meadows, Art
Carney and Joyce Randolph _ have all been invited to attend.
   A new logo is being designed for the depot and will be worn as a
uniform arm patch. The logo will be chosen from among three
finalists submitted by drivers and other employees. The three
resemble the scene shown at the beginning of each episode of ``The
Honeymooners.''
   Sonny Hall, president of the Transport Workers Union Local 100,
says renaming the depot is a great idea.
   ``I think Jackie did a lot for the image of the driver,'' he
said.
   Gleason, an honorary member of the TWU, died last year at the
age of 71.
</TEXT>
