<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0839EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     06-16 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Troops Press Offensive Against Tamil Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian peacekeeping troops cordoned
off a Tamil town in eastern Sri Lanka today and began rounding up
suspected rebels, area residents and diplomatic sources said.
   In India, meanwhile, a newspaper reported that the main Tamil
rebel group in Sri Lanka has agreed in principle to surrender most
of its arms in exchange for the rehabilitation of its fighters.
   Residents of Batticola, 135 miles east of Colombo, said by
telephone that Indian troops had surrounded the adjacent town of
Kallady at about dawn today and had rounded up hundreds of Tamils
for questioning.
   A spokeswoman for the Indian High Commission, or embassy, in
Colombo said only that ``Indian troops are continuing their search
for Tamil Tiger arms and fighters.'' She spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The state-run Daily News today quoted Indian sources as saying
Indian troops captured 21 Tamil rebels Wednesday, including four
guerrilla leaders.
   It said the rebels were arrested during ``white flag protests''
in the northern and eastern provinces, where Tamils predominate.
   Hundreds of Tamil homes were decked with white flags Wednesday
to underscore a demand that India begin negotiations with the
rebels.
   In July, President Junius Jayewardene of Sri Lanka signed an
Indian-sponsored peace accord aimed at ending the Tamils' guerrilla
war.
   But the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest of the
rebel groups, rejected the pact and continued fighting for a
separate homeland.
   The English-language Indian Express today quoted unidentified
Tamil leaders in the southern Indian city of Madras as saying an
agreement was in the works between the Tigers and the Indian
government.
   The Express said the two sides still were negotiating the period
of time over which the rebels would surrender their arms and their
role in restoring peace after five years of guerrilla warfare.
   The story did not specify exactly what is meant by
rehabilitation but the word is generally used to mean helping the
combatants shift from soldiering to more socially useful
occupations.
   The paper said the agreement could be announced as early as
Friday, when Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi visits Madras.
   An Indian official in New Delhi, speaking on condition of
anonymity, told The Associated Press that the report was
speculative, but that Indian officials had been talking with the
Tamil rebels.
   India became involved in the Sri Lankan war because it is the
dominant power in the region and because of the sympathies of its
own 60 million Tamils to the separatist rebels' cause.
   India has sent at least 50,000 troops to Sri Lanka to police the
cease-fire called for in the July agreement, and this force has
inflicted a series of defeats on the rebels in recent weeks.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, comprise 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. They claim discrimination by the
Sinhalese Buddhists, who form 75 percent of the population and
control the government and military.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
