<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NorthernIreland 2ndLd-Writethru   06-16 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0474,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede, BELFAST</HEAD>
<HEAD>IRA Bomb Kills Six Soldiers, Injures 10 Civilians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with IRA statement; quotes from
witnesses, details. No pickup. Adds byline</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBURN, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republican Army vowed
today to wage ``unceasing war'' against Britain after a guerrilla
bomb blew up at a festive foot race packed with people, killing six
soldiers and wounding 10 civilians.
   The IRA's Belfast Brigade claimed responsibility for Wednesday
night's bombing _ the guerrilla group's deadliest attack in seven
months _ in a statement today to news media in Belfast.
   IRA guerrillas slipped into the predominantly Protestant town of
Lisburn, headquarters of the British Army in Northern Ireland, and
wired a bomb containing seven pounds of explosives to an unmarked
army van, the statement said.
   The blue van exploded as six soldiers rode away in it after
taking part in half-marathon of 13 miles that had attracted 4,250
competitors to Lisburn, seven miles southwest of Belfast.
   All six soldiers were killed, bringing this year's death toll
from the province's sectarian violence to 38, eight this week alone.
   Mayor Billy Bleakes said the town was in ``shock and disbelief
that any human being could do this to other human beings.''
   None of the civilians, including an 80-year-old man and a
2-year-old boy, suffered serious injuries, police said.
   Valerie Fleming, 28, who lives nearby, said the town ``was
packed with people ... They were running about screaming. There
were children and families. They were terrified.''
   The death toll was the highest since an IRA bombing at a war
memorial ceremony in Enniskillen on Nov. 8. The IRA said that bomb
was meant to kill soldiers but accidentally massacred 11 Protestant
civilians.
   The explosion occurred as the van moved through the town center,
which was thronged with runners and spectators leaving the charity
run.
   Nigel Sands, 19, who was two cars behind the van, said he saw
smoke, then heard a loud explosion ``and I saw two bodies lying in
the middle of the road. One of them had no legs, and one of them
was burning. It as badly mutilated. It seems they were blown from
the van. There was panic and people were running everywhere.''
   Although police said they received no warning before the blast,
the IRA said: ``Every care was exercised by our volunteers to
ensure the minimum risk to the local population.
   The statement said the British presence in Northern Ireland
oppressed the Irish people, adding:
   ``Until that presence is removed and the Irish people as a unit
can exercise our right to national self-determination, the Irish
Republican Army will continue to wage unceasing war against the
British Crown Forces and the British colonial presence.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's representative in the
province, Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, toured the bomb
scene today and told reporters later the attack revealed the
``vileness of terrorism which we have to face.''
   King said, however, that the security forces had not taken
adequate security precautions to prevent the bombing.
   British soldiers and police are the main targets of the IRA in
its nearly 20-year war to oust the British from Northern Ireland
and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the mainly Roman
Catholic Irish Republic.
   Police on today cordoned the area where the bomb went off.
Townspeople gathered in clusters by ribbon barrier, gazing in
silence at the van's gutted hulk.
   Belfast's Irish News, the province's main Catholic newspaper,
said the IRA had opened ``another blood-stained chapter in their
perverted history ... The result of their savagery will only be to
harden hearts and block progress towards an eventual solution.''
   It was the army's worst blow since a 1982 bombing in a pub near
Londonderry killed 11 soldiers and six civilians. An IRA offshoot,
the Irish National Liberation Army, claimed responsibility for that
attack.
</TEXT>
