<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Opera-SwaggartAds     06-16 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Opera-Swaggart Ads,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cincinnati Opera Ads Use Jimmy Swaggart Clip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Swaggart's got a copyright on his
confession and his organization is not taking it lightly that the
Cincinnati Opera is promoting a production by using the minister's
public admission of sin.
   The radio commercial began airing today, opera officials said.
It promotes the opera company's June 30 and July 2 performances of
Carlisle Floyd's 1956 opera ``Susannah,'' in which an isolated
young woman is seduced by a hypocritical, backwoods Tennessee
preacher.
   In the commercial, the voice of Swaggart is heard to say: ``I do
not plan in any way to whitewash my sin. I have no one but myself
to blame.''
   Swaggart, a Louisiana-based television preacher, made the
statement during a February speech to his congregation. He never
specified the sin, but he was reported to have met several times
with a prostitute at a New Orleans motel to watch her perform
sexual acts. He has not denied those reports.
   ``We're looking into this to see if there's a violation of our
copyrights,'' said William Treeby, a New Orleans attorney who is a
board member of the Jimmy Swaggart Ministries.
   ``We are not going to comment further, just examine it from a
legal standpoint. They don't have the right to use material that
we've copyrighted.''
   He said the ministries have copyrighted the Swaggart confession.
   A 10-second television spot produced for the opera company
re-enacts a scene from the opera in which Susannah, with her back
to the camera, bathes nude in a creek, while an announcer says,
``Susannah takes it off, and the elders can't bear it.''
   Patricia Beggs, Cincinnati Opera marketing director, said the
hint of sexual scandal was a natural in marketing the opera.
   ``This is so topical it's unbelievable, with Jimmy Swaggart,
Jessica Hahn, Jim and Tammy Bakker,'' Ms. Beggs said. ``It was sort
of a connection everybody was drawing.''
   The company hopes the advertisements will amuse and not offend,
she said.
   ``We certainly didn't do it with any malicious intent. We just
want to bring opera into range of focus of people's experiences,''
Ms. Beggs said.
   The radio advertisement, which was produced by Lawler Ballard
Advertising, used the clip from Swaggart's Feb. 21 public
confession, then followed it with the voice of announcer Gary
Stephenson saying: ``Lustful evangelists have gotten a lot of
publicity lately. But if you want to see the most lustful
evangelist of all, come watch the Rev. Olin Blitch try to convert
the beautiful but innocent Susannah to a life of sin and
degradation in Carlisle Floyd's all-American opera `Susannah' ...
probably the only great opera ever written that takes place in
Tennessee.''
</TEXT>
