<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Election 3rdLd-Writethru   06-16 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Election, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0528,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliamentary Election Tests Power of Gandhi Rival</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with voting postponed at one
polling station after alleged vote-rigging; identifies wounded
legislator. Picks up 7th pvs, ``Singh, running...''
^By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLAHABAD, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One person was killed and several others
were injured today during a parliamentary election that will test
the power of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's main challenger.
   Election officials later postponed voting at one polling station
after allegations that loyalists of Gandhi's Congress Party tried
to rig ballots.
   The contest for a seat in the lower house of Parliament pitted
former Defense Minister V.P. Singh, a Gandhi ally-turned-foe,
against singer and film writer Sunil Shastri, of the governing
Congress Party.
   The battle between Singh, 56, and Shastri, 38, has been watched
closely as a measure of how Singh would do in a national contest
against Gandhi.
   The polling booth in the Satpura area of Allahabad did not open
today because of irregularities, election officials said. Balloting
was rescheduled for Friday. Officials gave no details.
   But Chander Amrit, a member of Singh's Jan Morcha political
group, said 15 armed men had raided the Satpura polling booth and
marked 800 ballots, most of them for the Congress Party candidate.
   One of Singh's supporters was shot and injured in a clash in the
village of Naini, 10 miles south of Allahabad, election authorities
said. He was identified as Narendra Pal Singh, a member of the
state assembly. He is not related to the candidate.
   In neighboring Haryana state, one person was killed and several
injured in clashes among factions at three villages, the Press
Trust of India reported. No details were available.
   Singh, running as an independent with the backing of most of
India's major opposition parties, was among the first to cast his
vote in Allahabad, 360 miles southeast of New Delhi.
   ``I voted for myself,'' he said. ``Who else is there?''
   Shastri was not eligible to vote because he is registered in his
home city of Gorakhpur, 120 miles northeast of Allahabad.
   More than 6.5 million voters in eight states were eligible to
vote in off-year elections for seven Parliament and 11 state
assembly seats.
   Lines formed outside the voting centers long before they opened
at 7:30 a.m. Polls were to close at 4:30 p.m., and final results
were expected late Friday or Saturday.
   Singh broke with the prime minister last year over the
government's hesitation to investigate alleged kickbacks in defense
contracts.
   Opposition parties and the press have alleged that government
officials and Gandhi cronies received kickbacks to facilitate the
purchase of Bofors artillery guns from Sweden and West German
submarines. Gandhi and his party have denied the charges.
   The Allahabad Parliament seat became vacant when film star
Agitabh Bachchan, a close friend of Gandhi, was forced to resign
because of allegations his brother may have been a conduit for
kickbacks. The Bachchan brothers have denied any wrongdoing.
   Shastri is the son of popular late Prime Minister Lal Bahadur
Shastri.
   Singh and Shastri are just two of the 68 candidates for the
Parliament seat, but only one other candidate, Kanshi Ram, is
considered a serious contender.
   Ram has championed the causes of the lower castes.
</TEXT>
