<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1002EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mayors-Holland     06-16 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mayors-Holland,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Mayor Becomes President Of U.S. Mayors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top priority of the U.S. Conference of
Mayors will be to convince the presidential candidates that cities
need help, especially in the fight against drugs, the
organization's new president said.
   Mayor Arthur Holland of Trenton, N.J., was installed Wednesday
as the 45th president of the organization during the closing
session of its annual meeting.
   Holland, who succeeds Mayor Richard L. Berkley of Kansas City in
the two-year post, said Republican George Bush may have erred in
being the only presidential nominee to snub an invitation to
address the gathering.
   Michael Dukakis spoke to the mayors on Sunday and Jesse Jackson
appeared on Tuesday.
   Bush said a scheduling conflict prevented him from coming to
Salt Lake City, but he sent a detailed letter addressing the needs
of cities, Holland said.
   ``If I were Bush, I would want to be here, and not having been
here, I would want to talk to as many mayors as possible,'' said
Holland, a Democrat.
   Of the problems facing cities, the most serious is the use of
illicit drugs and the crime it spawns, Holland said during a news
conference.
   ``Number one is drugs. The problem of crack is overwhelming
us,'' Holland said.
   ``Almost all of our crime is drug-related,'' in Trenton, he
said. ``We simply don't have the resources to fight this.''
   Holland said the conference sent a telegram to Congress on
Wednesday asking for an amendment that would allow federal
anti-crime funds to be sent directly to cities for use in the war
on drugs.
   ``We haven't acted as though we are at war, and we must if we
are to conquer that which is conquering us,'' he said.
   After drugs, cities need federal help for mass transit, housing
and job training, said Holland.
   Mayor Joe Riley of Charleston, S.C., whose city will host next
year's annual meeting, said aid to cities has dropped sharply in
recent years. Riley said Urban Development Action Grants have been
reduced from a high of about $750 million in 1980 to $216 million
last year.
   However, the mayors didn't blame the Reagan administration.
   ``I fault the Congress,'' said Holland.
   Mayors attending the conference hailed Holland as a creative
urban leader and articulate spokesman for the nation's cities.
   Holland was elected mayor of Trenton in 1959 after serving on
the city commission. He was defeated in 1966, but reclaimed the
office in 1970 and has held it since then.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
