<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 4thLd-Writethru a0545 06-16 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0545,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldier Shot And Wounded in Nablus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 4th, `Also today...' to UPDATE with
Herzog comments; picks up 5th pvs: The reserve...; ADDS two grafs;
deletes outdated material and minor editing throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli soldier was shot
and slightly wounded in Nablus today, and troops rounded up
Palestinian suspects and clamped a curfew on the occupied West
Bank's largest city, the army said.
   It was the first instance of a soldier being shot since Sgt.
Moshe Katz, 28, was killed in the West Bank town of Bethlehem on
March 20.
   An Arab witness said the suspects were made to stand on one foot
while being questioned.
   Also today, dozens of Jewish settlers, some donning prayer
shawls, blocked a major West Bank highway for two hours to demand
harsh army action against Palestinian firebombers.
   And, President Chaim Herzog sharply criticized foreign news
media, blaming subconscious anti-Semitic motives for the
publication of ``half-truths and occasionally even worse than
blatant lies'' about Israel.
   The reserve soldier was traveling in his own car when he was hit
by a bullet, an army spokesman said. He added that it was not
immmediately known if the soldier was in uniform.
   The wounded soldier was taken by helicopter to a Tel Aviv
hospital and ``the circumstances of the injury are being
investigated,'' the spokesman said, refusing to elaborate.
   Troops began an immediate search for Arab suspects and the
weapon inside Nablus, 40 miles north of Jerusalem, according to
security sources. They spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Following the shooting, all drivers except Jewish settlers who
live nearby were stopped from entering or leaving Nablus. A United
Nations vehicle as well as one belonging to the Red Cross were
turned back.
   Some four hours after the shooting, about 60 cars were lined up
outside Nablus and an equal number were queued inside the city
waiting to pass a roadblock manned by three jeeploads of troops. A
helicopter hovered overhead.
   Arab witnesses said troops rounded up dozens of Palestinians and
fired shots in the air.
   ``It seems the army is very angry because this is the first time
I've seen them this strict. They are shooting in the air like
crazy,'' said Nablus businessman Said Kenaan.
   Abu Islam Deedi, an Arab reporter who lives in Nablus, said the
army set up about 10 roadblocks in the city center, rounded up
about 50 suspects and made them stand on one leg against a wall.
   Deedi, who said he could see the roundup from a window in his
home, said soldiers blocked all entrances to the city and stopped
and searched cars. He said several busloads of troops patrolled the
streets.
   Several Palestinians in Nablus said by telephone that they
became aware of trouble only when they heard Israeli troops telling
them over loudspeakers to stay indoors.
   ``A curfew is being imposed until further notice,'' the troops
said in Arabic. The blared order could be heard over the telephone
line.
   Since anti-occupation unrest began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, 208 Arabs have been killed. Two Israelis also have died.
   Palestinians have stepped up firebomb attacks, and PLO-linked
leaders of the Arab uprising have ordered them to stock up on food,
first aid and gasoline to prolong their resistance to Israel's
21-year occupation.
   About 60 settlers from the occupied West Bank's settlement of
Efrat used their cars to block the major Jerusalem-Hebron highway,
the route to jobs in Israel for thousands of Arab workers, Israel
radio reported.
   The army responded to the increase in firebomb attacks with
orders this week to shoot firebombers.
   Herzog, the former army intelligence chief, said world leaders
made decisions about Israel based on television newscasts which he
said contained ``a considerable degree of bias.''
   The 30-minute speech during a conference on Israel and the media
at Hebrew University in Jerusalem was Herzog's most critical
attack, but not his first, on the media. It underscored rising
Israeli criticism of foreign journalists triggered by wide coverage
of the violence.
</TEXT>
