<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OffshoreDrilling     06-16 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Offshore Drilling,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interior Delaying New England, Florida Offshore Leases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Department will delay offering
oil and gas leases in federal waters off New England and Florida to
try to meet objections of the states involved, the department
announced today.
   It was the second time in two weeks that the department
announced postponements to try to settle controversies over its
drilling plans. Last week, a controversial sale off northern
California was delayed from February to at least October.
   Today's actions preceded scheduled deliberations by the House
Appropriations Committee on putting drilling prohibitions into the
department's appropriations bill for the fiscal year beginning Oct.
1. A subcommittee approved the bans last week.
   Spokesman Bob Walker said Secretary Donald Hodel had written the
committee explaining the delays in an attempt to keep it from
enacting drilling bans in an appropriations bill, as it has done
several times before.
   The New England offering had been scheduled for February and now
will be delayed at least six months, Walker said.
   This delay will enable the department to put together a
negotiating committee with governors of the coastal New England
states. ``We think we have made some progress'' in forming such a
group to try to reach a compromise, Walker said.
   In an attempt to protect the shallow Georges Bank fishing
grounds, the subcommittee provision would forbid drilling in waters
less than 400 meters deep (1,312 feet). Walker said this would
``leave only the marginal areas'' available for leasing and ``might
leave us without a sale,'' as happened once before when no one bid
on areas left out of a previous prohibition.
   The Florida postponement involved 14 million acres in the
eastern Gulf of Mexico north of the Florida Keys up to about Naples.
   The area will be dropped from a scheduled offering of tracts in
the eastern gulf scheduled for November and will be offered
separately. The department announced no schedule for that second
offering. The governor's office in Tallahassee said under today's
agreement it could not occur before next May.
   In the meantime, two 14-member federal-state committees will
study oil spills and cleanup in the gulf.
   The subcommittee measure would forbid drilling in a slightly
larger area, about 16 million acres.
   It was the second deletion of substantial acreage off Florida in
an attempt to satisfy the state. Hodel ruled the areas around the
keys off limits in March.
   The subcommittee proposal also called for delaying the northern
California offering until October, in effect putting Hodel's delay
into law.
</TEXT>
