<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1146EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SentencingGuidelines     06-16 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sentencing Guidelines,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Florida Federal Judges Strike Down U.S. Sentencing
Guidelines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision by federal judges in southern Florida to
discard federal sentencing guidelines as unconstitutional has been
hailed by defense lawyers as bringing humanity back to the
courtroom.
   ``The guidelines were barbaric,'' said West Palm Beach lawyer
Richard Lubin, an area director of the National Association of
Criminal Defense Lawyers. ``They turned the judges into
automatons.''
   Defense attorneys had argued the guidelines did not give judges
enough discretion in sentencing.
   Wednesday's 85-page opinion resulted from a rare ``en banc''
hearing of the Southern District of Florida's 16 federal judges,
held April 21.
   ``It's a very thorough and well-reasoned decision,'' said Benson
Weintraub, a Miami lawyer who spearheaded the arguments against the
guidelines.
   U.S. District Judge Norman Roettger, whose courtroom is in Fort
Lauderdale, said he didn't think the change would result in widely
different sentences.
   ``We'll just sentence on the old policy, that's all,'' Roettger
said. ``We have been sentencing as we have been for decades. All
we're doing is continuing that.''
   The guidelines were established by the seven-member U.S.
Sentencing Commission, set up by the 1984 Comprehensive Crime
Control Act, and applied to any offense comitted after Nov. 1, 1987.
   Written by U.S. District Judge Stanley Marcus, the 12-4 opinion
finds the guidelines unconstitutional primarily because of the
composition of the sentencing commission.
   Because the commission includes three federal judges, the
separation of powers outlined in the U.S. Constitution is violated,
the judges said. Fixing punishments belongs to the legislative
branch of government and cannot be established by judges, the
opinion said.
   ``This collaborative rule-making effort between the judicial and
the executive branches of government cast too long a shadow over
the independence and impartiality of the entire federal
judiciary,'' Marcus wrote.
   ``We conclude that the act is unconstitutional, and until we
receive contrary guidance from a higher authority, the guidelines
will not be applied in this district.''
   Under the decision, those who are awaiting sentencing for
convictions or guilty pleas will be dealt with under the old
guidelines.
   Richard Gregorie, the chief criminal prosecutor in South
Florida's U.S. Attorney's Office, said the Justice Department will
ask that the guidelines remain in force while the decision is
appealed.
   Similar hearings have been held around the country with
conflicting opinions on the generally stricter sentencing
guidelines included in the 1984 Comprehensive Crime Control Act.
   On Monday the U.S. Supreme Court agreed to step into the
dispute, and a decision by the high court is expected by early next
year, said John Steer, general counsel to the sentencing commission
in Washington.
   The guidelines allow sentencing judges to take into account the
nature of the crime, the grade of the offense, the amount of harm
caused, the community's view of the crime and the sentence's
deterrent value.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
