<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GriscomReplacement     06-16 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Griscom Replacement,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Campaign Press Secretary to Become White House Communications
Director</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mari Maseng, the press secretary to Sen. Bob
Dole's unsuccessful campaign for the presidency, will replace Tom
Griscom as White House director of communications and planning, it
was announced today.
   Griscom will leave the White House on June 30, returning to
private life after 16 months of service.
   His job was to oversee the speechwriting staff, draw up
long-range agendas for the president and plan special events, such
as the superpower summits last December in Washington and earlier
this month in Moscow.
   Ms. Maseng served in the Reagan White House previously on two
occasions. She was a member of the speechwriting staff from 1981
until 1983, when she became assistant secretary of transportation
for public affairs.
   Ms. Maseng returned to the White House in 1986 as director of
the Office of Public Liaison, maintaining contact with
constituencies such as women, minorities, anti-abortion groups and
others.
   She left the White House to serve on Dole's staff as his press
secretary until his withdrawal from the race earlier this year.
</TEXT>
