<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: graduation qualities.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 13
   The Kansas City (Mo.) Times on drinking and driving:
   One of the best reasons to periodically pause to take stock of
accomplishments in the crusade against drunken driving is that
things may be going better than they seem.
   For all the tragedy continuing as a result of alcohol-related
crashes, and the 20,000 deaths annually, there's been progress.
   Just to start, the death toll is no longer rising substantially
every year. Public awareness has been stirred by victim advocate
groups. ...
   Many states have passed tougher laws the past decade. They're
raised the legal age for consumption of alcohol.
   Possibly as a result of these persistent methods of chipping
away at casual public attitudes, arrests are way up.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 9
   The Los Angeles Herald Examiner on Jesse Jackson:
   Also-rans in the presidential primary marathon often are as
quickly forgotten as Super Bowl losers. Jesse Jackon, as in so many
other ways, is different.
   Michael Dukakis' victories, including his triumph in California,
made it certain that Jackson won't get the Democratic prsidential
nomination in 1988. But a loser? Not a chance.
   No, when the political history of this era is written, Jackson
will have a lead role, even if he accomplishes nothing more than he
did on the campaign trail in 1988. ...
   No one has brought more people into the process _ people who had
long since given up believing that their voices would be heard _
than Jackson. ...
   With charisma and hard work, Jackson has paved the way for a
black president, not this year, but in the near future. ...
   Although he's had little luck attracting many Democratic leaders
who will be attending the Atlanta convention as super-delegates,
Jackson is liable to be more successful in helping mold the 1988
Democratic platform.
   But after all which has come before, that will be a minor
triumph.
   Platforms are filed and forgotten. Jackson's already left a more
lasting mark _ on the history books.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 11
   The Duluth (Minn.) News-Tribune on the death penalty:
   It has a nice sound to it: Drug dealers who kill people must die
themselves.
   Who among us can condone the actions of drug dealers, especially
those who've been convicted of killing someone. After all, the
drugs they deal often kill users even if the peddlers don't
actually do the killing.
   But voting to impose the death penalty on drug-murders offers
more sound _ and fury _ than enlightened law enforcement. Thus
we're unimpressed with the U.S. Senate vote (June 10) and hope more
rational minds in the House will block the action. ...
   Under the bill, the death penalty could be invoked if someone is
convicted of violating federal drug laws and separately convicted
of killing a police officer or private citizen.
   Arguments on the merits of a death penalty aside, we're
persuaded by Sen. Lowell Weicker, R-Conn., who said if senators are
serious about fighting drugs they should vote to spend more money
on educating potential users and arresting those who deal in drugs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 10
   The Daily Oklahoman, Oklahoma City, on the Iran-Contra trials:
   Eager to conducts its own investigation of the Iran-Contra
affair, Congress last year granted immunity from prosecution to
several witnesses in exchange for their testimony.
   Now the chickens are coming home to roost in the courtroom of
U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell.
   He has ordered separate trials for former White House aide
Oliver North and three other defendants _ a serious blow to the
strategy of independent counsel Lawrence Walsh. ...
   Because of the legal complications incurred by the grants of
immunity and questions over use of classified information in a
public trial, the judge has hinted that the charges might have to
be dismissed.
   That wouldn't be a bad idea.
</TEXT>
