<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0795</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: bad idea.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 11
   Sioux Falls (S.D.) Argus Leader on House ethics:
   Democratic members of Congress frequently criticize the dealings
of Attorney General Edwin Meese and other members of President
Reagan's Republican administration.
   Now, members of the Democratic majority in the House find
themselves in the embarrassing position of having to defend their
leader, Speaker Jim Wright of Texas.
   Wright has denied any wrongdoing. At best, however, some of his
actions appear highly questionable.
   A thorough investigation of those activities is not only
appropriate but a matter of congressional duty.
   Congress has demanded repeatedly that members of President
Reagan's team avoid even the appearance of impropriety. Congress
must hold its own members to that same high standard.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 13
   The Westerly (R.I.) Sun on Soviet dissidents:
   The remarkable thing was not so much what Andrei Sakharov said,
though he spoke well as a leading champion of human rights in the
Soviet Union.
   Nor was the fact that the world-renowned dissident was speaking
on matters of this kind in public so very remarkable in itself; he
has made his views before.
   What was most noteworthy about the occasion was its setting and
its auspices.
   Dr. Sakharov, with the evident blessing of the Kremlin, spoke in
the very Moscow auditorium where two days earlier Mikhail Gorbachev
had held a post-summit news conference.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 11
   The Lafayette (Ind.) Journal and Courier on the drought:
   Nothing is as humbling as coming face to face with the fact that
despite all of our technology, we remain at the mercy of the
natural elements.
   All forms of natural disasters remind us of this: hurricanes,
earthquakes, tornadoes and flood.
   As we look around the Midwest, we see unfolding yet another of
nature's leveling influences. What started as a troublesome dry
spell in May has met or surpassed the pessimism of those who early
on predicted the worst drought since the Dust Bowl days. ...
   As we wait and pray for rain, let's not focus only on the bad
that the drought produces but the good as well.
   There is the breaking down of barriers between segments of the
community. There is the inward reflection on an individual basis
that promotes personal growth.
   While we all await the miracle of rain, let's remain in tune
with the other miracles that continue to occur each day. The tough
times will be over before we know it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 9
   Portland (Maine) Press Herald on acid rain cleanup:
   The details of an acid rain plan worked out by the governors of
New York and Ohio are less imnportant than the fact that an
agreement has been worked out at all.
   For Ohio to agree to any significant cleanup proposal at all is
a significant breakthrough, since coal-fired plants and other
industries there emit more sulfur dioxide than any other state in
the nation. ...
   Under the New York-Ohio plan, the federal government would put
up $900 million a year in cleanup funds (most of it to come from an
oil import fee) and $900 million would come from the polluters. ...
   Maine's Sen. George J. Mitchell, who has been leading the fight
for comprehensive acid rain legislation for years, calls the New
York-Ohio agreement ``encouraging.''
   Mitchell predicts it will pave the way for enactment of an acid
rain bill this year. If so, that's progress indeed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 10
   The Asbury Park (N.J.) Press on Reagan's slur of native
Americans:
   During a give-and-take session ... at Moscow University, one
student challenged (President Reagan) to address American Indian
grievances.
   (Reagan) proceeded to tick off all the wonderful things European
immigrants and their descendants have done for the Indian:
Reservations covering millions of acres, a Bureau of Indian
Affairs, education, a chance for some to get very rich pumping oil.
   The president's history lesson left out the broken treaties, the
forced expulsions, the outright theft of property, the loss of a
whole continent and the lingering legacy of disease, poverty and
joblessness.
   Nor could Reagan's myth of America as a shining city on a hill
acknowledge the Trail of Tears, in which 70,000 Indians died as
they were thrown off their lands and pushed across the Mississippi
River.
   The Soviet occupation of the nations of Eastern Europe, the
Baltic and Eurasia has had ghastly consequences. But there has been
little benign about the European occupation of land that belongs to
native Americans.
   Reagan's decision to dwell on the former while suppressing the
latter discredits his message.
</TEXT>
