<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Bhopal     06-16 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Bhopal,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Union Carbide's Request To Dismiss Himself From
Bhopal Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district judge today rejected a request
by Union Carbide Corp. that he remove himself from the Bhopal gas
disaster case because he showed bias against the company.
   ``Such a procedure is unheard of in trial courts in this
country, where the normal course is to approach the high court for
transfer of the suit,'' Judge M.W. Deo said.
   Union Carbide's lawyers on May 6 asked Deo to remove himself
from hearing India's $3 billion suit against the U.S.-based
multinational company. They said that Deo's order on Dec. 17 for
Union Carbide to pay ``interim relief'' to the gas victims showed
bias because he had not ruled on the merits of the case.
   Nearly 3,000 people were killed and at least 20,000 people were
seriously injured when toxic methyl-isocyanate leaked from a
pesticide-producing subsidiary of Union Carbide in Bhopal on Dec.
3, 1984.
   The Indian government is suing for damages in the gas leak, the
world's worst industrial accident.
   India has accused Union Carbide of negligence. Union Carbide
contends the accident was caused by sabotage.
   Deo set June 29 as the next date for a hearing on the damage
suit.
   Deo's December order was upheld in April by the Madhya Pradesh
High Court, which set the amount of payment at $192 million.
   Today, UnionCarbide attorney Fali Nariman argued that the order
for relief payments was made ``without any finding of liability and
without there being any material at all to indicate how the figure
... was arrived at.''
   He added that there was nothing in the order to allow refund of
the relief payments should the government lose the suit or final
adjudication set a lower liability figure.
   Bhopal is the capital of the central Indian state of Madhya
Pradesh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Norway-Tourists     06-16 0141</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Norway-Tourists,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Underground Tourist Center Opens In Norway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norway has opened a $15.5 million tourist
center chiseled into North Cape, the steep and barren cliff on the
top of Europe.
   On the rare days when the fog lifts, the center in the
1,000-foot-tall cliff on Mageroey island offers a panoramic view of
the midnight sun over the Barents Sea through an 860 square foot
window.
   The center also offers an audio-visual presentation on northern
Norway, a 250-seat restaurant and the world's northernmost bar. On
the clifftop is a domed telecommunications center.
   North Cape attracts about 100,000 tourists during the summer.
   After nearby Knivskjellodden, North Cape is Europe's
northernmost point.
   The cape was named in 1553 by Richard Chancellor, a British
navigator who two years later was lost in a shipwreck off the coast
of Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
