<DOCNO> AP880616-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1242EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HoldupHero     06-16 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holdup Hero,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Good Turn Deserved Another, `Hero' Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who foiled a bank holdup says he
hoped he'd impress the two police officers who took him under their
wing when as a teen-age gang member he witnessed a fatal shooting.
   ``I was hoping those guys would be proud of me,'' said Jim
Sperow, 25, who on Wednesday was called a hero by police.
   Sperow chased a suspected Wells Fargo Bank robber down the
street, tackled him in an alley and bashed his head with the man's
.44-caliber Magnum revolver. ``Those two cops straigtened me out
and got me on the right track,'' Sperow said after Tuesday's
incident. ``I was just glad I could do something to try to pay them
back.''
   Homicide inspector John Fotinos, one of the two officers, said
he was heartened to learn what Sperow had done, 11 years after
Fotinos and his partner tried to help him out.
   ``You tend to lose track of these kids, so it's great to learn
now that maybe we did a little bit of good,'' he said.
   Sperow's tackle of one suspect and description of another
resulted in the arrest of the two men and the recovery of $52,527,
police said.
   Michael Jameson, the arresting officer, was one of several
policemen who praised Sperow for his bravery.
   Sperow, who works at a print shop, was at the bank, waiting in
line, ``when when a guy jumped over the counter yelling: `It's a
holdup! It's a holdup!''' he said. ``I said to myself, `Wow! Here
we go.'''
   He, the other customers and the tellers watched as one suspect,
identified by police as Robert Michael Linsey, 41, of San Martin,
scooped money from cash drawers into a bag.
   The other suspect, later identified by police as Joe Dewayne
Duke, 41, stood by the door brandishing a revolver.
   Sperow took off after the men when they fled. He tackled Duke
and brought him to the ground, he said.
   ``I figured it was better to go for the guy with the gun. If I
went for the guy with the money I might have gotten shot,'' he said.
   A crowd gathered but nobody offered to help. Sperow managed to
get the gun away from the suspect, then hit him in the head with
the revolver.
   Police pulled up shortly afterward. About four hours later,
police arrested Linsey.
   Later, Sperow, who has a wife and 1{-year-old daughter, recalled
his days as a member of the Hunters Point gang. ``I was a punk,
someone who was on the wrong track,'' he said.
   At 14, he witnessed a drugstore robbery in which a guard was
shot dead.
   The two homicide investigators, Fotinos and Carl Klotz, got
Sperow into the John O'Connell School of Technology, where he has
earned his degree.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1242EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Restaurants     06-16 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Restaurants,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservation Chic: Eateries Serve Water on Request Only</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This is one in an ongoing series of stories about the effects
of the 1988 drought on the nation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Call it conservation chic: The latest trend
in California cusine is the waterless meal.
   There's more than civic spirit at work, however. In Los Angeles,
an ordinance that took effect at the end of April requires
restaurants to serve water on request only. But even outside city
limits, many restaurateurs are voluntarily turning off the tap.
   ``You think about it because of the fires,'' said Donna Averna,
manager of Splash, a bistro in the seaside celebrity community of
Malibu, where drought also brings the threat of devastating brush
fires.
   Posh celebrity hangout Spago in West Hollywood is voluntarily
dry, as are the Brown Derby in Pasadena and Chasen's in West
Hollywood, an old favorite of Ronald and Nancy Reagan.
   The conservation effort gets a boost this week, as the region's
biggest water supplier mails out 200,000 cards to more than 2,000
restaurants to post on tables, outlining the water-on-demand policy.
   The cards bear a picture of a water glass, one-quarter full, and
the caption, ``What, no water?'' On the back is an explanation that
for each serving of water, it takes three to four times that amount
to wash the glass.
   That's a small but important bit of conservation, with rain and
snow runoff in the Sierra Nevada, source of much of the state's
water, at one-half or less of normal levels, said Metropolitan
Water District spokesman Tim Skrove.
   The MWD, wholesale supplier to water districts serving 14
million people throughout Southern California, paid the $13,000 for
printing and mailing the restaurant cards, Skrove said.
   The California Restaurant Association supplied the mailing list
and is urging members to comply, said Stan Kyker, executive vice
president.
   The benefits of pulling water glasses off the tables, Kyker
tells members, are twofold. Not only do they save water and set an
example, they also save money by washing fewer dishes.
   ``It's your obligation to do your role,'' Kyker tells
restaurateurs, ``and besides that, it'll save you money.''
   The initial response has been good.
   Diners don't usually complain once they find they can get water
by asking, said Ms. Averna and Harry McCague, general manager at
the Brown Derby.
   But conservation chic isn't for everyone.
   Stylish Le Dome in West Hollywood wouldn't dream of asking its
patrons to sacrifice.
   Manager Michelle Ritz puts it simply but firmly: ``We always
serve water, sir.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
