<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech 1stLd-Writethru a0519 06-16 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Wedtech Prez: We Met Bush, Hoped to Eliminate Competitors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Guariglia told ...,' with 5 grafs to include
material from a0536, PM-Wedtech-Meese Memos.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ex-Wedtech president testified that company
officials met with George Bush in an effort to cut out competitors
for government contracts, but a Bush spokesman said the vice
president doesn't remember meeting them.
   Anthony Guariglia, the former president of the now-defunct
defense contractor, also testified in Rep. Mario Biaggi's
racketeering trial that Wedtech officials gave $200,000 to
President Reagan's 1984 campaign.
   Meanwhile, the Los Angeles Times reported today that allegations
against a Wedtech competitor contained in memos to Attorney General
Edwin Meese III by a friend, Wedtech consultant Robert Wallach,
bear a striking similarity to language contained in a highly
critical report on the company later issued by the Army.
   However, no link between Meese and the investigation of
Houston-based Garcia Ordnance Corp. has been documented, the
newspaper said.
   Wallach was indicted on charges that he accepted hundreds of
thousands of dollars from Wedtech in an improper attempt to
influence Meese on behalf of the defunct New York defense
contractor. Wallach is scheduled to be tried with two associates
later this year.
   Garcia Ordnance is not mentioned in Wallach's indictment.
   In his testimony in federal court, Guariglia said that
competitors from Texas and Puerto Rico disappeared after the
company officials were introduced to Bush.
   ``Was the purpose of being introduced to Vice President Bush to
get him to eliminate Wedtech's competition in Texas and Puerto
Rico?'' defense attorney Alan R. Kaufman asked during cross
examination.
   ``Yes,'' said Guariglia.
   ``Was that done? Was that competition eliminated?'' Kaufman
asked.
   ``Yes,'' responded Guariglia, ending the exchange without
specifically connecting Bush to the diminished competition.
   Bush spokesman Stephen Hart said, ``The vice president doesn't
recall meeting (Guariglia) on any occasion. And if he spoke to him,
no action was taken up to follow up on their conversation.''
   Guariglia made his statements during cross-examination late
Tuesday by Kaufman, who continued his questioning of the company
official on Wednesday.
   On trial are Biaggi, D-N.Y., and six co-defendants accused of
converting Wedtech into a racketeering enterprise for the payment
of bribes to obtain millions of dollars in no-bid contracts.
   According to Guariglia, another Wedtech official, Mario Moreno,
told him that New York state Republican Chairman George Clark
offered to help the company acquire a lucrative government bridge
pontoon contract in return for a $200,000 campaign contribution.
   ``Was the money paid?'' asked Kaufman, representing defendant
Ronald Betso.
   ``The monies were collected from various vendors, members of the
team, myself. All the officers of Wedtech made contributions to
Ronald Reagan totaling $200,000,'' Guariglia said.
   ``Was it money well spent?'' continued Kaufman.
   ``I do not know,'' replied Guariglia, the fourth and last
official of the South Bronx firm scheduled to testify. Moreno
testified earlier in the trial for the prosecution.
   Guariglia, in his fifth day of cross-examination, then testified
that Clark introduced him and several other Wedtech people to Bush.
   Clark, in a telephone call from Newport, R.I., said Wednesday
he'd never even met Guariglia: ``I wouldn't now him if he walked
past me now.'' As for the witness' charges, Clark said, ``I
absolutely, categorically deny doing anything on their behalf or
having any conversation about $200,000.''
   Defense lawyers are trying to demonstrate Wedtech's government
contracts were the result of its many Washington connections and
not its ties with the defendants.
   Toward that end, an assortment of names connected with the
Reagan administration, including Attorney General Edwin Meese III,
former adviser Lyn Nofziger and ex-National Security Adviser Robert
McFarlane, have surfaced during the 14-week trial.
   The defendants are Biaggi, his son Richard, and the others _
Wedtech founder John Mariotta, ex-Bronx Borough President Stanley
Simon, attorney Bernard Ehrlich, Small Business Administration
Regional Administrator Peter Neglia and Neglia friend Betso.
   Guariglia and three other Wedtech officials have pleaded guilty
to corruption charges and agreed to testify at the Biaggi trial in
exchange for leniency. Guariglia, 37, testified he could still
receive a 10-year prison term despite his testimony.
</TEXT>
