<DOCNO> AP880616-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1247EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Doles-Veep Bjt   06-16 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doles-Veep, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Veep List Includes Dole _ Both of Them</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One in a series of occasional stories about vice presidential
prospects</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a city where power is spelled with a
capital ``P'' the Doles _ Bob and Elizabeth _ are the
quintessential Power Couple, a status confirmed by the likelihood
that both are on George Bush's list of vice presidential prospects.
   A Bush-Dole ticket sounds good to a lot of people. The question
is, which Dole?
   The husband is the Senate Republican leader who finished second
to Bush in the race for the GOP presidential nomination.
   The wife is a former transportation secretary and Federal Trade
commissioner who won favorable reviews as a campaigner for her
husband when he was the GOP vice presidential nominee in 1976 and
during his two later bids for the presidential nomination
   Dole the senator is strongest where Bush is weakest _ in the
Farm Belt, where he thrashed Bush in Iowa, Kansas, South Dakota,
and Minnesota. Polls also show Dole running better among
independents and Democrats than does Bush.
   Dole the former transportation secretary also helps Bush in an
area where he needs it _ among women. Recent polls show a gender
gap for Bush that looks more like a chasm, with the vice
president's rating among women running almost 20 points below his
standing among men.
   ``I think it would clearly help Bush among women,'' said
Patricia Ireland, a vice president of the National Organization for
Women, when asked the impact of having Elizabeth Dole on the ticket.
   When Bob Dole was the GOP vice presidential nominee in 1976, the
Secret Service code names for the couple were Ramrod for the
candidate and Rainbow for his wife.
   Those names seem particularly well-chosen in the light of events
during and since that campaign.
   The Kansas senator has earned a reputation as a tough, acerbic
campaigner, whose most memorable moment in the 1988 contest was the
night of his New Hampshire primary loss when he was asked if he had
anything to say to Bush.
   ``Tell him to stop lying about my record,'' snarled the senator.
   A native of Salisbury, N.C., Elizabeth Hanford Dole is a
Harvard-educated lawyer who came to Washington in the 1960s as a
staff assistant in the old Department of Health, Education and
Welfare. She worked in the White House office of Consumer Affairs
under President Lyndon B. Johnson and was named to the Federal
Trade Commission by President Richard M. Nixon.
   She worked as a special assistant for public liaison in the
Reagan White House and, in February 1983, she was named secretary
of transportation.
   She resigned in September 1987 to do ``everything I can'' to
help her husband get elected president.
   ``I'm from Russell, Kansas, and proud of it,'' Bob Dole told
campaign audiences. It was an especially effective appeal to
Midwestern Republicans, as were the terrible wounds he suffered in
World War II which left him without the use of his right arm.
   He was elected to House in 1960 and to the Senate in 1968. In
addition to serving in the Senate, he was chairman of the
Republican National Committee from 1971 through 1973, and the early
days of the Watergate scandal. Dole was succeeded in the party post
by Bush.
   When President Gerald Ford picked the wisecracking Dole as his
running mate in 1976, the choice surprised many people. His
slashing campaign style surprised even more. He later said he was
sent ``into the briar patch while he (Ford) stayed in the Rose
Garden.''
   The low point came during a vice presidential debate with Walter
F. Mondale, when Dole referred to American lives lost in ``Democrat
wars.''
   The Kansas senator bid for the top spot on the ticket in 1980
and vowed to run a positive campaign. He did, but he got few votes
and was an early casualty.
   His fortunes took a positive turn in 1980 when the Republicans
captured control of the Senate in the Reagan landslide. Dole soon
was getting rave reviews as chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee and in 1985 he succeeded Howard H. Baker as Senate GOP
leader.
   He still had his eye on the White House and after a big victory
in Iowa in February 1988 appeared on his way to the nomination. But
Bush turned it around in New Hampshire, helped by television
commercials that portrayed Dole as waffling on arms control and as
a supporter of tax increases.
   Beaten everywhere by Bush on Super Tuesday, Dole never recovered
and dropped out of the GOP race on March 29.
   Elizabeth Dole often was credited with moving her husband away
from the slashing style he displayed in the 1976 campaign, but the
``old'' Bob Dole often reappeared this year.
   During the Illinois primary campaign, Dole said Bush had ``sort
of had a charmed life in politics. He's gotten quite a ways without
ever doing much.''
   That kind of talk might make it likely that the Dole on a
Bush-Dole ticket would be named Elizabeth.
</TEXT>
