<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Wright-Ethics 4thLd-Writethru a0592 06-16 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wright-Ethics, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0592,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Calls For Independent Probe of Wright</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 13 pvs, Rep. Newt, to restore Bush's title, first
name.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright said today he would
welcome the hiring of an outside investigator by the House ethics
committee if that would speed up the panel's probe of his financial
dealings.
   Wright, D-Texas, reacting to President Reagan's call for an
independent counsel in the case, said, ``I have frequently said it
is all right with me for the committee to do whatever it will.''
   ``If the committee feels its work can be expedited by hiring of
an outside counsel, then by all means,'' he told reporters. He
declined to comment directly on Reagan's remarks, including the
president's incorrect assertion that Democrats controlled the
ethics committee, saying, ``I'm going to be kinder to the president
than he was to me.''
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., the next ranking
Democrat after Wright, said Reagan apparently was ``confused'' and
had aligned the White House with ``politically motivated''
Republicans.
   Foley said that continued Republican pressure against Wright is
``a politically motivated attack on the speaker, designed to ...
theoretically balance the problems the administration has had with
ethics, and even criminal problems.''
   Foley, speaking on CBS-TV's ``This Morning,'' said the criticism
of Wright is ``linked to such things as sort of crass fundraising
efforts for the Republican Party.''
   Reagan, becoming the latest GOP officeholder to join the verbal
fray over allegations Wright has violated House ethics rules, said
Wednesday that ``everyone would feel that it was more proper'' if
an investigation were done by someone outside Congress.
   The bipartisan House ethics committee voted last week to
investigate allegations the speaker misused his office for personal
gain.
   Reagan, speaking to reporters, said, ``I have to wonder if it
should not be an independent counsel from the standpoint of the
relationship of the speaker to the majority of the committee. And I
think everyone would feel that it was more proper if it was done by
an investigator outside _ an appointed investigator.''
   Said Foley, ``there's a confusion over the president's
terminology and his comments about the committee.''
   ``The president said he thought it was especially important
because of the majority. This is an even committee _ six Democrats,
six Republicans,'' said Foley. ``None of the Democrats (were)
appointed originally by this speaker. They're people of high
integrity; that's why they're put on the committee.''
   The committee is looking into allegations that Wright, D-Texas,
has violated House ethics rules by misusing his office for personal
gain and improperly intervening with federal regulators.
   Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who first raised the allegations,
Vice President George Bush and several other GOP officeholders have
suggested that it would be better to have the investigation
conducted by an independent counsel.
   Reagan made the remarks during an interview with seven reporters
from the seven countries that will participate in the economic
summit June 19-21 in Toronto.
   Wright is accused of six possible violations of House rules but
has denied any wrongdoing.
   The accusations include improper lobbying on behalf of oil
companies with which Wright may have had financial relationships,
circumstances surrounding publication of a book for which he
received a higher-than-usual royalty and which was produced with
the help of a congressionally paid staffer, contacts with federal
officials on behalf of Texas savings and loans and the use of a
condominium in Fort Worth for which he paid no monthly rent.
</TEXT>
