<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     06-16 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRIMOS, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After more than four decades of dusty travels
entertaining fans around the minor leagues, the ``Clown Prince of
Baseball,'' Max Patkin, is getting a chance to show his antics on
the big screen.
   Patkin, 68, plays himself in his motion picture debut in ``Bull
Durham,'' a baseball comedy opening in theaters this week.
   ``More people will know who I am, and that feels pretty good,''
said Patkin, who lives in the Philadelphia suburb of King of
Prussia.
   Patkin's acting career began in the 1940s, when an injury ended
the young pitcher's dream of playing in the big leagues. He still
made it _ but as a baseball clown, contorting his face and
prominent nose while mimicking baseball people with exaggerated
gestures.
   Writer-director Ron Shelton caught Patkin's act in the early
1960s while Shelton was a second baseman in the minors.
   ``He was just a kid,'' Patkin recalled. ``We palled around a
little bit back then, and years later, he wrote me into the film.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Georgia state Sen. Julian Bond will
join the faculty of Drexel University this fall, a university
spokesman said.
   Bond, as an adjunct member of the school's Department of History
and Politics, will give biweekly lectures on the civil rights
movement, said spokesman Philip Terranova. Bond is in Philadelphia
this week to address the 19th annual national Conference on Fair
Housing on the Drexel campus.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Ballet Theatre will dance in Paris in
October for the first time in more than a decade, Mikhail
Baryshnikov announced Thursday.
   Baryshnikov, ABT's artistic director, said the company will
perform as part of the city-sponsored 26th International Dance
Festival.
   ``I think the company is ready for Europe, it is in good
shape,'' he said.
   It has been 11 years since the company last danced in Paris and
four years since their last tour outside the United States. The
dancers, he said, ``are very excited'' about the trip.
   Centerpiece of the tour will be the performance of Leonide
Massine's ``Gaite Parisienne,'' set to the music of Jacques
Offenbach, with costumes by haute couture superstar Christian
Lacroix.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JOHNSON CITY, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Timothy Busfield, who stars in
ABC-TV's ``thirtysomething,'' says he never wanted to be a
television actor while he was growing up.
   ``I saw `Goldfinger' when I was about 7 and I thought, `That's
it. I want to be James Bond.' But I never got a chin, so I knew
that was out,'' said Busfield during a visit Wednesday to East
Tennessee State University, where he majored in acting.
   A baseball career also interested him, but Busfield said he was
too small.
   Busfield said he wound up in television after he found he
enjoyed television more than theater after bit roles on the tube
that included the son of ``Trapper John, M.D.''
   Busfield, 31, who plays Elliott on ``thirtysomething,'' recently
set up a scholarship fund at East Tennessee State that offers
aspiring young actors $500 each.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Songwriter Otis Blackwell says a bottle
of soft drink inspired him to write the tune ``All Shook Up,''
which Elvis Presley recorded more than 30 years ago.
   Blackwell said music publisher Goldy Goldmark used to tell him,
`` `You can write about anything. Write about this!' And he shook a
bottle of soda.''
   Blackwell went home and wrote ``All Shook Up.''
   ``I just wanted to show him I could do it,'' he said.
   His other hit compositions include ``Handy Man,'' ``Great Balls
of Fire,'' ``Fever'' and ``Return to Sender.''
   Blackwell, who has lived in New York City much of his life, has
just opened a publishing company, a small recording studio and a
record company in Nashville.
</TEXT>
