<DOCNO> AP880616-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1302EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0436 06-16 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,810</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 4 grafs new with Gore endorsement; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
bgng, `Dukakis was.' Edits to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis today picked up
the endorsement of former rival Albert Gore Jr., who predicted that
the likely presidential nominee will capture the backing of the
South's conservative electorate.
   ``On occasion, Mike and I had differences but out friendship
always grew and our debates helped strengthen the Democratic Party
and increase the Democrats' chance of victory in the fall,'' the
Tennessee senator said in a statement he was to deliver later today.
   Gore, one of four recent opponents to endorse Dukakis, said the
Massachusetts governor ``is going to carry our party to victory in
November. He is going to win in the East, in the North, in the
West, and he is going to win right here in the South.''
   ``Our part of the country spoke for change on Super Tuesday and
Mike Dukakis stands for change,'' said Gore, who planned to call on
his 289 delegates to back the Massachusetts governor at the
Democratic National Convention in July.
   Dukakis was using the Gore endorsement to kick off a trip
through seven Southern states, many of them once considered secure
for Bush.
   ``Dukakis can win Florida,'' said Charles Whitehead, the state's
Democratic Party chairman. ``I think Florida is the hardest state
for any Democrat to win of any Southern state.''
   But, said Whitehead, Dukakis is ``not being perceived as a
liberal. He's a progressive, a middle-of-the-roader.''
   At the same time, the Democratic chairman said, Bush is
perceived ``as a follower, not as a leader.''
   In the final round of primaries last week, Dukakis surpassed the
2,081 delegates he needed for a majority, but Jesse Jackson has
vowed to remain in the race for the nomination until the votes are
counted at the convention.
   Gore dropped out of the race after the New York primary in which
he finished a disappointing third in a field of three. The
Tennessee senator had pursued a Southern strategy for the
nomination, downplaying the traditional early tests in Iowa and New
Hampshire and hoping to benefit from a flood of Dixie votes on
March 8.
   Gore did well on March 8, but then failed to attract much
support in such Northern states as Illinois, Wisconsin and New York.
   For Dukakis, as with all Democratic presidential candidates, the
South is a critical part of the coalition needed to attain the 270
electoral votes needed to win the presidency.
   In the last five presidential elections, the only Democratic
winner was Jimmy Carter of Georgia who carried 10 of 11 Southern
states.
   Bush took command of the race for the Republican presidential
nomination by winning 16 primaries on March 8, most of them in the
South.
   Strategists for the vice president, a New Englander who now
claims Texas as his home, consider the region his base, a claim
disputed by Dukakis.
   ``Mike Dukakis knows he can win states in the South and he's
going to campaign actively there,'' said Leslie Dach, a Dukakis
campaign spokesman. ``While George Bush has a lot of homes, he has
no secure political base and he's going to have to campaign
everywhere.''
   Dukakis' three-day foray into the region was to include stops in
Tennessee, South Carolina, Florida, Mississippi, Louisiana, Texas
and Alabama.
   He won the Florida and Texas primaries on March 8. Gore carried
Tennessee, while Jackson was the winner in Alabama and South
Carolina.
   Most Southern Democrats were openly urging Dukakis to choose
someone like Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas
or Sen. Robert Graham of Florida from the region as his running
mate.
   ``The decision on the vice presidency will be fundamental,''
said Wayne Bailey, a professor of political science at Stetson
University in Deland, Fla., and a Democratic Party activist.
   The seven states where Dukakis was campaigning have a total of
95 electoral votes, the biggest prizes being Texas with 29 and
Florida with 21.
   The Massachusetts governor is given little chance of beating
Bush in the most conservative of the Southern states.
   ``I honestly don't expect him to take Alabama,'' said Natalie
Davis, a pollster based in Birmingham. ``Bush is going to have to
lose it.''
   One theme Dukakis was sounding that is welcomed by Southern
voters was a tough stand against crime and drugs.
   During appearances in his home state on Wednesday, Dukakis
touted the declining Massachusetts crime rate and lambasted the
Reagan administration for obstructing the war on drugs by cutting
Coast Guard funds.
   ``How can we possibly be serious about fighting a war on drugs
when we're cutting Coast Guard patrols by 55 percent?'' he told
reporters outside the state police academy. ``It's that kind of
thing _ one of the reasons I'm running for the presidency.''
</TEXT>
