<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0529 06-16 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0529,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberates In Mecham Criminal Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `The jury ...,' to UPDATE with deliberations
under way today.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham said he had a
``clear conscience'' as he awaited a jury's verdict on criminal
charges that he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan.
   The jury deliberated for 3 hours and 45 minutes after receiving
the case Wednesday, then resumed work today.
   ``I'll feel better when it's here (the verdict),'' Mecham, 64,
told reporters as the jury was dismissed for the night. But he
added he expected to sleep well because ``I have a clear
conscience.''
   The former governor again insisted that he and his co-defendant,
his brother Willard, were innocent of any crime.
   But prosecutor Barnett Lotstein told the jury in Wednesday's
final portion of the closing arguments that the Mechams' ``cloak of
innocence has been stripped away thread by thread by thread;
Willard Mecham and Evan Mecham stand naked before you now ...
because the evidence is overwhelming of their guilt.''
   Mecham, a Republican, took office in January 1987 and was
removed April 4 when the state Senate convicted him of two
unrelated impeachment charges. He also was impeached in connection
with the loan, but the Senate decided not to hear that charge for
fear of prejudicing his criminal trial.
   The Mechams face felony charges of concealing the $350,000 loan
on financial disclosure reports required by the state. The loan
from developer Barry Wolfson did not appear on Mecham's personal or
campaign finance statements.
   Mecham's lawyer, Michael Scott, told reporters ``there was
absolutely no evidence of intent'' to conceal the loan.
   The defense said the loan was properly reported as part of a
$465,000 lump sum that was listed as a campaign contribution from
Evan Mecham, and that the failure to itemize the loan was an
innocent mistake by his brother, Willard Mecham, who was his
campaign treasurer.
   Lotstein disputed a defense claim that the loan was common
knowledge because one former top Mecham aide said she knew about it.
   ``To claim that the loan was not a secret from the public
because some insiders knew about it would be like claiming that the
secret plan for the Normandy invasion in World War II was public
knowledge because the general that planned it knew about it,'' the
prosecutor said.
   Lotstein contended that Mecham lied when he told reporters Oct.
30 that he did not owe any loan to Wolfson, but that his campaign
did, and that he did not intend to repay it. Wolfson testified that
Mecham called him shortly afterward, assured Wolfson he would be
repaid, and said his attorney had told him to make the public
statement.
   The defense said Mecham had no motive to hide the loan because
the report on which it appeared was not filed until a month after
the Nov. 4, 1986, election.
   But Lotstein said a disclosure of the loan early in Mecham's new
administration would have destroyed his image of being anti-special
interest.
   Mecham was charged with six felony counts of perjury, willful
concealment and filing false documents and faced from almost nine
to 22 years in prison if convicted of all charges.
   Willard Mecham faced three similar counts and up to 9{ years in
prison if convicted of all charges.
</TEXT>
