<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0601 06-16 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0601,790</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERT new grafs 9-11 with Hollings comments bgng ``Hollings
said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson today urged the
government to use caution in involving the military in its war on
drugs and said that option should be used primarily as a backup.
   Jackson testified before the Senate Committee on Labor and Human
Resources about prevention and treatment of drug abuse, and in the
session senators lavished him with praise for his outspoken
leadership on the subject.
   In answer to a question from Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, about
current sentiment in some quarters for legalization of drugs,
Jackson replied, ``That would be a mistake. It would be surrender
to the No. 1 threat to our national security. We would not think of
legalization of smog because there's a lot of it. It's dangerous.''
   Jackson, commenting on the current effort to use the military in
drug interdiction, said, ``We must be careful, however, to avoid
involving the military in any police actions against citizens or
arrests.''
   He said strengthening the Coast Guard and Customs border patrol
should be the first priority in interdiction.
   ``We should not lead with our military forces in drugs or any
other aspect of foreign policy. But the military can play a greater
and useful role in backing up these efforts and providing
intelligence assistance,'' he said.
   Before the hearing, Jackson jokingly pinned a large ``Jackson
88'' badge on Hatch's lapel. Hatch, one of the conservative
movement's guiding lights, wore the button through the hearing, but
joked that ``I thought you were worried sick about the effect it
would have on you'' to have such a conservative wearing the badge.
   Jackson later met with Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., the only
senator who has said he will give Jackson his delegate vote at the
convention.
   Hollings said he supports Jackson because he won South Carolina
and he said more Democrats should follow his example ``for the good
of the party.'' Hollings also said Jackson had changed since 1984,
when both of them ran for president.
   ``I would think Jesse frightened the bejesus out of them four
years ago. I remember him standing up and saying his time has come!
`I want it all,''' Hollings said.
   ``This time he's run a winning campaign. He hasn't frightened
anyone. He's charmed them in all of those different debates and in
his own right has leveled off.''
   On Wednesday, Jackson said he met with Dukakis campaign chairman
Paul Brountas, who has been interviewing potential running mates to
join the Massachusetts governor on the Democratic presidential
ticket.
   But Jackson told a news conference he has not yet decided
whether he would want the post, only that he has earned ``serious
consideration.''
   He made the comments after a meeting with the Congressional
Black Caucus, whose members urged him to seek the post and said
they will try to meet with Dukakis and lobby him to choose Jackson.
   Jackson would not discuss his meeting with Brountas but said it
was ``a very meaningful preliminary discussion.''
   In a Wednesday evening interview on Cable News Network, Jackson
elaborated: ``We simply discussed today the process, discussed the
guidelines, we talked about the requirements. After all, we need to
know what the rules are, what the standards will be.''
   He said he is talking to Dukakis not only about the vice
presidency, but about his budget concerns and his proposal to pay
for social spending by freezing military spending and hiking taxes
on the rich and corporations.
   He said earlier in the day that his budget priorities are his
``most critical'' concern now that Dukakis and he agree on South
Africa policy.
   ``The most critical becomes this budget, a commitment to invest
in people, a commitment to reinvest in America,'' Jackson said
following a meeting with leaders of civil rights groups.
   He said he is prepared to go to the convention floor if Dukakis
balks.
   ``Of course, that's the proper mechanism and it's the thing to
do,'' he told CNN when asked if he might wage a floor fight.
   Asked what would happen if he loses the fight, Jackson took a
philosophical approach: ``Sometimes you win, sometimes you lose.
... If you lose you will at least have left your imprint.''
   On the vice presidency issue, Dukakis has said previously that
Jackson will be considered, but not that he will get any special
consideration by being runner up.
   Jackson made clear he would like the offer to be made to him
although he has declined to say that in so many words publicly,
instead stating that it is Dukakis' option.
</TEXT>
