<1ST_LINE>u a PM-GeorgiaExecution 3rdLd-Writethru a0603 06-16 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Georgia Execution, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0603,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Execution Halted In Georgia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with execution halted. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Georgia Board of Pardons and Paroles today
blocked the execution of Freddie Davis six hours before he was to
die in the electric chair for raping and stabbing to death a woman
in 1977.
   The five-member board suspended the execution for up to 90 days
to decide whether Davis' life should be spared.
   Although the board could lift the suspension at any time, board
chairman Wayne Snow said he expected it would take at least that
long to make a decision.
   Davis, 30, would have been the second murderer put to death in
the nation in two days and the 101st since resumption of capital
punishment in 1977.
   The board, which conducted a hearing Wednesday, is the only
non-judicial state entity with the authority to commute a death
sentence.
   Davis' execution order expires at noon Tuesday. If the
suspension remains in effect beyond then, the state will have to
seek a new execution order.
   Snow said the decision was prompted by questions over Davis'
role in the killing, a new trial granted an alleged accomplice and
the accomplice's recantation of incriminating testimony.
   Earlier today, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals denied
without comment a request for a stay, and attorneys appealed to the
U.S. Supreme Court.
   The execution was scheduled for 7 p.m. at the Georgia Diagnostic
and Classification Center near Jackson.
   Davis was sentenced to death for the 1977 rape and stabbing of
Frances Rice Coe, whose neighbor Eddie Spraggins also was convicted
and sentenced to death in the case. Davis was 19 at the time of the
slaying.
   Spraggins, who was the prime witness against Davis, won a new
trial after his lawyers argued that the judge failed to properly
inform the jury that his I.Q. was 65.
   Spraggins has recanted his 1977 testimony against Davis. In an
affidavit filed with the Georgia Supreme Court he said: ``When I
testified at Freddie Davis' trial that Freddie Davis was in the
room with Mrs. Coe when Mrs. Coe was killed, this was false and
untrue.''
   On Tuesday, Edward R. Byrne Jr., 28, was executed in Louisiana
for killing a service station cashier he had romanced as part of a
plot to rob her in 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
