<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Germany-Pardon,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Red Army Faction Terrorist Pardoned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Klaus Juenschke, a former left-wing
terrorist sentenced to life in prison for robbing a bank and
killing a police officer, was pardoned Thursday after serving 16
years in prison.
   Juenschke, 40, a former member of the Red Army Faction, has
renounced terrorism in several interviews with the West German news
media.
   He was pardoned by Rheinland Pfalz governor Bernhard Vogel.
   Vogel said he pardoned Juenschke because he had changed in
views, behaved well in prison and had already spent many years
behind bars.
   Juenschke was convicted of robbing a bank in Kaiserslautern and
killing a police officer who tried to stop the Dec. 22, 1971 crime.
   The Red Army Faction, which grew from the radical students'
movement of the 1960s, claimed responsibility for killings and
attacks on U.S. military installations. The group has been inactive
in recent years, but smaller offshoots continue to operate in West
Germany.
