<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1443EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     06-16 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eban Says Party Made Mistake In Ousting Him</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elder statesman Abba Eban said Thursday the
Labor Party made a mistake when it pushed him off its slate for the
November elections to make room for political newcomers deemed more
attractive to voters.
   Eban, 73, fell victim a new selection system in which for the
first time the rank-and-file, not party bosses, chose the slate for
the elections to Israel's parliament, the Knesset.
   Half the candidates elected Wednesday were political newcomers,
and Labor's general secretary, Uzi Baram, called the outcome a
``revolution'' and ``feast for Israel's democracy.''
   ``It's clearly a disappointment,'' Eban told Israel army radio.
``During the years I have accumulated valuable knowledge and
experience. I told party members I'm ready to offer this, but if
you don't want it, I won't.''
   During his 40-year political career, Eban served as deputy prime
minister, foreign minister and Israel's ambassador to the United
States and the United Nations.
   Samuel Lewis, a former U.S. ambassador to Israel, said Eban's
ouster was a ``real tragedy, not for him, but for the country.''
   ``I've never known anyone else who I thought had made a greater
contribution to his country,'' Lewis told Israel radio from
Washington.
   Political analyst Yitzhak Galnoor said Eban might have retained
his position had the party bosses formed the slate, but the new
selection process showed he ``doesn't have a following in Israel.''
   ``Eban is not connected to any influential groups. He's just a
bright guy with a terrific sense of humor. Unfortunately, these
things are not very admired in Israeli politics,'' said Galnoor, a
political scientist at Jerusalem's Hebrew University.
   Party members did not choose Eban in the Labor Party's ranked
list of candidates for Israel's 120-member Knesset. The number of
parliament seats assigned to a party depends on its total vote in
the elections.
   Based on previous election results, Labor candidates in the top
40 to 45 slots are expected to be re-elected.
   Eleven slots, including the top seven reserved for party
leaders, were filled by appointment, not popular vote. Twenty-one
of the remaining 34 slots considered ``safe'' were given to
newcomers.
   Four of the newcomers were Sephardic Jews from North African
nations, a group that has traditionally voted for Labor's political
rival, the right-wing Likud bloc.
   Galnoor said the selection might improve Labor's chances in the
election, but also said such gains could be offset if Labor doesn't
deliver a clear message on how it will solve the Arab-Israeli
conflict.
   Polls have indicated that the Labor Party might lose the
election to Likud because many voters have moved to the right in
response to the 6-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Likud leaders say Israel will never withdraw from the occupied
territories. Labor advocates the return of some land in exchange
for peace, but opposes formation of a Palestinian state or the
dismantling of Jewish settlements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
