<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Hollings     06-16 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Hollings,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Carolina Senator Lauds Jackson Candidacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, the only senator who
has endorsed Jesse Jackson, said Thursday the Democratic
presidential candidate has run a winning campaign in 1988 that
hasn't frightened voters as it did four years ago.
   Hollings, who joined fellow South Carolinian Jackson at a
Capitol Hill news conference, said the Jackson candidacy of 1988 is
markedly different from his 1984 campaign.
   ``I would think Jesse frightened the bejesus out of them four
years ago. I remember him standing up and saying his time has come!
`I want it all,''' said Hollings, who made an unsuccessful bid for
the presidency in 1984.
   ``This time he's run a winning campaign. He hasn't frightened
anyone. He's charmed them in all of those different debates and in
his own right has leveled off,'' he said.
   People are ``looking at Jesse Jackson not as a black but really
for his own philosophy with respect to hunger and nutrition and
jobs and drugs and everything else,'' Hollings said.
   ``That's why I think he's won support black and white and from
Vermont down to Texas and the state of Washington over to South
Carolina. It's a substantially different campaign'' than four years
ago.
   Hollings, who announced last week that he will vote for Jackson
at the Democratic National Convention, said that although Michael
Dukakis is ``the obvious winner'' of the party's presidential race,
Jackson has earned his support.
   Hollings also urged other ``super delegates'' whose states and
districts were won by Jackson to join him in voting for the
candidate. Super delegates are the unpledged public and party
officeholders who will attend the convention in Atlanta, July 18-21.
   ``The obvious winner is Governor Dukakis. For the good of the
party, we also ought to be supporting Reverand Jackson. That's why
coming from my home state, he won my home state, he certainly has
earned my vote'' at the convention, Hollings said.
   Other Democratic senators met with Jackson but no endorsement
was forthcoming.
   Jackson, ignoring rival Michael Dukakis' mathematical lock on
the Democratic nomination, has said he will seek out the support of
the super delegates. And he has repeatedly pointed to Hollings as
an example for other super delegates.
   The senator, in announcing his decision last week, said he
wanted to honor a native South Carolinian and join the delegates
supporting Jackson.
   Jackson has said he is not willing to concede the nomination to
Dukakis. ``My priority at this point is to seek the nomination,''
Jackson insisted.
   Dukakis holds a commanding 2-to-1 lead over Jackson in the
latest Associated Press delegate count, and leads by a wide margin
in the number of super delegates _ 348 to 54.
   Jackson's super delegates include 20 members of the House and
just one member of the Senate _ Hollings. Only three of his super
delegates are white.
   Dukakis's 348 super delegates include 62 non-whites.
</TEXT>
