<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Vatican-Lefebvre     06-16 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Lefebvre,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Urges Rebel Archbishop Not to Consecrate Bishops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II has urged Archbishop
Marcel Lefebvre to abandon a consecration of bishops that would
split the church and probably get the rebel traditionalist
excommunicated, the Vatican said Thursday.
   Creating bishops without papal permission is against canon. It
seems a certain path to expulsion from the Roman Catholic Church
for the French archbishop, who has rebelled for two decades against
what he calls ``self-destructive'' changes in the church.
   Without being specific, the pope reminded Lefebvre by letter of
``the inevitable theological and canonical consequences that are
known to you.''
   Leaders of the church in France, Switzerland and West Germany
issued a joint statement Thursday urging Lefebvre to ``to change
his decision and we pray that he does not commit the unrepairable.''
   The last schism in the church occurred in 1870 over the dogma of
papal infallibity.
   Lefebvre, 82-year-old founder of the traditionalist St. Pius X
Fraternity based in Switzerland, said Wednesday he would consecrate
four followers as bishops June 30. The fraternity was named after
Piux X, who was pope in 1903-14 and who condemned religious
modernism.
   The Vatican said in a statement Thursday that, in a May 5
protocol worked out by Lefebvre and the Vatican, the pontiff gave
the archbishop permission to consecrate one bishop Aug. 15.
   Pope Paul VI barred Lefebvre in 1976 from saying Mass and giving
the sacraments, but the archbishop has ordained more than 200
priests who continue to use the 16th century Tridentine Mass, a
Latin rite for which special permission is required. His movement
claims millions of followers worldwide.
   According to the statement Thursday, the Vatican issued a
``pressing appeal to members of (Lefebvre's) Fraternity and their
followers ... to rethink their position and remain united'' with
the pope, ``assuring them that all measures will be taken to
guarantee their identity in full communion with the Catholic
Church.''
   Noting Lefebvre's announcement ``with profound pain,'' the
Vatican issued a chronology Thursday of its efforts in the past
seven months to resolve the dispute. It also published the texts of
the protocol and letters between the the archbishop and John Paul.
   Under the protocol, Lefebvre would have promised tobe faithful
to the church and pope and to accept the teachings of the Second
Vatican Council of 1962-65. The council simplified and modernized
the liturgy, instituting such reforms as celebration of the Mass in
the local language.
   The protocol required Lefebvre's recognition of the ``validity
of the Mass and the sacraments ... according to the rites ...
promulgated by Paul VI and by John Paul II,'' but would allow the
archbishop to use liturgy antedating the council.
   Lefebvre wrote to Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, head of the
Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, the day after the
protocol insisting that consecration of the bishop take place June
30, the Vatican said.
   When his request was refused, it said, Lefebvre wrote to the
cardinal and John Paul renewing both his demand for June 30 and a
previous proposal that four bishops be consecrated.
   At one point in the exchange of correspondence with the pope,
Lefebvre said: ``The false ecumenism which lies at the origin of
all the innovations, in liturgy, in new relations between the
church and the world, in the conception of the church itself, leads
the church to its ruin and Catholics to apostasy.''
   John Paul responded: ``From a paternal heart, but with all the
gravity required by the present circumstances, I exhort you,
Venerable Brother, to renounce your plan, which, if realized, could
only appear as a schismatic act whose inevitable theological and
canonical consequences are known to you.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1500EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Children'sHome     06-16 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Vows To Continue Bethel After Release On Bail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Baptist minister who runs a
children's home the state ordered shut down vowed to keep it open
as he was released on bond on charges of assaulting a police
officer.
   The Rev. Herman Fountain, posting $40,000 bail on three felony
counts, walked out late Wednesday and said, ``I plan to continue
like I always have.''
   Bethel Home for Children, operated by Fountain's independent
Baptist group, was ordered closed down June 10 when a judge ruled
its residents were subjected to ``physical abuse, medical neglect
and detention amounting to imprisonment.''
   State welfare officials have taken custody of a total of 77
children, ages 10 to 17, from the home. About 50 have been released
to their parents and the status of the others is pending.
   Meanwhile, Welfare Commissioner Thomas Brittain said he had
hidden his 13-year-old daughter because of kidnapping threats
following the closure of Bethel.
   Brittain said he decided to hide his daughter after callers
talked of kidnapping and putting her in a home such as Bethel.
   Fountain, 38, was arrested Monday when officers went to the
campus church to search for children who had run off when the home
was shut down. He was accused of scuffling with some of the
officers who were serving subpoenas on staff members.
   Before state welfare workers arrived at the home June 10 to take
custody of the children, most had fled. Law officers later found
about 60 children hiding at private residences and roaming the
streets of Lucedale. About 60 state troopers and local law officers
raided Fountain's church Monday to search for others. Eleven
children were taken into custody at that time.
   Fountain has refused to give the state a list of the children
that were at the home. He also has said he has taken in an
additional child since the court order.
   The state has required that parents or guardians to regain
custody must sign a statment promising not to send the children
back to Bethel.
</TEXT>
