<HEAD>Man Impaled Through Leg While Scaling Wrought-Iron Fence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 32-year-old man was in stable condition
Thursday after he was impaled on a wrought-iron fence and had to be
rushed to the hospital on a flat-bed truck with the fence spike
sticking through his leg, authorities said.
   Mark Smith, whose last known address was a shelter in Hartford,
was found hanging from the fence he was climbing with a spearlike
iron spike stuck through his leg below his knee.
   A security guard called police early Wednesday to report a man
yelling from behind Christ Church Cathedral, police said.
   The spike was about 2 inches thick at the top and the tip was
pointed, making its extraction extremely difficult, police said.
Rescuers cut a section of about 3 feet square using blowtorches.
   Doctors at Hartford Hospital relaxed Smith's muscles and pull
the fence spear from his leg, police said.
   ``They made an ambulance out of a wrecker,'' said Harvey L.
Kagan, president of Professional Ambulance Service. ``They couldn't
get the man in the ambulance with the fence.''
