<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietFilmmaker     06-16 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Filmmaker,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Filmmaker Visits Israel, Praises Solzhenitsyn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Soviet film director visiting Israel
praised books banned in his country, said the Kremlin should renew
ties with the Jewish state and showed Soviet immigrants his latest
movie.
   Eldar Ryazanov, secretary of the Soviet Cinematographers Union,
also told about 1,000 Soviet Jews at Wednesday night's screening
that some political emigrants should be pardoned and allowed to
visit the land of their birth.
   Ryazanov hailed Mikhail S. Gorbachev as ``the most humane
leader'' in the Soviet Union in decades. He cited reforms that
allowed him and his wife to visit Israel.
   Ryazonov is the highest-ranking Soviet artist to come to Israel
since such visits became possible about a year ago. Travel from the
Soviet Union to Israel was barred after the Kremlin severed ties in
1967, and Soviet artists who did visit the West usually traveled
without their families.
   ``But it's very tragic to spend a lifetime before starting to
enjoy freedom,'' said Ryazanov.
   The 60-year-old filmmaker, who is known for satirical comedies,
greeted former compatriots in halting Hebrew and won applause as he
said ties between Israel and the Soviet Union should be restored.
   Ryazanov then switched to native Russian to praise Gorbachev's
reforms, but almost in the same breath said he just resigned from a
job at the Soviet Television in protest over state censorship.
   Answering written questions, he praised books by exiled Nobel
Prize winner Alexander Solzhenitsyn, who now lives in the United
States, and called ``The Gulag Archipelago'' ``a work of vast
social importance.'' Solzhenitsyn's books are banned in the Soviet
Union.
   But Ryazanov omitted the writer's name when he said some
political emigrants _ such as theater director Yuri Lyubimov, who
took Israeli citizenship, and writers Vasily Aksyonov of the United
States and Naum Korzavin of France _ should get back their Soviet
citizenship.
   ``They should be able to choose where to live while being able
to travel freely to their homeland,'' Ryazanov said. ``Freedom to
travel ... is as natural as freedom to breathe.''
   He noted that the airplane that brought him to Israel was packed
with Soviet Jews visiting emigrant relatives in Israel. ``They
could not see their relatives for years. There were embraces,
tears, and one couldn't watch it calmly.''
   In recent months, hundreds of Soviet Jews have been allowed to
visit relatives in Israel, and some immigrants are permitted to
travel to the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet Union also allowed 4,695 Jews to emigrate this year.
Israel officially estimates as many as 380,000 want to leave, but
an Israeli delegation leader who recently visited the Soviet Union
put the figure at 25,000.
   Ryazanov said that he tried ``to use freedom as much as
possible'' in his 1987 romantic comedy ``Forgotten Melody For A
Flute,'' which was screened for the Israeli audience.
   The movie is about a Soviet bureaucrat who is married to a woman
he doesn't love but whose influential father promises to help his
career. The hero must decide whether to remain married or run off
with a poor nurse he loves.
   ``At last Soviet lovers have sex,'' said one immigrant viewer,
referring to a scene in which the adulterous couple is shown naked
in bed. Others praised the film for making fun of Soviet censorship
and influence peddling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1528EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FletcherSpeech     06-16 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fletcher Speech,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>R&D Lag Threatening US Position, Space Agency Chief Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration warned Thursday that the United States is losing its
position as leader of the world's industrial nations because it is
spending less now on technical research and development.
   James Fletcher, in a speech prepared for the National Conference
on Strategic Management of Research and Development, said the
nation is ``just now beginning to recognize a long-term drought in
the national technical capability.''
   For instance, he said, the American machine tool industry ``has
been swamped'' by Japan, West Germany and Italy and the U.S. market
share of civil aircraft has dropped to 65 percent ``and promises to
continue its decline.''
   ``We have focused on marketing old products in newer packages at
the expense of investments in innovation and evolutionary
improvements,'' the NASA administrator said.
   Fletcher said the federal investment in aeronautics and space
research and development has declined, causing NASA to be less bold
in its technological innovation and exploration of the unknown.
   ``This is the wrong direction for leadership,'' he said. ``This
is living off the advances of the past _ in NASA's case, of the
Apollo era.''
   Fletcher said that if the U.S. trends continue in technology,
``NASA and the nation will become net consumers, not producers, of
science and the technology it makes possible. If that occurs, the
climb back to any position of parity in world affairs will be
arduous indeed, and certainly not certain of success.''
</TEXT>
