<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-AfghanPOWS     06-16 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan POWS,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Appeal for Information on Soldiers Missing in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Contents of 9th graf may offend some readers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin on Thursday stepped up its campaign
for information on 300 Red Army soldiers missing in Afghanistan,
and the Soviet Red Cross appealed for the return of prisoners held
by Afghan guerrillas.
   Dmitri Venediktov, chairman of the Soviet Red Cross and Red
Crescent societies, appealed for help from the governments of
Pakistan, Iran and the United States as well as from Afghanistan's
guerrillas, who according to one estimate are holding up to 250
Soviets prisoner.
   On Monday, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
summoned the Pakistani ambassador in Moscow to ask for help finding
missing soldiers and freeing POWs. The official Soviet news agency
Tass quoted Venediktov as saying he had made similar requests to
the Pakistani Red Cross Society.
   ``The reply to the first request has said the Pakistan Red Cross
Society does not know if there are Soviet POWs (prisoners of war)
in that country. A response to the second request has yet to
come,'' Venediktov told Tass.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, told
reporters Monday that previous appeals to Pakistan had led to the
release of some Soviet prisoners, but he did say when or how many.
   Gerasimov also said Pakistan continued to channel U.S.-supplied
arms to the guerrillas, which he said violated the Geneva accords
on an Afghan settlement.
   In New York on Wednesday, expatriate Soviet artist Mihail
Chemiakin and American writers, scholars and religious figures
announced the formation of the International Committee for the
Rescue of Russian Prisoners of War in Afghanistan.
   The only Soviet citizen on the committee, Iona Andronov, New
York correspondent for the weekly Literary Gazette, said that 250
of the missing Soviets were being held by the guerrillas.
   A statement from the committee, distributed by Tass, said that
``even some Americans unfriendly to the Soviet Union, after
visiting the Mujahedeen in Afghanistan, have told of the killing of
Soviet POWs, how prior to their execution the young men's eyes were
torn out, their noses, ears and genitals cut off.''
   ``Sometimes, the doomed prisoners are skinned alive,'' the
statement asserted. ``American eyewitnesses also inform us that
those POWs who have survived so far are chained hand and foot and
held underground in constant darkness.''
   The Soviets have said they had 100,300 soldiers in Afghanistan
before they began pulling them out May 15. Under the terms of the
U.N.-sponsored agreement on Afghanistan signed in Geneva in April,
half of the Soviet troops are supposed to be home by Aug. 15 and
the remainder by Feb. 15.
   Tass reported Thursday that seven people were killed and 13 were
wounded by rockets fired by Afghan guerrillas into a residential
neighborhood of Kabul.
   The agency, in a dispatch from Kabul, gave few details of the
attack, which occurred Wednesday night, except to say that the dead
included women and children and that several houses were destroyed.
</TEXT>
