<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WhiteHouseTurnover     06-16 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-White House Turnover,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mari Maseng To Succeed Griscom As Communications Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mari Maseng, who left the White House last
year to be press secretary to Sen. Bob Dole's presidential
campaign, will return to work for President Reagan as chief of
communications and planning, succeeding Thomas C. Griscom, it was
announced Thursday.
   Griscom submitted his resignation, effective June 30. He did not
disclose what he planned to do next, though he had said for months
that he planned to leave the White House after the Moscow summit.
   Griscom joined the White House in February 1987 when former Sen.
Howard Baker, his long-time associate, took over as chief of staff.
As director of communications and planning, Griscom was in charge
of the speechwriting staff, planning Reagan's agenda and arranging
special events, such as the superpower summit meetings in
Washington and Moscow.
   In his resignation letter, he said he would remember the summits
as the high point of his tenure.
   Ms. Maseng, 34, worked at the White House on two occasions
during the Reagan administration. She was a member of Reagan's
speechwriting team from January 1981 until November 1983, and
director of the office of public liaison, responsibile for contact
with constituent groups, from May 1986 until July 1987.
   In addition, she served as assistant secretary for public
affairs at the Transportation Department in between her White House
jobs.
   When she left the White House in 1987, she became press
secretary to Dole's presidential campaign, a post she held until
his withdrawal as a candidate earlier this year. Since then, she
has worked as a management and public affairs consultant.
   Dole, R-Kan., the Senate's Republican leader, said in a
statement: ``I congratulate Mari, and wish her all the best in her
new assignment. She is everything you would want in a staffer:
tireless, committed and loyal. The president will be well served.''
</TEXT>
