<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>14 Killed in Separate Battles in Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mortars and rockets whizzed through two
refugee camps in Beirut on Thursday, leaving 12 people dead and 29
injured as rival Palestinian groups fought for control of the areas.
   In southeast Lebanon, Israeli soldiers killed two Lebanese
guerrillas in an ambush on the western slopes of Mount Hermon,
police said.
   Police said the new casualties in Beirut brought the toll to 31
people killed and 130 wounded since the latest clashes over the
Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh refugee camps broke out last week.
   The thuds of exploding shells resounded as ambulances evacuated
casualties from the two shantytowns on the southern outskirts of
the Lebanese capital.
   The Fatah guerrilla group of Yasser Arafat's mainstream
Palestine Liberation Organization accused the breakaway faction
called Fatah-Uprising of indiscriminate shelling. The group
rebelled against Arafat's leadership with Syrian backing in May
1983.
   A spokesman for Arafat's group, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the rival group was shelling both refugee camps
from the outside. He said his group repulsed several attacks.
   A police spokesman said Fatah-Uprising rebels shelled the camps
from Syrian-controlled territory in west Beirut and the seaside
suburb of Ouzai.
   The police spokesman confirmed Fatah-Uprising tried but failed
to enter the camps. The fighting raged despite efforts by a
committee of representatives from seven neutral Palestinian groups
to supervise a cease-fire.
   In southeast Lebanon, Israeli gunners and helicopter gunships
attacked the terrain north of Israel's self-proclaimed security
zone while pursuing a guerrilla group, another police spokesman
said.
   He said the hunt by Israel and their militia allies, the South
Lebanon Army, ended when two guerrillas from the Lebanese Communist
Party were killed in an ambush north of the security zone.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified according to police
regulations, said an Israeli patrol set up the ambush overnight
north of the zone and confronted the communist group as it left to
carry out an attack in the zone.
