<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MineSafety     06-16 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mine Safety,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miners Protest Safety Rule Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 coal miners hooted and
cheered as union leaders and miners denounced proposed federal
safety rule changes at a public hearing Thursday.
   The hearing was punctuated by catcalls, shouts and standing
ovations from the miners, who union officials said were on a
contract-sanctioned day off from 87 mines in Illinois and Indiana.
   The United Mine Workers is staging rallies at public hearings on
the proposed changes being conducted around the country by the Mine
Safety and Health Administration. Thursday's hearing was the fourth
of six planned.
   ``Excuse me,'' said moderator Patricia Silvey, trying to quiet
the crowd. ``This will be an orderly proceeding.''
   Jerry Jones, president of UMW District 12 in Illinois, also
appealed for order, then accused the Reagan administration of
putting the interests of mine owners before safety.
   ``Their position is that they want to get government out of
industry,'' Jones said. ``Now surely a coal operator, for example,
should know how to operate his mine. But deregulation has not been
effective.''
   Some miners carried signs reading, ``We give our sweat but not
our blood,'' and ``Laws to live by, not die by.''
   The proposals on underground mine ventilation include
elimination of required 20-minute checks for methane gas, an
increase in the allowable limits of methane and a lifting of the
requirement that miners be evacuated whenever ventilation fans
break down.
   Representatives from the federal agency maintained that the
proposed changes partly reflect improvements in mine monitoring
systems.
   ``We included several new provisions in the proposals that we
think would be definite (safety) improvements,'' said Ms. Silvey,
director of the agency's Office of Standards, Regulations and
Variances.
   She said the changes include a provision for electronic systems
that continuously monitor mine air for methane and oxygen
deficiencies.
   Miner Robert M. Danner, from nearby Newburgh, said methane fire
is one of the miners' greatest fears. He recalled an accident at
the Madisonville, Ky., mine where he worked 15 years ago.
   ``We had an ignition and a roll of fire came across the man from
a pocket of gas,'' Danner said. ``It didn't kill him, but it
charred him black. It's a horrible site if you've ever seen a man
who's just been burned to a crisp.''
   The union contends the rule changes were designed primarily to
save mining companies money.
   However, testimony from companies at previous hearings indicates
that use of the electronic air monitoring system does not guarantee
higher profits, said Richard Zuetenhorst, a deputy director in the
federal mining regulations office.
</TEXT>
