<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Gets Gore Endorsement, Endorses Wright Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis endorsed the
idea of a special counsel to investigate House Speaker Jim Wright
on Thursday and said Wright was willing to go along in contrast
``to the kind of stonewalling we've had from the administration.''
   Asked about Wright as he opened a Southern campaign swing,
Dukakis said he understood the Texas Democrat had ``welcomed the
independent counsel.''
   Wright said Thursday in Washington that he would welcome the
hiring of an outside investigator by the House ethics committee if
that would speed up the panel's probe of his financial dealings.
   Dukakis was in Nashville to receive the endorsement of Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, one of his former rivals for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
   During the primary campaign, Gore had compared Dukakis to the
Democratic presidential candidates who had lost four of the past
five national elections.
   But Gore, who dropped out of the race after losing badly in the
New York primary, said, ``I think that Mike Dukakis' image in the
South and all over the country is very different than many people
thought it was going to be when this campaign began.''
   Gore differed strongly with Dukakis on defense and foreign
policy issues during the campaign. But he said Thursday, ``I was
pleased to see not only Mike Dukakis but all of us learning from
each other.''
   Dukakis, when asked if he hoped to get a similar endorsement
from Jesse Jackson before the Democratic convention next month,
said, ``I would hope Jesse Jackson will be a part of this campaign
and as early as possible.''
   Jackson has vowed to continue his campaign until the convention
roll call that decides the nomination.
   Dukakis already has far more than the delegates he needs for a
majority on that roll call.
   Asked if he was concerned at the prospect of Wright presiding
over the convention at the same time he was under investigation,
Dukakis said, ``I thought there was a presumption of innocence in
this country, certainly one I believe in.''
   At the same time, he said he has called for Attorney General
Edwin Meese III to resign. ``I certainly have,'' said the
Massachusetts governor. ``That's after repeated evidence of
insensitivity, a lack of awareness of what we mean when we talk
about high standards.''
   ``If you're attorney general of this country and you've stumbled
as often as he has and made as many mistakes as he has and provided
as weak leadership as he has, you ought to leave office,'' Dukakis
said.
   He said that Wright's attitude toward the idea of an independent
counsel ``contrasts rather sharply with the kind of stonewalling
we've had from the administration on case after case after case.''
   He said Wright's approach was ``the way that we ought to respond
to these kind of things.''
   Gore said he was confident Dukakis would carry five or six
states in the South against Republican George Bush.
</TEXT>
