<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea     06-16 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Attack Police; 6 Arrested for Firebomb Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical mobs shouting about government
corruption attacked riot squads Thursday, and police said they
arrested six students who tried to throw firebombs at the home of
former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   Fighting began at the University of Foreign Studies in eastern
Seoul when police fired volleys of tear gas to keep 1,000 radicals
from five nearby schools from marching off the campus.
   Students hurled firebombs and rocks for two hours, screaming
``Punish criminals!'' ``Yankee go home!'' and other demands for
withdrawal of the 42,000 U.S. troops stationed in South Korea under
a mutual defense pact.
   Anti-Americanism has become a strong element in recent protests
by the radical students, who contend the United States enforces
partition of the Korean peninsula and treats the South as a colony.
   Twenty students throwing firebombs dashed toward Chun's home
Wednesday night, but tear gas stopped them 150 yards short of the
target and six were arrested, police reported.
   They said the students flung six firebombs at riot officers and
a nearby police post afterward, shouting: ``Investigate corruption
under the former government!'' No damage or injuries were reported.
   Police seized 48 firebombs and leaflets accusing Chun of
corruption and abuse of power during his seven years in office,
which ended in February. They demanded a full investigation and
punishment.
   Accusations of corruption and embezzlement of funds have been
made against Chun and members of his family since he left office.
The political opposition also claims Chun, a former general put in
power by the army, was responsible for numerous cases of torture
and brutality.
   Radical students accuse Chun; President Roh Tae-woo, a fellow
general who succeeded him; and the United States of responsibility
for military repression of a 1980 civil uprising in the southern
city of Kwangju. Nearly 200 people were killed, according to
government figures.
   Minor clashes were reported Thursday in Taejon, another southern
city, between police and students denouncing the blockade of a
march to the border with communist North Korea.
   Much larger battles occurred Jun 10 when police stopped
thousands of radicals from marching to the border for meetings with
North Korean students on reunifying the peninsula, which was
divided in 1945.
   In another development, Chief Justice Kim Yong-chun of the
Supreme Court said Thursday he would resign in response to calls by
junior magistrates for judicial reform.
   On Wednesday, 85 judges issued a statement saying the judiciary
is seen as subservient to the government and has not benefited from
recent democratic changes. It was the first such collective action
by judges in the nation's history.
   Another 194 judges joined in a supporting statement Thursday and
support for the demand is expected to continue growing among the
940 magistrates in South Korea.
</TEXT>
