<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SouthernPoll     06-16 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Southern Poll,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis and Bush Tied In South, New Poll Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis and Republican George
Bush are running neck-and-neck in the South but the tide could turn
quickly against Dukakis if he selects Jesse Jackson as his running
mate, a poll released Thursday showed.
   Democratic pollster Claibourne Darden Jr. said the survey of 750
voters in nine Southern states found that the Massachusetts
governor and the vice president are in a statistical tie among
traditionally conservative Southern voters. Dukakis was the choice
of 45.1 percent, Bush 42.3 percent and 12.7 percent were undecided.
   The telephone poll was conducted June 8-13 among voters in what
Darden described as the ``hard-core Southern states'' of Virginia,
North Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia, Florida, Alabama,
Mississippi, Louisiana and Tennessee. The margin of error was 3.6
percent.
   ``It's a horse race, but Dukakis is on shaky ground,'' Darden
said.
   Of the people surveyed who said they would vote for Dukakis,
``four of 10 are for Dukakis not because of Dukakis but because
they dislike Bush. ... An `anti' vote early in a campaign is based
on personality, and can leave you very quickly,'' he said.
   Bush, among other things, must ``learn to speak English,'' by
bringing his vocabulary down to earth, Darden said.
   With the two likely nominees running neck-and-neck, the vice
presidential choice becomes critical, Darden said. For Dukakis to
choose Jackson ``would be disastrous in the South,'' the pollster
said.
   Only 25.8 percent said the selection of Jackson for the No. 2
spot would make them more inclined to vote for Dukakis, while 53.1
percent said they would be less inclined to vote Democratic. Some
21.2 percent were undecided.
   ``I think everyone has to be surprised at how well Dukakis is
doing in the South,'' Darden said, but he added that because it is
based largely on an anti-Bush sentiment, ``George Bush, himself, is
doing more to break the Republican `lock' on the South than Michael
Dukakis is doing.''
</TEXT>
