<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MarineGuards-Cuba     06-16 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marine Guards-Cuba,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy, State Department Checking Fratrnization Reports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy and the State Department are
investigating allegations that Marine security guards stationed in
Havana improperly fraternized with Cuban women, officials said
Thursday.
   The investigation focuses on four Marines and their off-duty
social activities and does not involve any allegations of
espionage, the officials said.
   Two years ago, a similiar fraternization scandal erupted
involving Marine guards at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow. One Marine
was convicted of espionage.
   ``Right now, there is no indication of the four of them being
involved in anything except fraternization,'' Lt. Col. John
Shotwell, a Marine Corps spokesman, said of the latest case. ``And
the investigation is still continuing.''
   The Pentagon, in a brief statement, said the four guards ``have
been returned to their parent unit, the Marine Security Guard
Battalion, located at Quantico, Va.,'' pending completion of the
investigation.
   ``Four Marine security guards assigned to the U.S. diplomatic
post in Cuba, the U.S. Interest Section, co-located with the Swiss
embassy, are suspected of fraternization with local civilians in
violation of State Department policy,'' the statement added.
   ``The Naval Security and Investigative Command, in coordination
with the State Department, is conducting a routine investigation of
the matter. Because the matter is under investigation, and no
individuals have been charged with any wrong-doing, it would be
premature to release any details at this time.''
   The State Department and Marine Corps forbid fraternization
between security guards and local women at posts in the Soviet
Union, the Warsaw Pact countries and several other nations,
including communist Cuba.
   According to Pentagon sources, the alleged fraternization among
guards in Cuba included sexual intercourse during several contacts
that occurred late last year and early this year.
   The sources, who agreed to discuss the matter only if not
identified, said the allegations came to light in February when two
Cuban women sought asylum at the Canadian embassy, claiming they
feared arrest for consorting with foreigners. The women had with
them the names of some Marine guards, the officials said.
   Assuming no evidence of espionage is developed, the sources said
the four Marines would probably face only administrative
disciplinary action and not courts-martial.
   According to the Marine Corps, the guard force in Cuba for the
interests section includes one detachment commander and seven
watchstanders.
</TEXT>
