<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AgFunds     06-16 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ag Funds,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Gives Approval to $44.1 Billion Farm Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved a $44.1 billion money bill
for farm programs and food aid Thursday with fewer complaints this
year from urban lawmakers that payment programs have gotten out of
hand.
   ``Everyone's pointing to agriculture like we're the ones who are
causing the deficit, like we're all causing all this international
debt,'' Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la Garza said.
   He said agriculture represented only a small part of the
estimated $176 billion budget deficit for the fiscal year that
starts Oct. 1.
   ``They stumble over that much at the Pentagon,'' the Texas
Democrat said.
   Farm payment programs, which include price supports, income
supports and conservation payments, peaked at $26 billion in 1986.
Those programs now are down to an estimated $17 billion in fiscal
1988.
   The drop in overall farm payments has muted somewhat the chorus
of complaints that met 1985 legislation designed to alleviate
painful problems in the farm economy.
   But while farm payments have gone down as the farm economy has
recovered, a number of critics of ``excesses'' in the farm programs
say there still is much to complain about.
   The House voted 343-54 to approve the money bill amid calls from
farm-bloc lawmakers for aid to growers and livestock producers
squeezed financially by a drought across broad areas of the country.
   The bill earmarked no drought aid, however, and most lawmakers
said they were inclined to go along with administration suggestions
that it would be best to wait until the full extent of the problem
becomes clear.
   The Agriculture Department has been saying an inch or so of rain
once a week for the rest of the growing season would rescue Midwest
corn and soybeans, although wheat in Montana and the Dakotas is in
far worse condition.
   The bill calls for outlays of $44.1 billion for the fiscal 1989
for programs ranging from farm payments to food stamps. That is
$2.5 billion less than requested by President Reagan and $12
billion below last year's amount.
   It also is $3 billion below an agricultural appropriations bill
currently being drawn up in the Senate.
   It contains $16.3 billion for food and nutrition programs, $12.4
billion for rural development and $6.8 billion to replace losses of
the government-owned Commodity Credit Corp., which operates federal
payment programs for farmers.
   Farm program spending has dropped sharply over the last year as
exports expanded and the farm economy shook off the doldrums of the
early 1980s.
   Thus a $14.3 billion decrease in funds to cover losses of the
Commodity Credit Corp. represents the bill's major savings.
Critics, however, said it is optimistic to expect a sale of
government-held stocks will yield $3 billion to help cover
additional losses and hold down costs.
   ``It appears to me there are lots of mirrors on the ceiling and
lots of smoke coming from the cloakroom,'' Rep. Robert S. Walker,
R-Pa., said.
   Rep. Steve Gunderson, R-Wis., said it most likely would be
necessary to come back for a supplemental appropriation later.
   The House debated for two hours a plan by Rep. Joseph J.
DioGuardi, R-N.Y., to bar further Farmers Home Administration loans
to farmers already in default. But farm forces defeated, 310-88, a
parliamentary maneuver designed to bring up his proposal for a vote.
   ``Everybody knows that you don't lend money to people who never
paid you back on you're previous loans,'' DioGuardi said.
``Everybody but the United States of America.''
   Farm state lawmakers were quick to take up DioGuardi's challenge.
   ``This gentleman who comes here from New York and suggests that
the farmers are trying to pull the wool over the Farmers Home
Administration just hasn't been there to share the problems,'' said
Rep. Dick Durbin, D-Ill.
   The Targeted Export Assistance program, established in 1985 as a
subsidy for overseas advertising and promotion of food exports
exports, came under renewed criticism from Rep. Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y.
   ``Even if the program were extremely well run, maybe we ought
not to be funding it,'' he said. He pointed to millions of dollars
paid out to private companies for advertising campaigns abroad.
   Schumer cited a report from the General Accounting Office that
found program mismanagement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1938EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PeaceCorps     06-16 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peace Corps,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Corps Expanding Operations, Director Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Peace Corps is sending volunteers to
Pakistan for the first time in 21 years and will begin a new
program in the Comoros Islands off Africa, agency director Loret
Miller Ruppe said Thursday.
   A Peace Corps assessment team will also go to China this summer,
to plan for the first set of volunteers for that country, Mrs.
Ruppe told a luncheon audience at the National Press Club.
   The three new programs will bring to nearly 70 the number of
countries welcoming the Peace Corps, and Mrs. Ruppe said the
grass-roots agency hopes to grow even bigger.
   ``Those cynics who wonder if the Peace Corps is still around
should know that the Congress and the president have not only
endorsed, but mandated, a five-year growth plan for the Peace Corps
to double in size to 10,000 volunteers by 1992,'' she said.
   The agency, whose last program in Pakistan ended in 1967, is
sending eight volunteers to Islamabad and Lahore this fall to train
high school teachers. The emphasis will be on training English
teachers, but education courses for biology, chemistry and physics
instructors also will be given.
   Nine volunteers will be assigned to the Comoros Islands, an
Islamic nation 250 miles off the coast of Mozambique. They will
arrive in July for language and cultural training and begin working
in September, Mrs. Ruppe said.
   The China program is scheduled to begin sometime next year.
   Since Chinese Foreign Minister Wu Xueqian's announcement in
March that China would welcome the Peace Corps, the agency has
received 300 public queries from Americans declaring their
eagerness to participate in the Chinese program, said agency
spokesman James C. Flanigan.
   ``That's a fairly good number of people expressing an interest
in going to a particular country,'' Flanigan said. The Peace Corps
never guarantees a volunteer's choice of country, but Flanigan said
the agency was bouyed by the interest shown in China.
   At the time of Wu's announcement, officials said an
English-teaching program would be the most likely plan and that the
initial complement would be about 50 volunteers. The assessment
team will discuss the location of the first group.
   ``It's very much their call,'' Mrs. Ruppe said of the Chinese.
   The Peace Corps was created during the Kennedy administration to
spread skills to the grass roots of developing countries and
broaden the horizons of young Americans. Despite conservative
hostility to the agency at the outset of the Reagan administration,
it has grown in the past seven years.
   The Peace Corps gets 200,000 queries a year from potential
volunteers, of whom 17,000 fill out applications and 2,600 are
accepted. Currently, the agency is particularly interested in
people with skills as teacher trainers and agriculture experts,
Mrs. Ruppe said.
   In its expansion plans, the agency will try to increase the size
of some of its contingents and try to get more nations to accept
volunteers. During its heyday, the agency's biggest program was in
India, where up to 1,600 volunteers served. The biggest one is now
in Honduras, where there are 300 Peace Corps people.
   South America would be a fertile ground for new programs, Mrs.
Ruppe said. On that continent, only Paraguay and Ecuador accept
volunteers, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
