<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1539EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BusinessInventories     06-16 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Business Inventories,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Inventories Up in April as Sales Slow</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose moderately as sales
slackened in April, the government said Thursday in a report
signaling slower economic growth for the second quarter.
   The Commerce Department said inventories climbed 0.5 percent to
a seasonally adjusted $723.7 billion in April. The gain came as
total business sales fell 0.2 percent to a seasonally adjusted
$478.8 billion.
   The rise in goods stockpiled on shelves and backlots followed a
0.3 percent climb in March and a 0.4 percent increase in February.
The slight drop in business sales came after a 1.9 percent jump in
March, the largest in more than a year, and a 1.1 percent gain in
February.
   Economists generally take rising inventories as a sign that
buying demand is slowing and as an indication that manufacturers
may have to cut back production.
   Lawrence Chimerine, chairman of the Wefa Group, an economic
forecasting service in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., said April inventory
growth was ``slightly disturbing'' and would be ``a real source of
concern'' if it continued.
   But he said he expected smaller growth in the months ahead and
did not foresee a return to the high rate of inventory expansion
from October to January, when monthly increases ranged from 0.7
percent to 1.2 percent.
   David Jones, an economist with Aubrey G. Lanston & Co., a
goverment securities dealer in New York, said slower growth in the
economy as a whole, as measured by the gross national product, may
be a ``blessing in disguise.''
   ``The inventory numbers certainly signal the likelihood we'll
grow at a slower pace. Maybe GNP will hit 2.5 percent in the second
quarter, compared with 3.9 percent in the first quarter,'' Jones
said.
   ``But that may be desireable because it could well make it
possible to maintain more sustained growth without a sharp
acceleration of inflationary pressure,'' he said.
   Inventories in April were 7.9 percent higher than a year ago,
while sales were 7.6 percent greater.
   The rise in April inventories included a 0.9 percent increase at
the wholesale level, a 0.4 percent rise in goods held by
manufacturers and a 0.3 percent growth at the retail level.
   The 0.2 percent decline in business sales was paced by 0.4
percent drops in both wholesale and retail sales. Sales by
manufacturers were unchanged.
   In an advance report on Wednesday, the government said retail
sales edged up only 0.1 percent in May.
   The combination of falling sales and moderately rising
inventories pushed the inventory-to-sales ratio up from 1.50 in
March to 1.51 in April. That means it would take 1.51 months to
exhaust inventories at the April sales pace, a ratio not considered
abnormally high.
</TEXT>
