<1ST_LINE>r w AM-OSHA-Construction     06-16 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OSHA-Construction,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Propose Tightening OSHA Regulations In Wake Of Apartment
Collapse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers who say the Occupational Safety and
Health Adminstration has taken little action to prevent
construction accidents such as last year's collapse of a
Connecticut apartment complex that killed 28 workers on Thursday
proposed tightening federal laws regulating construction.
   The legislation would stiffen OSHA fines, tighten accident
reporting requirements, mandate a professional engineer to oversee
construction projects, make negligent employers liable to stiff
prison terms and give the agency authority to shut down a work site
to investigate an accident.
   Connecticut lawmakers drafted the measure following House and
Senate hearings examining the April 23, 1987, collapse of
L'Ambiance Plaza, a half-built apartment complex in Bridgeport,
Conn. L'Ambiance Plaza was the worst construction accident in New
England history.
   ``It has been more than a year since L'Ambiance collapsed,''
said Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., the chief House spnosor.
``Tragically, we have seen little movement to change any of the
factors that contributed to the accident.''
   Shays said he hoped the bill would ``arm OSHA with the proper
tools to help fulfill its mandate to protect worker health and
safety.''
   Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr., R-Conn., the chief sponsor in the
Senate, said the country ``must not tolerate any more Willow
Islands or L'Ambiance Plazas or any of the thousands of other
accidents that claim lives and futures and could be avoided if
industry and government act swiftly and responsibly.''
   L'Ambiance Plaza was the nation's worst construction accident
since a cooling tower under construction in Willow Island, W. Va.,
collapsed in 1978, killing 51.
   The Shays-Weicker bill:
   _ Requires an onsite engineer or architect to oversee
construction projects.
   _ Increases maximum OSHA construction fines from $10,000 per
violation to $25,000.
   _ Increases maximum criminal penalties for first-time ``willful
violations'' from six months in prison and $10,000 in fines to 10
years in prison and $250,000 in fines. Repeat offenders would be
subject to 20 years in prison and $500,000 in fines.
   _ Gives OSHA officials the authority to close down a work site
to investigate an accident.
   _ Mandates employers to report accidents and for OSHA officials
to inspect within 24 hours when there are at least three workers
hospitalized, one ``life-threatening'' injury or fatality or a
collapse, partial collapse or near collapse of a building.
   Under current OSHA regulations, contractors are required to
report an accident only if a worker is killed or at least five are
seriously injured, and there is no mandate for OSHA inspections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
