<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 2043EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-VicePresidents     06-16 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vice Presidents,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Task Force: Make Careful Vice Presidential Choices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidates should thoroughly
evaluate their running mates and not make hasty decisions for the
occupant of the office a heartbeak away from the White House,
political experts said Thursday.
   ``The speed with which vice presidential candidates are selected
can still create serious problems,'' according to a report prepared
by a task force that included former top aides to Presidents
Kennedy, Johnson, Nixon, Ford and Carter.
   The report, commissioned by the 20th Century Fund, a non-profit
research organization, said the position of vice president, long
the butt of jokes, is critical because it is so close to the Oval
Office.
   To ensure the best person gets the nod, presidential candidates
could use a mix of tools: questionnaires, interviews, polls and
informal inquiries. In the end, however, politics plays a big role
in the selection.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Vice President George
Bush, respectively the expected 1988 Democratic and Republican
presidential nominees, have not revealed their choice of running
mate, but the issue is attracting widespread attention.
   James Cannon, a former aide to Ford, recalled that Sen. Bob
Dole, R-Kan., was a compromise vice presidential candidate in 1976.
   Although Ford maintains Dole was an asset, others viewed Dole as
``not a good candidate.'' Ford lost the election to Jimmy Carter.
   ``All too often you end up making the decision at 2 a.m.,''
Cannon said.
   Hugh Heclo, a professor at George Mason University in Fairfax,
Va., criticized the selection process.
   He said vice presidential candidates William Miller in 1964;
Thomas Eagleton in 1972; Spiro Agnew in 1968 and Geraldine Ferraro
in 1984 were not ``shining successes of finding what the Founding
Fathers used to call the continental character.''
   Agnew, the only one of those candidates elected, was forced out
of office in a corruption scandal.
   On balance, the experts said the vice presidency is a healthy if
imperfect institution in which the incumbent can play a role
advising the president on a range of issues and representing the
United States abroad.
   But Helco and two other panel members, Arthur M. Schlesinger
Jr., Kennedy's former aide, and Henry F. Reuss, former chairman of
the Joint Economic Committee, suggested the vice presidency does
more harm than good and should be abolished.
   ``All you are trying to do is create some stand-by equipment,''
said Heclo, who argued that a special election could be held to
choose a successor to a disabled president.
   Reuss criticized the ``imperial nature'' of the vice presidency,
which comes with a mansion, a seal and its own aircraft, Air Force
Two. The vice president also has a large staff.
   ``The modern vice presidency that has developed with little
forethought over the past 30 years is proving a more disruptive
than constructive feature of our political system,'' the dissenters
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0143 </DOCNO>
