<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0659 06-16 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,0795</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldier Wounded by Gunfire; Army Clamps Curfew on Nablus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 1 graf after 2nd graf pvs, ``The army...'' to UPDATE
with homes of firebomb throwers destroyed. Pickup 3rd graf pvs,
``Elsewhere in...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An assailant shot and wounded
an Israeli soldier here Thursday, and troops rounded up dozens of
Arabs for questioning. One witness said suspects were forced to
stand on one foot under the hot sun.
   The army clamped a curfew on Nablus, the West Bank's largest
city. It was the second shooting of an Israeli soldier since the
Arab uprising against Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip began Dec. 8.
   In a crackdown on the recent wave of firebomb attacks on Israeli
targets, troops demolished seven houses of Arab suspects and sealed
five other homes in the West Bank. Soldiers have been ordered to
shoot at firebomb throwers with the intent to injure and to
demolish the homes of suspects.
   Elsewhere in the West Bank, dozens of Jewish settlers, some
wearing prayer shawls, blocked a major highway for two hours to
demand harsh army action against Palestinian firebombers.
   The army said the reserve soldier was traveling in his own car
when he was hit by a bullet. A spokesman declined to say if the
soldier was in uniform.
   The wounded soldier was taken by helicopter to a Tel Aviv
hospital and the shooting was being investigated, the spokesman
said. He said the soldier was slightly injured, but refused to
elaborate or identify him.
   The other Israeli soldier shot during the uprising, Sgt. Moshe
Katz, 28, died of a head wound received in the West Bank town of
Bethlehem on March 20.
   Troops conducted a search for suspects and the weapon, sealing
off Nablus and prohibiting all drivers except Jewish settlers who
live nearby from entering or leaving the city. Nablus is 40 miles
north of Jerusalem.
   Four hours after the shooting, about 60 cars were lined up
outside Nablus and an equal number were lined up inside the city
waiting to pass a roadblock manned by three jeeploads of troops.
   A United Nations vehicle, a car belonging to the Red Cross and
an Arab ambulance were turned back.
   Arab witnesses said troops rounded up dozens of Palestinians,
confiscated their identity cards and fired shots in the air.
   ``It seems the army is very angry because this is the first time
I've seen them this strict. They are shooting in the air like
crazy,'' said Nablus businessman Said Kenaan.
   Abu Islam Deedi, an Arab reporter who lives in Nablus, said
troops detained about 50 suspects and lined them up against walls.
   During questioning under the hot summer sun, the Arabs were made
to stand on one leg with their arms outstretched, said Deedi, who
said he watched the roundup from a window in his home.
   Deedi said troops also wired off streets where the shooting
occurred and erected about 10 roadblocks in the city center where
they stopped and searched Palestinian cars. He said several
busloads of troops patrolled the streets.
   According to army figures, 346 soldiers have been injured since
the uprising began, most of them by stones. The United Nations puts
the Palestinian death toll at 208. Two Israelis also have been
killed.
   Underground leaders of the uprising ordered Palestinians to
observe Thursday as a day for stockpiling food, first aid supplies
and gasoline to prolong their resistance to Israel's 21-year
occupation.
   Arabs from a bus stalled at the roadblock descended and began
throwing rocks at the settlers, who responded by hurling them back,
Israel radio and a Jewish settler said. The army fired in the air
to disperse the stone-throwers, then dismantled the roadblock.
   About 60 Jewish settlers from the West Bank settlement of Efrat,
meanwhile, used their cars to block the major Jerusalem-Hebron
highway used by thousands of Arab workers to get to their jobs in
Israel.
   The settlers said in a statement the action was to protest an
increase in Palestinian firebomb attacks. The army responded to the
stepped up attacks by orders this week to shoot firebombers.
   Also Thursday, a 17-year-old Palestinian prostitute was charged
in a Jerusalem district court with the shooting death of a Jewish
seminary student earlier this month. The charge sheet alleges
nationalistic motives.
   A military court sentenced four Palestinians convicted of
throwing firebombs. Three were sentenced to 10 years in prison for
hurling a homemade gasoline bomb at a civilian car Jan. 31 in
Jerusalem. The fourth was given eight years for throwing a firebomb
at a military jeep in Jerusalem on Feb. 26.
</TEXT>
