<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Piscopo     06-16 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Piscopo,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tastes Great, Less Filling, Big Trouble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Call them big, call them hefty _ hey, call 'em
huge _ but don't say the Fat Boys, those high-calorie rappers,
drink Miller Lite beer.
   The three beefy bandmates charged in a federal lawsuit this week
that the Miller Brewing Co. intimated just that in one of its Lite
commercials _ the one where an immense Joe ``Rapping Fats'' Piscopo
raps that the ``less-filling'' brew ``tastes great.''
   The suit says Piscopo's obese appearance and rapping have left a
bad taste in the Fat Boys' mouths _ one that the comic, the beer
company and its ad agency should pay $5 million to remove.
   ``In their efforts to promote the sale of alcohol, Miller
intentionally selected and exploited the likenesses and performing
musical styles of the Fat Boys,'' the suit filed Monday charged.
   The portly plaintiffs are Mark Morales (better known as ``Prince
Markie Dee''), Damon Wimbley (aka ``Kool Rock Ski'') and Darren
Robinson (``The Human Beat Box''), along with the group's record
company and music publisher. They're asking for $5 million in
damages and withdrawal of the commercial.
   They allege the ad, which features Piscopo rolling around on a
huge bogus belly while rapping with three heavyweight partners,
takes advantage of their platinum-selling record success and
infringes on the Fat Boys trademark.
   That's right. The Fat Boys received Registration No. 1,351,054
from the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office for their name on July
23, 1985.
   ``The weight of the members _ their actual physical size _
combined with other elements of music, costume and performance
style constitutes an identifiable and unique characteristic of the
group,'' the lawsuit said.
   It also alleges the commercial's music, particularly the vocal
percussion of one rotund performer behind Piscopo, ``contains a
melody copied from (and) derived from'' the Fat Boys' music.
   A spokesman for the comedian, Glen Schwartz, had no immediate
comment on the suit. The ad agency, Backer & Spielvogel Inc. of
Manhattan, declined comment; a Miller spokesman was not in the
company's Wisconsin headquarters to react to the suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
