<DOCNO> AP880616-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1628EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-Rivers Bjt   06-16 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Rivers, Bjt,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Takes Toll on Nation's Rivers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A drought parching much of the country dropped water levels in
the Mississippi and Ohio rivers, making the waterways unnavigable
Thursday and meaning ``major-league'' losses for the inland
shipping industry.
   A seven-mile stretch of the Ohio River near Mound City, Ill.,
remained closed to all traffic while a dredge deepened a shallow
channel. Dozens of towboats and barges were stranded.
   Meanwhile, nearly 700 barges in the Mississippi River were tied
up north and south of the Greenville, Miss., bridge because the
river had dropped to the lowest levels since authorities began
keeping records in 1872.
   ``Everybody is concerned,'' said Chris Brinkop of the Ohio River
Ice Committee. The group comprises industry, U.S. Coast Guard and
Army Corps of Engineers officials who monitor river conditions.
   ``We've experienced tough river conditions and closures before,
but nothing this bad,'' said Brinkop. He said the industry is
losing ``major-league dollars'' because of the traffic stoppage.
   Towboat crews stranded on the Mississippi and Ohio rivers spent
their time painting, watching television, doing light maintenance
and even fishing while each towboat owner loses about $10,000 daily.
   Chuck Shumann of the Army Corps of Engineers in Louisville, Ky.,
said a 300-foot stretch of the Ohio River north of Cairo had water
levels of about eight feet _ the lowest mark there since January
1969.
   For safe passage, he said barges need at least 8.11 feet of
water.
   The Coast Guard in Paducah, Ky., closed the river. It was to
reopen Thursday night, but underground cables and debris forced a
delay until Friday afternoon.
   In the past two weeks, more than a dozen barges have gone
aground near the Mound City area, said Guard spokesman Jack Buri.
The dredge Elco was summoned to dig a 2,100-foot channel 11 feet
deep by 250 feet wide, he said.
   Low water in the Mississippi has created bottlenecks in places
like Vaucluse Landing, Ark., about three miles north of the
Greenville, Miss., bridge.
   An Army Corps of Engineers patrol boat has been escorting barges
with light loads one-by-one, and prospects for ending the
bottleneck north of Greenville brightened Thursday.
   Spokesman Michael Logue in Vicksburg, Miss., said the Corps
marked a previously unknown secondary channel at Greenville. He
said it appeared smaller towboats would be able to use it.
   ``Since we found the secondary channel, it looks like the small
tows will be able to go ahead and pass,'' Logue said. ``The larger
tows will have to wait.''
   Authorities said it would take at least a day and possibly two
to dredge a channel 16-feet to 20-feet deep that could handle
larger barges.
   On board the stranded towboats, crews made the best of it.
   ``There's plenty of work, there's always something to do,'' said
Steve Southern of Paducah, Ky., a first mate on the John M.
Donnelly on the Mississippi. ``Some people are even trying to
fish.''
   Idle barges also worried shippers like James Crafton, executive
vice president of Home Oil Co. of Henderson, Ky. He depends on
barges to deliver his petroleum products.
   ``Our last shipment was delayed about a day,'' he said. ``The
river conditions concern me. Like everyone else, I'm hoping for
some rainfall.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
