<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Science     06-16 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Science,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Urges No Cuts in Science, Technology Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan urged Congress on Thursday to
approve full funding of science, space and technology programs
despite efforts to balance the federal budget.
   In a letter to key lawmakers, Reagan said the bipartisan budget
agreement reached by the administration and Congress in November
was designed to ``put the federal government firmly on the path
toward elimination of the budget deficit.''
   ``Achievement of that critically important objective requires
those in office to make difficult choices among competing
priorities,'' he said.
   ``We have considered the full range of federal programs and
their competing demands on scarce taxpayers' dollars and have
concluded that full funding of science, space and technology
programs must remain a top priority.''
   ``I urge the Congress to provide full funding and support for
these programs,''the president said.
   Reagan's letter was addressed to Sens. William Proxmire, D-Wis.,
and Jake Garn, R-Utah, and Reps. Edward P. Boland, D-Mass., and
Bill Green, R-N.Y., the chairmen and ranking minority members,
respectively, of the Senate and and House appropriations
subcommittees that will review science and technology expenditures.
