<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-16 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can't get a ticket for running a red
light in Carroll County. There are none.
   The county's last traffic signal was turned off this month when
Avenue Elementary School closed.
   There are fewer than 19,000 residents over 600 square miles in
the county in the northwest Illinois. The Missisippi River town of
Savanna, with 4,500 residents, had the last traffic light.
   ``It was green all the time unless somebody pushed the button on
it,'' Comptroller Corrine Myers said.
   The signal was installed near the school to control traffic when
children and school employees crossed the street, Superintendent
Max Pierson said.
   The county will be free of red lights through at least 1989, but
a traffic signal will be erected in Savanna when a bridge
construction project is finished.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Cooley says it was in the stars
that he should be honored as the 50 millionth person to ride the
city's public transportation system.
   His horoscope predicted he had a chance to win a contest.
   ``Do you realize what the odds are _ 50 million to one?'' Cooley
said Wednesday. ``I should be so lucky when I play the lottery.''
   On Tuesday morning, after a dispatcher alerted drivers that the
50 millionth rider was about to board a bus, drivers handed out a
registration form to the next passenger to get on or off their bus.
   Cooley's form was drawn from the 36 returned.
   Before the drawing Wednesday, Cooley said his wife, Virginia,
telephoned him at work and read the horoscope for Virgo: ``Lunar
position accents popularity, ability to persuade, valid chance to
win contest.''
   ``I got the biggest bang out of that,'' Cooley said. ``I said,
`Well, Mrs. Reagan and I, we read them.' I don't really take it too
seriously.''
   Cooley, 61, will receive a two-night vacation for four in Pigeon
Forge, Tenn., a resort area near Great Smoky Mountains National
Park, a free bus pass for a year and other prizes.
</TEXT>
