<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ArmsSales     06-16 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Sales,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon OKs F-16 Fighter Sale To Bahrain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon notified Congress on Thursday it
had approved a sale of F-16 jet fighters to Bahrain and artillery
radar units to Pakistan.
   Assuming there are no congressional objections, the Pentagon
said it planned to sell four new F-16 fighters and associated spare
parts to Bahrain for about $90 million.
   Bahrain had previously purchased 12 of the fighters ``and
therefore will have no difficulty absorbing these same model
aircraft into its armed forces,'' the Pentagon said.
   The Pentagon said the U.S. Air Force would oversee the
transaction with Bahrain and the General Dynamics Corp. would serve
as the prime contractor.
   As for Pakistan, the Pentagon said it planned to sell that
country five Firefinder radar sets, which are used to fix the
locations of enemy artillery and mortars. That deal is worth an
estimated $31 million.
   The U.S. Army will oversee the transaction and the Hughes
Aircraft Corp. of Fullerton, Calif., will serve as the prime
contractor.
</TEXT>
