<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BackpackCocaine     06-16 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Backpack Cocaine,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Whose Daughter Brought Cocaine to School Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian woman whose 7-year-old daughter
brought a lump of cocaine to school in her backpack this week was
arrested on a federal warrant Thursday when she came to court to
regain custody of her children.
   Maria Cristina Torres was arrested by a U.S. marshal when she
appeared in Commissioner Jack Gold's court, where she sought the
return of the girl and her 5-year-old son.
   The daughter and eight classmates at Canoga Park Lutheran School
tasted the lump of cocaine on Monday but none suffered any lasting
ill effects.
   The no-bail warrant was issued Wednesday by U.S. District Judge
A. Andrew Hauk after Ms. Torres was found to be on probation in
another case in which she tried to carry thousands of dollars out
of the country without reporting it.
   Ms. Torres, 39, was arrested Monday for investigation of child
endangerment and released on $100,000 bail. She was freed before
her probationary status was discovered.
   Ms. Torres was arrested March 18, 1985, when she tried to take
$146,257 in cash aboard a Canada-bound flight. She told inspectors
she was carrying $3,000. Cash over $5,000 must be reported.
   She pleaded guilty to failing to report currency and giving a
false statement to a government agency. On June 17, 1985, she was
placed on five years' probation.
</TEXT>
