<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Estonia     06-16 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Estonia,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Estonian Party Leader Is Replaced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party chief in strongly
nationalistic Estonia was relieved of his job Thursday and replaced
by the current Soviet ambassador to Nicaragua, Vajno I. Vaelaes,
the Tass news agency said.
   It was not clear from the brief Tass dispatch whether Karl G.
Vayno's departure came because of a fall from political favor.
   Vayno's leaving marked the third change in republic-level party
leaders in less than a month. On May 21, the party chiefs in
Armenia and Azerbaijan were replaced as the simmering territorial
dispute over the Nagorno-Karabakh region continued.
   Vayno, 65, had been party boss in the Soviet republic on the
Baltic Sea since July 1978. Tass said his departure was approved at
a meeting Thursday of the Estonian party's Central Committee.
   Under Vayno's guidance, Estonia became a testing ground for many
of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's economic reform policies.
   However, Vayno's leadership came under strong criticism at an
April meeting of Estonian writers, filmmakers and other cultural
workers, who complained of ecological problems, corruption and the
functionings of Estonia's government.
   Estonian nationalism has been strong since the formerly
independent Baltic land was forcibly incorporated into the Soviet
Union in 1940. This nationalism continued during Vayno's tenure in
the Switzerland-sized jurisdiction.
   Tass said Vanjo was relieved ``in connection with a transfer
under the jurisdiction'' of the Moscow-based Central Committee, the
party's policy-making body. The Committee could assign him to a job
in Moscow or elsewhere in the Soviet Union.
   His replacement, Vaelaes, 57, served earlier as a secretary of
the Estonian party.
   In a separate biographical note, Tass indicated the choice of
Vaelaes was not unanimous, saying he received ``the majority of the
votes'' from Estonia's Central Committee. Such decisions are
usually unanimous.
   Vaelaes began his political career in Tartu, Estonia, where he
was elected head of the city's Komsomol _ young Communist league _
after graduating from Tartu University, Tass said.
   He went on to lead the party organization in Tallinn, Estonia's
capital, for 10 years, and then was elected a party secretary for
the republic-wide party apparatus.
   He joined the diplomatic corps in 1980, and served as Soviet
ambassador to Venezuela, Trinidad and Tobago and Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
