<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSLaws     06-16 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Laws,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laws Preserving AIDS Confidentiality Limited, Professor Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laws protecting confidentiality for AIDS patients
are less effective than those aimed at preventing discrimination in
areas such as jobs and housing, a law professor writes in a leading
medical publication.
   When it comes to AIDS infection, legal protection of medical
confidence is often an illusion, said Professor Bernard M. Dickens
of the University of Toronto in Ontario.
   ``While some laws appear to require and provide secrecy of
medical data, others compel disclosures,'' he wrote in Friday's
Journal of the American Medical Association.
   He cited examples in non-AIDS cases in which courts have ruled
that public policies favoring confidentiality must yield when it is
necessary to prevent danger to others.
   ``The protection privilege ends where the public peril begins,''
he said, quoting a California Supreme Court decision concerning the
appropriateness of warning a person believed to be in danger of
attack from a mental health patient.
   In general, high legal principles exist to justify the breaking
of some medical confidences, regardless of laws to preserve those
confidences, Dickens wrote.
   An example, he said, would be a spouse's right to know if her
mate is infected with the AIDS virus, because the information
pertains to a risk to her life, he wrote.
   If potential victims can't be identified, disclosing the names
of people with AIDS-related conditions to health authorities might
be legally justifiable even if it isn't specifically required by
law, according to the article.
   Currently, all 50 states require that diagnoses of AIDS be
reported to health authorities, he said. Some states require the
names of people diagnosed with the disease be reported. A number of
states mandate reporting of every laboratory test that indicates
infection is present, Dickens said.
   AIDS, a fatal and incurable viral illness, is believed to be
passed mainly through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic needles
and from infected mothers to their infants before or during birth.
   The disease has struck more than 64,000 people in this country
since 1979 and killed more than 36,000 of them, according to the
national Centers for Disease Control.
   Laboratory tests for AIDS infection do not indicate whether a
person has the disease, but only if the virus that causes it has
entered his system. It can be years between infection and the
appearance of symptoms.
   Dickens said that rather than beefing up laws protecting
confidentiality, it makes more sense to reinforce laws prohibiting
discrimination against people with AIDS, with related conditions or
people suspected of being infected.
   He praised a proposal in Congress aimed mainly at curbing
discrimination in areas such as housing, employment, education,
insurance and access to medical care.
   The measure, an amendment to the federal Public Health Service
Act, does not omit guidelines to protect confidentiality, but
couples them with anti-discrimination provisions, he wrote.
   Leonard Graff, legal director for National Gay Rights Advocates
in San Francisco, agreed.
   ``Our position has been is that it is important to have
confidentiality and anti-discrimination laws working in tandem to
protect individuals,'' he said by telephone Thursday. ``And we know
that this works.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
