<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Pay     06-16 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Pay,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Pay Plan Would Bar Legislators From Keeping Honoraria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior House Democrat on Thursday proposed a
new congressional salary system that would prohibit lawmakers from
keeping honoraria earned from making speeches and writing articles.
   Under the legislation, members would select their own salaries
in a range from the current level of $89,500 up to as much as
$135,000, the amount recommended by a presidential pay commission.
   The proposal by Rep. Dan Rostenkowski of Illinois, chairman of
the House Ways and Means Committee, came two days after the House
voted to reject a 4 percent cost-of-living increase for next year.
   ``In being shy about declaring our worth in an honest way, all
we do is demean our office and reinforce the public misimpression
about public service,'' Rostenkowski said in a statement.
   He said that while he defends the current system, which lets
House members accept up to $2,000 per speech up to an annual limit
of 30 percent of their congressional salaries, ``we are well
advised to guard against even the appearance of a conflict of
interest.''
   Rostenkowski is consistently one of the top honoraria-earners in
Congress.
   His proposal would permit lawmakers to choose a salary up to the
last amount recommended by the presidential commission.
   ``Those members with more responsibility or longer tenure would
be free to make a statement of their worth to their constituents
openly and honestly by signing in at the high end of the scale,''
he said.
   The current limit of $3,000 in business-related living expense
tax deductions also would be lifted under Rostenkowski's proposal,
allowing members of Congress to deduct as much as they could
justify to the Internal Revenue Service.
</TEXT>
