<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BallfieldDispute     06-16 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ballfield Dispute,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Leaguers Quitting After Parents Play Basebrawl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Little Leaguers who just wanted
to play ball are quitting after watching their parents brawl and
their coaches threaten to sue each other.
   A smoldering dispute flared into a 20-minute brawl last week
after a championship game, and police were called to break it up.
   ``It's just a bunch of mad parents acting like fools,'' said
Ginger Metcalf, who has three sons on one of the teams.
   Lucille King called the situation unbelievable and said her
12-year-old son Marty has decided to quit the league.
   ``It got to a point where he couldn't even play anymore because
the parents were fighting,'' Mrs. King said. ``They were fighting
with the coaches, the board members were fighting, every game we
had they'd always come up with a different rule.''
   No matter which side the parents take in the controversy, they
agree the infighting is hurting the kids and tarnishing the
league's reputation.
   Fighting erupted Thursday when the A's beat the Mets by a run to
claim the championship.
   A's Coach Reed McMillan said Mets' Coach Steve Isaacs attacked
his son after the game, grabbing him by the neck and shaking him.
   McMillan said he got so angry he tackled Isaacs, and other
parents jumped in.
   Isaacs indicated he was only trying to head off a fight between
the kids. He said his son, Jason, and McMillan's son, Dwane, were
arguing, so he grabbed Dwane by the shirt. Then McMillan pounced on
him from behind, he said.
   Both coaches retained lawyers and are considering suits.
   McMillan and some other parents claim the league is not being
run by Little League rules and was dominated by President Karl
Cummings who made his own rules and changed them frequently.
   But Isaacs says the problem is McMillan.
   Cummings and parents supporting Isaacs maintain the problems
began when McMillan started coaching this year.
   ``Things were more touchy. Things were more on edge,'' said
Cummings. He called McMillan ``a very competitive type person. I
believed we lost the joy toward the children, and I believe a lot
of parents picked up on that.''
</TEXT>
