<DOCNO> AP880616-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1758EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Philippines     06-16 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Philippines,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says U.S. Won't Pay Philippines Rent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said
Thursday the United States would not get dragged into ``bidding
wars'' for the right to locate American military bases in the
Philippines or anywhere else in the world.
   Asked by Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, whether the United States
should get into ``bidding wars'' for such bases, Shultz told the
Senate Appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations that ``the
concept of rent for bases we have to reject. When we have a base,
it must because it is in the interests of both'' countries.
   Specifically, in the negotiations for extending the leases on
the Clark air base and Subic naval base, ``there are those in the
Philippines who think it is a great asset and they would rent it
out at a staggering sum of money,'' Shultz said.
   ``We've told them we reject that and will go elsewhere. We will
stick to our position, and if we have to find other places for our
ships and planes, we'll do it,'' he added.
   Negotiations are under way between the two countries to renew
the five-year base leases that expire in 1991. Some Filipino
officials have suggested the United States pay more than $1 billion
a year over the current $180 million attached to annual aid for the
two bases.
   Regarding a law under consideration by the Philippine congress
that would ban U.S. nuclear weapons, Shultz said ``nuclear
deterrence is an esential ingredient in keeping the peace.''
   If a host country says U.S. ships are not welcome because they
may be carrying nuclear weapons, ``then we have to part company,''
he said.
   ``Nuclear weapons make some people nervous,'' Shultz said. ``But
they'd be even more nervous if the other side had them and we
didn't.''
   The law has passed the Philippine Senate but is expected to face
opposition in the Philippine House.
   On another issue, Inouye said his committee had received letters
from the Philippines charging that human rights violations there
had increased and that vigilante groups are getting official
government support.
   Shultz replied that he was aware of the proliferaiton of
vigilantes and said the development ``has pluses but also minuses.''
   ``President (Corazon) Aquino has increasingly recognized that
the communist insurgency has to be dealt with with great severity
and firmness. ... So the tendency is to reach out and find
additional strength'' outside the military, he said.
   But Shultz cautioned that ``this is a development everyone must
be weary of.''
</TEXT>
