<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ConventionHotels     06-16 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention Hotels,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hotels Held For Democratic Convention Getting Antsy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Atlanta hotels, concerned that they have
not received names or deposits for rooms reserved for people
attending the Democratic National Convention next month, are
raising the possibility they'll sell the rooms to other customers.
   While none has sold all its reserved rooms for the July 18-21
convention, ``some are contemplating selling their rooms and
function space,'' said Robert King, president of the Georgia
Hospitality & Travel Association. ``They are concerned that they
are not getting the names and they are not getting the money. They
are getting worried.''
   ``I get the feeling they are not organized,'' King said of the
Democratic National Convention Committee and Atlanta '88, the local
organizing committee. ``I was hoping as we got closer to the time
of the convention that things would fall into place.''
   Democraticofficials said they have not provided complete guest
lists to the hotels because some delegates have not been chosen and
some news organizations have not provided the names of their
convention staffs.
   Nearly 19,000 rooms in 107 area hotels have been committed for
the convention.
