<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NuclearBolts     06-16 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Bolts,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Called Slow To Respond To Substandard Bolt Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission was
criticized Thursday for failing to rid nuclear power plants of
substandard nuts, bolts and other fasteners since the problem was
discovered in 1982.
   ``The NRC has dragged its feet and boggled the whole question,''
said Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore. ``You have had since 1982 to think
about this problem and it is now 1988 and you are still thinking
about it.''
   Wyden's comments came at a hearing of the House Energy and
Commerce oversight and investigations subcommittee during which NRC
officials estimated that up to 20 percent of the fasteners in the
nation's nuclear plants may fail to meet specifications.
   ``We expect standards we require for nuclear plants will be
met,'' said Victor Stello, the NRC's executive director for
operations. ``They have not been met. We are not happy.''
   Stello said the NRC was ``not satisfied'' that nuclear power
plant operators had done enough to eliminate substandard bolts and
that the commission was studying ways to ensure compliance,
including barring the use of bolts supplied by manufacturers with a
history of problems.
   The NRC plans to move ``agressively'' against manufacturers who
supply counterfeit fasteners or fraudulently claim their products
meet specifications, Stello said.
   He said the extent of the problem was just now becoming clear.
   In addition, Stello said he would attempt to convene a meeting
involving other federal agencies that also have faced problems
eliminating the use of substandard fasteners in facilities they
oversee.
</TEXT>
