<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Election     06-16 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Election,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Rival Tests Power in Special Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLAHABAD, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Minister V. P. Singh, a
political foe of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, tested his popularity
with voters Thursday by running for Parliament, but the special
elections were marred by violence.
   Six people were injured in clashes in the Allahabad
constituency, where Singh ran on an anti-corruption platform, and
voting was postponed because of ballot-stuffing in one village,
authorities said.
   In another election district, a man was shot and killed and 10
people were injured.
   The contest between Singh, 56, and singer and film writer Sunil
Shastri, 38, of the Gandhi's governing Congress Party, has been
closely watched as a barometer of how Singh would fare against
Gandhi in a national election.
   Election results were not expected before Saturday in the
Singh-Shastri contest.
   The worst violence reported was in Palwal village in the
Faridabad constituency, about 18 miles south of New Delhi, when men
with guns, knives and sticks tried to storm a Congress Party
office, according to dispatches from the United News of India and
the Press Trust of India. It was there that the shooting death
occurred.
   The Allahabad voting was one of seven special elections held
Thursday to fill vacancies in the 544-seat lower house of
Parliament. Elections for all Parliament seats, which will
determine India's next prime minister, must be held no later than
January 1990.
   Singh, a former ally of Gandhi, broke with him last year over
what he saw as government footdragging over investigating alleged
kickbacks in defense contracts.
   Singh ran as an independent with the backing of several
opposition parties against Shastri, son of the late Prime Minister
Lal Bahadur Shastri.
   Voting in Satpura village in Allahabad constituency was
postponed until Friday after unidentified men seized the ballots
and started filling them out, the constituency's top election
official, P.C. Chaturvedi, said.
   Ballot-counting in the entire constituency cannot start until
the Satpura situation is resolved, he said.
   Chaturvedi also said at least six people were hurt when rival
groups of political workers clashed near Naini, 10 miles south of
Allahabad.
   Arun Nehru, a onetime Gandhi ally and former minister of state
for home affairs, who now supports Singh, told a news conference
the Satpura ballot-stuffing was engineered by Congress Party
members.
   ``It was a planned and systematic attempt to rig votes,'' Nehru
said.
   Nehru also said that V..P. Singh's nephew, Vikram Singh, was
shot at and injured by Congress supporters at Manda, 25 miles
southwest of Allahabad. The report could not be confirmed.
   At another news conference, Congress General Secretary Ghulam
Nabi Azad denied Nehru's charges and accused the opposition of
``intimidation and terror tactics.''
   V.P. Singh was an early voter in Allahabad, 360 miles southeast
of New Delhi.
   An estimated 45 percent of the 850,000 eligible voters took part
in the Allahabad election, state governemnt spokesman P.K. Asthana
said.
</TEXT>
