<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LeapfrogRecord     06-16 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Leapfrog Record,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hanover High Students Break Leapfrogging Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid the empty Gatorade bottles, flattened
tubes of sun block and stacks of fetid sweat socks, 14 Hanover High
School students leapfrogged their way into the record books
Thursday.
   Actually, the pace was more like a few steps of jogging, then a
leap. And the 14 _ who were at it on the soccer field in two-hour
shifts, round-the-clock since Friday afternoon _ weren't exactly
bounding with energy.
   But according to the Guinness Book of World Records, that
qualifies as leapfrogging, and at 11:30 a.m. the students
``frogged'' past 662 miles, breaking the record set by a fraternity
at the University of Seattle.
   Thomas Lambert and Steve Bonz, both seniors, made the record
leap.
   ``People ask which hurts more _ the bending or the leaping,''
said Doug North, 17, between swigs of Gatorade. ``It's the jogging
in between.''
   The students, who planned to continue leaping until they reach
888 miles _ estimated to happen sometime Saturday morning _ are
raising money for the Norris Cotton Cancer Center at the
Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center.
   So far, passers-by have donated $2,000, and the students aren't
sure how much they will raise in pledges.
   The students formed four-person teams to frog in shifts of two
hours on, four off. In between, they cheer each other on, eat,
sleep, spray each other down with hoses, soak aching ankles in
coolers of ice and take final exams.
   ``I studied this morning at seven o'clock with flash cards,''
while leaping, said Brendan Creagh, 18. Creagh said the students
are averaging 19 leaping miles a day, most of it in temperatures in
the 90s during the first heat wave of the summer.
   A cluster of tents in one corner of the field, called
``Frogville,'' is home to the leapers, and candles in paper bags
mark the path around the field at night. In one tent are some
instruments and a stereo, upon which the students played the theme
from the film ``Chariots of Fire'' as they broke the record.
   Despite the excitement, most of the leapers are looking forward
to the end.
   ``I have not done it before and I will not do it again,'' North
said.
</TEXT>
