<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1850EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-NorthDakota Bjt   06-16 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-North Dakota, Bjt,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Dakota Farmer Says 1,000 Acres Of His Grain Lost To Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STERLING, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Brown looked across a 30-acre wheat
field Thursday, at shafts of grain barely a foot tall and
shriveling from the prolonged drought that has hit North Dakota
harder than any other state.
   ``The best purpose for this right now is the cows,'' he said,
digging into dirt that was bone dry three inches below the surface.
``What we are trying to do now is get enough grazing to get the
cattle through the summer.''
   Brown's farm, which has received less than an inch of
precipitation since January, normally would be lush and green this
time of year. Instead, his pastures are parched and his grain crops
are wilted.
   Brown figures the 1,000 acres of wheat, oats and barley that he
planted this spring already have been wiped out. ``We are not even
going to start the combine this year from what I can see.''
   North Dakota farmers are selling off cattle, plowing under crops
and filing crop insurance claims while the drought Gov. George
Sinner characterizes as the worst since Dust Bowl days grips the
state from border to border.
   The drought is expected to cost the state 40 percent of its farm
income and seal the fate of many farmers who already were
struggling financially.
   ``We didn't need this,'' said economist Arlen Leholm of North
Dakota State University.
   ``The economy in North Dakota was starting to rebound. We had
crop prices that were starting to rise, not wildly, but mildly.
Livestock prices were pretty decent,'' Leholm said.
   The drought could cost the state's economy at least $2.7
billion, a loss that could throw it into another tailspin, Leholm
said.
   Direct crop losses on wheat, barley and oats will total about
$500 million. Because market prices are higher, producers will also
receive about $400 million less in federal deficiency payments, he
said.
   ``We have got large sections of North Dakota where they are
estimating that 70 percent of the crop is already gone,'' Leholm
said.
   The drought is more widespread than the last one in 1980, Leholm
said. ``The last real wipe-out was in 1961,'' he said.
   If adequate rain doesn't fall by mid-July, the threshhold for
planting later forage crops, another 10 percent of the state's
farmers could be put out of business, he said.
   One crop insurer, Rain and Hail Insurance Services, already has
received about 500 crop damage claims from its 4,500 policy
holders, said Eldon Wollmann, a field supervisor.
   ``They are coming in at about 100 a day lately now. And that's
only going to get worse,'' Wollmann said. ``I would guess that
there would be very few insured we have policies with that would
not be filing some kind of claim.''
   An estimated 40 percent of North Dakota's farmers carry crop
insurance, which basically covers a farmer's cost of production,
officials said.
   ``The way they are looking right now, if we get by paying $7
million to $8 million (in losses), we will be lucky. It could be
double that, easily,'' Wollmann said.
   For Brown, his major struggle right now is trying to find feed
for his 160 head of cattle, a herd his family has been building for
20 years.
   Already, he's sold off 32 cows and some calves for lack of feed.
``I am sure, if things don't change, there will be some more
going.''
   His alfalfa fields are brown, except for low spots that might
yield some bales of hay if it rains, he said. Brown intends to
maintain at least 100 cows, which could force him to ship the cows
elsewhere, perhaps Nebraska, for feeding this winter, he said.
   Weather forecasts are so depressing Brown has quit listening to
them.
   What he would have heard Thursday was a prediction of
temperatures in the 90s and high winds.
   ``You watch the sky and hope. That's about it,'' Brown said.
</TEXT>
