<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica 2ndLd-Writethru a0733 06-16 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0733,0812</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blacks Boycott Jobs To Mark `76 Soweto Riots</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 4 grafs to include man blowing himself up; Raises
grafs 18-20 `Some trains ... three blacks.'; PICKS up 3rd graf pvs
`Police said' with some editing thereafter to TRIM. SUBS 21st graf
`Mining executives' with 1 graf to include day of week for
transition. PICKS up 22nd graf pvs bgng, The biggest...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks took a self-proclaimed
national holiday Thursday, boycotting jobs and praying at churches
to commemorate the 1976 Soweto riots that set off months of
violence.
   Two bombings were reported in Cape Town and police said a
guerrilla blew himself up accidentally.
   The first bomb wrecked part of a commuter rail line in the
city's black township of Langa and the second went off in the lobby
of a civic center during a meeting of the far-right Conservative
Party, causing damage but no injuries.
   Reports said some trains from Soweto to Johannesburg were stoned
and passengers had to lie on the floor. Firebombs were thrown at
buses and delivery vans in other townships, causing serious
injuries to three blacks.
   Police said the African National Congress, the main guerrilla
movement fighting white domination, had planned a major offensive
to coincide with the anniversary but was at least partially
thwarted.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok said 11 suspected guerrillas
had been killed in the past week.
   One was killed Thursday near Cape Town by explosives he was
carrying, another blew himself up Tuesday and nine, including three
women, were killed by police in two shootouts near the Swaziland
border, Vlok said.
   The state-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said police were
tipped off that guerrillas based in Mozambique would try to enter
South Africa through Swaziland for ``massive acts of terrorism''
Thursday. In each of the two shootouts, it said, police stopped
vehicles at roadblocks and riddled them with bullets after someone
inside opened fire.
   The African National Congress issued a statement from its
headquarters in Zambia paying homage to blacks killed in Soweto 12
years ago and pledging to ``escalate our political and military
offensive.''
   Many blacks have regarded June 16 as a holiday since 1976, when
nationwide rioting broke out after police fired on a student march
in Soweto, Johannesburg's main black township.
   At least 575 blacks were killed in the ensuing months, when the
anti-apartheid movement acquired a new militancy.
   No official holidays mark events of specific significance to the
26-million black majority, but several black unions have negotiated
with employers to have June 16 as a day off.
   Many factories closed Thursday, and the largest daily newspaper
for blacks, The Sowetan, did not publish. Workers at three diamond
mines struck to demand that their employer, De Beers, join other
companies in making the day a paid holiday.
   Commemorative church services were held in several black
townships. Reports said security forces fired tear gas and bird
shot because of stone-throwing that occurred as blacks left a
church service in Lamontville, outside Durban.
   About 15 people gathered at Soweto's Avalon Cemetery at the
grave of Hector Pieterson, a 13-year-old shot by police during the
march in 1976.
   Pieterson's sister, Margot, 17, and his nephew, Hector Tabane,
6, put flowers on the grave, which bears a marker saying: ``Deeply
mourned by his parents, sisters, and a nation that remembers.''
Popi Buthelezi, 29, wounded in the 1976 shootings, came to the
service in a wheelchair.
   Later, 1,500 people attended a service at Soweto's largest Roman
Catholic Church. At one point, two white men in civilian clothes
were chased by members of the crowd who thought they were policemen
and grabbed cameras they were carrying. The crowd dispersed hastily
after the service with many policemen looking on.
   The Soweto students 12 years ago had been protesting a range of
grievances, particularly the use of Afrikaans in their schools.
   In July 1976, the government announced that black schools could
choose their language of instruction but activists say most other
demands, generally related to giving black communities more control
over their schools, have not been met.
   Mining executives said 24,500 of 540,000 black employees at
major mines were absent Thursday.
   The biggest stayaway was at General Mining Union Corp.'s Kinross
gold mine, where 86 percent of black workers were absent. Kinross
was the site of the nation's worst gold mine disaster when 177 men,
all but five of them black, died in a fire in 1986.
   Public Utility Transport Co., which carries hundreds of
thousands of black commuters from their townships, reported a 90-95
percent stayaway in the Johannesburg area, 50-80 percent in
Pretoria and about 30 percent in Durban. Many stores in downtown
Johannesburg because black employees were absent.
</TEXT>
