<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NBC-JournalPoll     06-16 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NBC-Journal Poll,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC-Journal Poll Finds 15-Point Dukakis Lead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Michael
Dukakis held a 15-point lead over Republican George Bush in an NBC
News-Wall Street Journal poll released Thursday, largely on the
strength of overwhelming support for Dukakis among women.
   Dukakis was supported by 49 percent of the registered voters in
the poll, to 34 percent for Bush, NBC News reported. Among men the
split was 46-40 for Dukakis, but among women his margin was 52-28.
   The national survey of 2,014 adults was conducted June 9-12. Its
result was similar to that of a Gallup poll, conducted June 10-12,
that found a 14-point Dukakis lead. Two other polls early in June
put his lead in single digits; others in May had Dukakis' lead as
great as 16 points.
   The ``gender gap'' facing Bush also appeared in an ABC
News-Washington Post poll last month, which suggested he trailed
Dukakis narrowly among men but by a 2-1 margin among women. In
another measure, the NBC-Journal poll Thursday found that only 38
percent of women said Bush cares about people like them.
   In another important measure of voter sentiment, poll
respondents said by a 2-1 margin that it is time for the nation to
change direction rather than to follow the course set by President
Reagan. And while 49 percent approved of the job Reagan has been
doing as president, 39 percent disapproved.
   Respondents disapproved, 48 percent to 41 percent, of the Reagan
administration's handling of the nation's illegal drug problem _ an
issue in which Bush has taken a prominent role.
   Dukakis was rated higher than Bush on handling the nation's
economic problems, reducing the federal deficit and dealing with
drugs. Bush was rated higher on defense and foreign policy.
   The margin of sampling error in the telephone survey was three
percentage points.
</TEXT>
