<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MechamProfile     06-16 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham Profile,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor Still An Outsider</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mecham</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evan Mecham's tumultuous ride as governor
of Arizona ruined his business and landed him in two courts. But it
left him the same man as when he started: a political outsider
railing at the system that refused to work in his favor.
   Eighteen months ago the outspoken Republican was at the top, a
prosperous automobile dealer who had finally won the chance to
govern his state after five tries for the office.
   Now the governorship and the auto business are gone, one lost
when he was convicted by the Arizona Senate in an impeachment
trial, the other sold because business was lagging under the weight
of bad publicity.
   Now another critical chapter has been closed: Mecham and his
brother, Willard, were acquitted Thursday of criminal charges
related to the alleged concealment of a campaign loan.
   The 64-year-old ex-governor had faced six felony counts and up
to 22 years in prison on charges of hiding a $350,000 campaign loan
on personal and campaign financial reports required by the state.
Willard Mecham, his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, faced three
similar counts and up to 9{ years in prison.
   Evan Mecham insisted throughout his trial that the charges were
based on ``smoke and mirrors,'' but he had stopped short of
predicting that the Maricopa County Superior Court jury would find
him innocent.
   Although he said for months he wanted nothing more than to get
the facts out regarding the loan from attorney Barry Wolfson,
neither Mecham nor his brother took the stand during seven days of
testimony.
   It was an uncommon spell of official silence for the combative
Mecham, who testified in the Senate impeachment court and who never
shrunk from speaking his mind as governor.
   As Arizona's chief executive he angered many constituents by
canceling a Martin Luther King holiday on grounds it was illegally
created and by saying he didn't believe the slain civil rights
leader deserved a holiday.
   He was criticized for defending a book's use of the word
``pickaninny'' for blacks. Other statements deeply offended Jews,
homosexuals, women and Japanese-Americans.
   But Mecham never backed away from his comments, and he remained
defiant even after the Senate convicted him April 4 on impeachment
charges of misusing money from a state protocol fund and trying to
thwart an investigation of a death threat.
   A son of Mormon farmers, a fighter pilot in World War II, Mecham
put himself through college by selling cars in the rural town of
Ajo. In 1950 he moved his Pontiac dealership to Glendale, a Phoenix
suburb.
   He published his own newspaper in the 1960s as an alternative to
the Phoenix press. He also developed a virtual hobby of running for
public office. He won his first race in 1960, gaining a two-year
term in the state Senate.
   But he lost a 1962 bid for the U.S. Senate and ran
unsuccessfully for governor four times, including a near-miss in
the 1978 election against Democrat Bruce Babbitt.
   Fortune finally turned in Mecham's favor in 1986, when he
shocked the political establishment by winning the GOP primary and
the three-way general election race.
   Even after taking over as governor, Mecham saw himself as an
outsider attacked by an establishment of legislative leaders, the
news media and Attorney General Bob Corbin, a fellow Republican.
   In Mecham's eyes, those forces conspired to force him out of
office and into criminal court.
   But even before the jury returned its verdict, Mecham declared
he had been vindicated by the testimony.
   It ``has been totally revealed to the world that there was no
conspiracy (to hide the loan),'' the former governor said when the
defense had rested its case.
   Although Mecham often appeared haggard during his legal ordeal,
at other times he seemed anything but a broken man as he joked with
the reporters he has blamed for helping bring him down.
   In any case, he insisted all along that nothing would destroy
his peace of mind. He often quoted Abraham Lincoln, saying he would
be happy if he eventually won out but if he didn't, ``10 angels
swearing I was right won't make any difference.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
