<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RocketContract     06-16 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rocket Contract,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Awards Contract For Rocket To Carry Satellites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force awarded the General Dynamics
Corp. a $135.3 million, first-phase contract Thursday to provide a
new medium-lift booster rocket to ferry defense communication
satellites into orbit.
   The service announced a month ago it had selected General
Dynamics over another team consisting of the McDonnell Douglas
Corp. and the Martin Marietta Corp. to build the so-called Medium
Launch Vehicle II.
   Following that decision, negotiations were opened to finalize a
contract and that has now been done, the Air Force added.
   The service plans to purchase 11 of the new booster rockets over
the next few years. The first-phase contract covers research and
development expenses along with construction and launch services
for the first two boosters.
   Over the life of the program, each of the new boosters ``will
cost less than $40 million a copy and save the taxpayer hundreds of
millions of dollars in the process,'' said Air Force Secretary
Edward C. ``Pete'' Aldridge.
   ``That's the result of competition.''
   The MLV II is part of an ambitious acceleration of umanned
rocket programs started by the Pentagon after the loss of the
shuttle Challenger. The General Dynamics booster, designed to
handle payloads in the 6,000-pound class, will be a variant of the
oft-used Atlas Centaur launcher dubbed the Atlas II.
</TEXT>
