<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-SovietUnrest     06-16 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Soviet Unrest,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Azerbaijan Offcial Blames Armenian Orthodox Churdh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior official in the Soviet
republic of Azerbaijan blamed nationalists influenced by the
Armenian Orthodox Church for protests in a territorial dispute, a
Hungarian newspaper said Thursday.
   In what it called an exclusive interview with Azerbaijan state
prosecutor Ilias Ismailov, the Magyar Hirlap quoted him as saying
the disputed Nagorno-Karabakh region ``has never belonged to
Armenia'' and ``any return is out of the question.''
   The parliaments, or Supreme Soviets, of the two southern
republics held separate votes this week. Azerbaijan's decided not
to give up Nagorno-Karabakh and the Armenian parliament backed
demands by protesters that the mountainous region to be
incorporated into Armenia.
   About 80 percent of Ngorno-Karabakh's 160,000 people are ethnic
Armenians. It was assigned to Azerbaijan in 1923 but Armenians
consider it part of their ancestral homeland.
   ``You can only return what has been taken from you, legally or
illegally,'' Ismailov was quoted as saying. ``Karabakh has never
been part of Armenian territory.''
   Magyar Hirlap did not say when it obtained the interview with
Ismailov, which it said was conducted in Baku, capital of
Azerbaijan.
   Unrest over the fate of Nagorno-Karabakh began in February with
mass street protests in the Armenian capital, Yerevan, and strikes
and protests in Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Violence folowed in Azerbaijan, where 32 people were killed in
ethnic rioting in the port city of Sumgait, most of them ethnic
Armenians. Soviet authorities said a policeman was killed in
further unrest in Baku last week.
   The Soviet Communist party daily Pravda reported last Friday
that a general strike had virtually shut down industry and
agriculture in Nagorno-Karabakh for three weeks.
   According to the Magyar Hirlap report, Ismailov said: ``What is
happening in Karabakh was well organized in advance ... by Armenian
nationalists ... and under the influence of Echmiadzin,'' center of
the Armenian Orthodox Church.
   ``The whole ideology originated in Echmiadzin,'' Ismailov said,
referring to the religious center outside Yerevan.
   Despite his accusations associating Armenia's church with the
unrest, Ismailov said the conflict should not be seen as a
religious clash between Armenian Christians and the predominantly
Moslem people of Azerbaijan.
   ``There is an attempt to give a religious color to the conflict,
saying Christians do not want to live under Moslem sovereignty,''
Ismailov said. ``To put it mildly, this is a malicious approach to
the question _ there is no religious basis to this conflict.''
</TEXT>
