<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0770 06-16 0890</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0770,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Calls On Dukakis To Detail Cost Of Replacing Star Wars</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs with Dukakis campaign comment after 2nd graf
pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush challenged Democrat Michael
Dukakis on Thursday to come up with a price tag for his proposal to
junk the Reagan administration's Strategic Defense Inititative and
replace it with a buildup in conventional forces.
   ``Where do you go when you get into the most expensive side of
this of all, which is conventional forces?'' the vice president
asked, speaking with reporters on Air Force II.
   Jim Steinberg, deputy issues director for the Dukakis campaign,
said substantial funds would be freed up by halting work on the
so-called ``Star Wars'' missile defense system.
   ``The administration is now proposing to spend $4 billion on
SDI,'' Steinberg said. ``The governor feels those funds can
be...devoted to areas of greatest needs.''
   Bush, who has accused the all-but-certain Democratic
presidential nominee of lacking experience on foreign policy and
defense issues, said the Massachusetts governor's proposals could
jeopardize efforts to reach a strategic arms treaty with the
Soviets.
   ``My question to him would be: are you talking about the
winnability of a conventional war without any reliance whatsoever
on a nuclear deterrence? I don't know how he'd answer that
question. But if he answers yes, then I think he's wrong,'' Bush
said.
   ``And where's the price tag?'' he asked.
   Dukakis earlier this week, in a major foreign-policy speech in
Washington, voiced opposition to the MX missile and for SDI,
calling instead for a ``Conventional Defense Initiative.''
   ``I don't think that's a good concept,'' said Bush.
   Bush also told reporters he sees no problem with the fact that
his newly named communications adviser, James H. Lake, and his law
and consulting firm are registered lobbyists for Japanese business
companies.
   Noting that Lake, who was named to the campaign post on Monday,
is a volunteer and not a salaried campaign worker, Bush said: ``I
don't think there's a conflict at all. Are we going go now and look
at every client for every law firm for every volunteer?''
   Lake's firm, Robinson, Lake, Lerer & Montgomery, of which Lake
is chairman, represents Mitsubishi Electric Corp., Suzuki of
America Automotive Corop. and Japan Auto Parts Industries
Association, according to reports in the Detroit News and the
Washington Times.
   Bush also said he had no recollection of ever having met a
former Wedtech Corp. president, Anthony Guariglia, who testified
that he was introduced to Bush as part of an effort to obtain help
on a Navy pontoon contract.
   Guariglia made the claim on Wednesday in testimony in New York
in the Wedtech corrpution trial. He said Wedtech had raised
$200,000 for President Reagan's 1984 re-election campaign as part
of its effort to win the Navy contract.
   ``Was the guy ever at a fundraiser or something? Maybe. But I
don't remember anything, the name or anything about him,'' Bush
said.
   Asked whether he had any advice for syndicated columnist Carl
Rowan, who shot and wounded a teenage intruder in his back yard
earlier this week, Bush said: ``No, I don't have any advice for
him. I'm not having much fun out of it. I think it's a matter where
I can't make much of a contribution to it by saying anything.''
   Noting Rowan's own strong views in favor of gun control laws,
Bush added: ``I suspect it's causing him some difficulties sorting
out in his own mind, given his strong position on gun control, with
which I very much disagree.''
   ``I kind of emphathize with him on what he was going through
when somebody was coming up at him. It's all easy to second guess
now.''
   In a speech to an annual meeting of the U.S. Jaycees here, Bush
reiterated his views on strong penalties for those convicted of
drug offenses and said the policy of ``zero tolerance'' for drugs
should be applied to the workplace as well as to cars, planes and
boats.
   The vice president has proposed mandatory drug testing for
prison guards, airline pilots and for others responsible for the
public safety, and has suggested that all companies with government
contracts have ``drug free'' programs for their employes that might
include some form of drug testing.
   ``There are those who say that drug testing is an invasion of
individual rights. But the use of drugs...is a matter that affects
the lives of others,'' he said.
   Bush told his audience that while the government could not
require drug-testing or drug-education programs of private
businesses, ``each of you, pesonally, can stand up against drug
use.''
   Bush said he fully supports the zero-tolerance policy under
which yachts and other vehicles on which drugs have been found have
been seized. ``I don't mind inconveniencing a yacht owner or a car
driver if it results somehow in saving the life of one kid,'' Bush
said.
   In his talk with reporters on Air Force Two, on the way home to
Washington from Richmond, Bush said, ``I just can't get too excited
about the yacht owner, even though some would like you to believe I
am one.''
   ``Mine is 28 feet long. I want that in there too,'' he said,
referring to the $40,000 racing powerboat that he keeps at his
vacation retreat in Kennebunkport, Maine.
</TEXT>
