<1ST_LINE>r w BC-SearchWarrant     06-16 1188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Search Warrant,1,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Search Warrant Outlines Theory of Government Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A search warrant obtained by the Justice
Department and made public Thursday reveals the background and the
theory of the government's investigation into possible corruption
involving the Defense Department and private contractors.
   The following are excerpts from that search warrant, which was
issued by a federal judge in St. Louis in response to the Justioce
Department request to search an office at McDonnell Douglas, the
nation's largest defense contractor:
   ``Melvin Paisley resigned from his position as Assistant
Secretary of the Navy for Research, Engineering and Systems in
April, 1987. In April, 1987, PAISLEY opened his own private
consulting business in the Washington, D.C. area. As a consultant
to defense contractors, PAISLEY provided advise (sic) to
corporations and contractors who do business with varous agencies
within the Department of Defense. One of his consulting contracts
is with McDonnell Douglas. A large portion of his dealings with
McDonnell Douglas are with or go through Thomas Gunn, a
vice-president in marketing.
   ``DOD awards approximately 150 billion dollars worth of
contracts every year. DOD, through its constituent agencies, makes
decisions in areas for the acquisition and award of contracts to
further the national defense. At various stages, decisions are made
in DOD and the military departments concerning the development of
defense materials, equipment and services and the allocation of
funds appropriated to DOD for the national defense.
   ``Information and data used to develop and implement the
acquisition strategies are often closely held by DOD and its
military departments and are of value and interest to companies
seeking contracts from DOD. A company with such advance information
can prepare more advantageously for procurements which are likely
to be upcoming. Moreover, if a company learns of the Government's
plans, the company can evaluate the plans and try to influence the
decision makers to make modifications which would favor the
particular company. As such, a company may want to influence a
decision about the size of a particular procurement, the
specifications for the items being procured, the prerequisites
which a company must meet in order to be eligible for the award of
the procurement, or the weighing which the Government will use in
evaluating different aspects of all competitors' proposals.
   ``Once DOD decides to seek a particular procurement, a majority
of the contracts are awarded following a competitive bidding
process. DOD has contracting officers who oversee the bidding
process and are assigned within the various military services
(Army, Navy, Marine Corps and Air Force). The process begins with
an advertisement for a new contract which is followed by companies
receiving a document called a Request for Proposal (RFP) which
details contract specifications and other contractual requirements.
   ``A time limit is set for the recipients to respond with their
offers. Generally the price submitted by a company is critical to
the company's winning a contract because the Government usually
awards the contracts to the lowest bidder which is technically
qualified to complete the contract. Once the initial offers have
been submitted, the Government analyzes the offers for both
technical expertise and price. The government determines a
competitive range based upon the technical and pricing factors. If
it is determined that at least two of the companies' offers are
within the competitive range the competitive process is continued
for those companies.
   ``The government holds discussions with each company and tells
it where its offer is weak technically. The companies are then
asked to submit their Best and Final Offers (BAFO). The BAFO
provides them with the opportunity to adjust their offers with
respect to the price and the portions that were technically weak.
However, if the Government determines that only one company's offer
is within the competitive range, the Government can award the
contract without a BAFO stage.
   ``Information about a company's competitors' offers and the
Government's evaluation of those offers is never disclosed to a
company prior to the award of the contract. Therefore, a company
which has access to that information prior to the time when BAFO's
must be submitted can benefit greatly. The information can assist
the company in deciding how to modify its own offer.
   ``The information can also help a company learn that it has no
chance of winning a contract. Then the company can decide to either
drop out of the bidding or to seek to influence the Government to
withdraw the RFP and change it in a way to be more favorable to the
company.
   ``In addition, companies can obtain an edge if they obtain
information about the Government's intentions which have not been
disclosed prior to or during the bidding process. For instance, the
Government may not have disclosed the amount of funds it has
budgeted for a procurement or its estimates of how many options it
will exercise under a contract containing options. Such information
can help a company in drafting its proposal.
   ``The scheme involves the illegal disclosure of information and
the exertion of influence with respect to Department of Defense
contracts. The information disclosed is often provided by
Government employees receiving bribes or gratuities. The disclosed
information has been of the type that can provide a company with an
unfair advantage over its competitors and@or the government. A
substantial portion of the disclosed information is classified or
confidential.
   ``As a defense contractor consultant, PAISLEY relies upon
Government officials to provide Department of Defense contract
information which is not available to the contracting public.
PAISLEY then provides this information, for a fee or as part of his
``consulting contract'' to McDonnell Douglas, who is a Department
of Defense contractor. PAISLEY has provided McDonnell Douglas and
THOMAS GUNN substantial information obtained from Government
officials which has been classified and@or confidential or not
available to the contracting public. This information has included
the following:
   ``1) information regarding McDonnell Douglas proposed sale of
its F-18 fighter airplane to the Swiss government, including
internal information of the Navy regarding the Super Hornet
configuration; a proposed letter to McDonnell Douglas regarding the
F-18; information regarding Best and Final Offers (BAFO) on the
Swiss contract; inside information pertaining to General Dynamics
F-16 proposal;
   ``2) information regarding a co-development plan with the French
government regarding an updated F-18 (called FA-18) including an
internal Navy study;
   ``3) information regarding the sale of F-18s to Korea including,
names of individuals with ability to influence the U.S. Government
to approve the sale of F-18s to Korea and;
   ``4) information relating to sale of F-18s to European Fighter
Aircraft (EFA) nations, including a telex from an EFA nation
Embassy (United Kingdom, Germany, Italy and Spain) dated
axpproximately February 3, 1988, notes on Keb briefing on the
Hornet 2000; documents on the APG 65 Radar; and letters from the
Germans on the APG 65 Radar; and letters from the Germans on the
radar for the F-18;
   ``5) the summer of 1987 Naval Research Advisory Committee study;
   ``6) early 1987 Center for Naval Analysis study regarding the
500 MG Helicopter (Killer Egg) and the future helicoper needs of
the Marine Corps;
   ``7) information relating to the Advanced Tactical Aircraft
program, including BAFO information.''
</TEXT>
