<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1926EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   06-16 1096</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0772,1,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Campaign Across South</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS graf 2 pvs to UPDATE with 2nd poll; SUBS 21st graf pvs
to UPDATE with Dukakis campaign comment; ADDS 3 grafs with
NBC-Journal poll</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis and George Bush laid the foundation Thursday for
their general election battle in the South, with Bush trumpeting a
tough anti-drug stand in Virginia and Dukakis in Tennessee seeking
to unify his party in a region that was once its stronghold.
   A new poll said the two men are locked in a tight contest there.
And another survey out Thursday gave Dukakis a double-digit lead
nationwide.
   Dukakis started a regional campaign swing with a stop in
Nashville to pick up the endorsement of former Democratic
presidential rival Albert Gore Jr.
   ``Mike Dukakis is going to carry our party to victory in
November. He is going to win in the East, in the North, in the
West, and he is going to win right here in the South,'' Gore said
of the Massachusetts governor he criticized during the primary
season.
   Dukakis' ``image in the South and all over the country is very
different than many people thought it was going to be when this
campaign began. I think he moves beyond the old labels,'' Gore said.
   Jesse Jackson, Dukakis' remaining rival, testified before a
Senate committee on drug abuse and basked in the praise of a
senator he competed against in the 1984 presidential campaign.
   ``I would think Jesse frightened the bejesus out of them four
years ago,'' said Sen. Ernest F. Hollings of South Carolina. ``I
remember him standing up and saying his time has come! ... This
time he's run a winning campaign. He hasn't frightened anyone. He's
charmed them in all of those different debates.''
   Hollings, the only senator to back Jackson, said Dukakis has
locked up the nomination, but he said his vote at the Atlanta
convention would be based on South Carolina Democrats' support of
Jackson.
   ``He won my home state; he certainly has earned my vote,''
Hollings said.
   Jackson met with 33 Democratic senators as he pressed for more
unpledged ``super delegates'' to the July Democratic convention to
support him. He said the party leadership ``while accepting my
investment in the party to make it strong, has not been as
reciprocal as it ought to be.''
   ``If I invest, I should reasonably expect return,'' Jackson told
reporters. ``So I appreciate the accolades that I am the voter
registration champion for the party, that I have led the drive to
return the Senate back to the Democrats...If I have done all of
that, I simply say let's be fair.''
   Dukakis welcomed Gore's support and said he looked to Jackson to
join the bandwagon.
   ``I would hope Jesse Jackson will be a part of this campaign and
as early as possible,'' the Massachusetts governor said.
   Dukakis added his backing to the idea of a special outside
counsel to probe charges against House Speaker Jim Wright, who will
preside over the Democratic convention next month.
   He said Wright had welcomed the idea, and he called that a
stance that ``contrasts rather sharply with the kind of
stonewalling we've had from the administration on case after case
after case.''
   Dukakis distinguished his support for Wright from his call for
the resignation of Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   ``That's after repeated evidence of insensitivity, a lack of
awareness of what we mean when we talk about high standards,''
Dukakis said. ``If you're attorney general of this country and
you've stumbled as often as he has and made as many mistakes as he
has and provided as weak leadership as he has, you ought to leave
office.''
   Bush, with his budget cramped by federal spending limits, went
only as far south as Richmond, Va., where the Republican vice
president declared drugs ``the ultimate fatal attraction.'' He also
renewed his call for companies to put anti-drug programs in place
before they can receive federal contracts.
   ``The point is that stopping drugs in the workplace is not just
a profit and loss issue, it's a matter of protecting the health and
safety of workers,'' the all-but-certain Republican presidential
nominee told the U.S. Jaycees annual meeting. ``It's no less
important than OSHA regulations on the conditions of machinery.''
   ``The federal government should not dictate what kind of
drug-free program a company should have, but it should require any
federal contractor to have one in place,'' he said.
   Bush also demanded ``Where's the price tag?'' for Dukakis's
advocacy of increased spending on non-nuclear forces, which the
Massachusetts governor called a Conventional Defense Initiative, to
replace President Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative.
   Dukakis' deputy issues director Jim Steinberg replied that the
administration has earmarked $4 billion for SDI, and that freeing
up those funds would help finance other military spending.
   Drugs were Jackson's topic in testimony before the Senate
Committee on Labor and Human Resources, where he denounced calls
for legalization.
   ``That would be a mistake. It would be surrender to the No. 1
threat to our national security. We would not think of legalization
of smog because there's a lot of it. It's dangerous,'' Jackson said.
   Dukakis got some good news as he started his three-day Southern
swing.
   A new poll in nine Southern states said Dukakis and Bush are
neck-and-neck in the region once called solid for the Democrats. In
recent years, GOP presidential candidates have counted a strong
showing in the region, but pollster Claibourne Darden said Bush
can't make that assumption.
   ``I think everyone has to be surprised at how well Dukakis is
doing in the South,'' Darden said. ``George Bush himself is doing
more to break the Republican `lock' on the South than Michael
Dukakis is doing.''
   The telephone poll of 750 voters gave Dukakis the support of 45
percent and Bush the backing of 42 percent. Thirteen percent were
undecided.
   Given the poll's sampling error margin of 4 percentage points,
that finding is a dead heat for the states involved: Virginia,
North Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia, Florida, Alabama,
Mississippi, Louisiana and Tennessee.
   And in another poll, this one nationwide, Dukakis held a
15-point lead over Bush. The NBC News-Wall Street Journal survey,
conducted June 9-12, said Dukakis had the support of 49 percent of
the registered voters polled, compared to 34 percent for Bush.
   The survey suggested Dukakis' lead was based largely on
overwhelming support among women, where he held a 24-point lead,
52-28.
   The national survey of 2,014 adults had a margin of sampling
error of 3 percentage points, NBC said.
</TEXT>
