<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HeroinCandy     06-16 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heroin Candy,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heroin Candies Called ``New Trend'' in Drug Smuggling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Candies made from enough heroin to kill a child
are the latest way smugglers are trying to bring the drug into
Britain, customs officials said Thursday.
   Twenty pounds of the fake candies, each containing the
equivalent of nearly $550 worth of heroin, have been discovered in
the luggage of smugglers arriving from Pakistan in the past three
weeks, the officials said. The total value was put at $1.34 million.
   The officials said they were alerting customs officials in other
countries, of the danger.
   ``Somewhere in Pakistan there is a factory compressing, glazing
and wrapping heroin to look exactly like sweets,'' said Mike Curr,
assistant chief investigations officer.
   ``If they are stolen by kids or otherwise get into their hands,
just one sweet will kill a child,'' he said. ``Even touching it by
unwrapping the cellophane will leave a rash as the heroin is
absorbed into the skin.''
   Howard Sutton, chief press officer at national customs
headquarters in London, said heroin disguised as candy was seized
before at a British border but called it ``a relatively new trend
in smuggling techniques.''
   He said smugglers usually baked the drug until it was black and
looked like licorice, then wrapped it in real candy wrappers.
   The fake candy was found in two confiscations involving five
passengers coming in from Pakistan, which is known as a drug
source, Sutton said.
</TEXT>
