<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ColorizedMovies     06-16 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colorized Movies,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Measure Aimed at `Colorized' Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With actor Jimmy Stewart looking on, a House
committee approved a measure Thursday that would create a
commission to act against ``colorized'' black-and-white movies.
   Among other things, those movies could not be shown under their
original titles if the measure becomes law _ which even backers
concede is doubtful.
   Disregarding objections that the action was an infringement on
the rights of other congressional committees, the Appropriations
Committee refused, 25-20, to delete the anti-coloring provision
from the $9.7 billion appropriations bill it later passed for the
Interior Department and related agencies.
   Several committee members, including the chairman, Rep. Jamie
Whitten, D-Miss., argued that the committee should not proceed
because the decision belongs to the Judiciary Committee and its
copyright subcommittee.
   Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., chairman of the Rules Committee,
wrote Whitten to object to the procedure.
   ``Obviously this is not going to survive the Rules Committee,''
said Rep. Robert J. Mrazek, D-N.Y., a supporter of the measure.
``But if it survives this Appropriations Committee, it will send a
signal.''
   The measure is similar to a proposal pending before the
Judiciary Committee. It would set up a nine-member commission to
judge which films are significant enough to deserve protection.
   Those films, if significantly altered, could not be shown or
distributed without disclosure of the alterations and the desire of
the director or principal writer to disassociate themselves from
the changes.
   Black-and-white films to which color had been added could not be
shown or distributed under their original titles.
   The issue arose last year after Atlanta businessman Ted Turner,
owner of a gigantic film library, began releasing black-and-white
classics such as ``The Maltese Falcon'' in computer-colored
versions.
   Many film buffs and directors have objected that the process
perverts the vision of the makers of the original film.
   ``I find it offensive for a government body to designate what is
art,'' said Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., leader of the opponents of
the provision in the committee. In addition, ``We are saying that
property rights (of the owners) should be limited or terminated.''
   Mrazek argued that the issue was one of vandalizing art that
ought to be protected. He read a telegram from director Frank Capra
that complained the current owners of his 1940s film with Stewart,
``It's a Wonderful Life,'' had ``splashed it all over with Easter
egg colors and ruined it.''
   Referring to Stewart's role as the reforming senator in ``Mr.
Smith Goes to Washington,'' Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., argued,
``Mr. Smith would have been standing up in this committee arguing
against the bypassing of committee procedures.''
   The 80-year-old Stewart expressed elight after the vote, saying,
``Nobody was quite sure who was going to win right up to the end.''
   Adding color to black-and-white movies, he said, is ``really a
terrible practice and something that should be outlawed.''
   Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, the principal studio-producer trade association, said
Mrazek's opponents had only about five votes when the issue moved
into the committee a few days ago. ``There was a big change in my
direction,'' he said.
   Whitten's opposition is bound to be influential from here on, he
added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
