<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-BoatPeople     06-16 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Boat People,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Detains 78 Boat People Under Tough New Immigration
Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Thursday detained Vietnamese
boat people as illegal immigrants, instead of granting them asylum
as refugees from their communist country as has been Hong Kong's
policy for 13 years.
   Officials arrested 78 Vietnamese who came ashore, under a tough
new policy to stop the influx of boat people to this tiny British
colony. The detainees will be returned to Vietnam unless they can
prove they face political or religious persecution back home.
   Britain's ambassador to Vietnam, Emrys Davies, told reporters in
Hong Kong that Hanoi ``saw enormous difficulties'' in taking back
large numbers of boat people and had given no indication it would
accept them by the early 1990s.
   Davies said Hanoi is punishing people who organize the exodus
from Vietnam but added that it was difficult to patrol Vietnam's
long coastline.
   Since the Vietnam War ended in 1975 with the communists taking
over the goverment, Hong Kong has considered all boat people to be
refugees fleeing persecution. The policy was reviewed as the number
of Vietnamese arrivals rose to nearly 8,000 this year, of which
only 1,200 have been resettled.
   Government officials say prospects are dim for finding homes for
more than 16,000 refugees now in Hong Kong camps.
   Under the policy, boat people who fled for economic reasons will
be detained until they can be sent back to Vietnam. Those who can
prove they faced persecution in Vietnam will be granted refugee
status and become eligible for resettlement.
   One of the Vietnamese who was detained told reporters that his
boat carried more than 30 relatives. Nguyen Dai Quy said he did not
know of the new policy when he left his home in central Vietnam two
weeks ago but would have fled anyway.
   The 32-year-old man said he was a political refugee, noting that
the Communist government did not allow him to pursue deep sea
fishing and that his children could not attend school. He claimed
his mother was killed by Viet Cong and he was a volunteer soldier
for the pro-American South Vietnam army during the war.
   ``I hope the Hong Kong government will change its policy and let
me get out,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
