<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 2155EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CzechoslovakEconomy     06-16 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovak Economy,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Passes Limited Economic Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ONDREJ HEJMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament has passed reforms that
give state enterprises more say in production, make them
self-financing and could reduce the economic bureaucracy by 30
percent, the government said Thursday.
   The limited package passed in a special three-day session is
patterned after Soviet reforms that prescribe self-management and
self-financing for state enterprises and cooperatives while taking
away some or all state subsidies.
   CTK, the official news agency, said state companies will be
directly subordinate to ministries and that eliminating
middle-level bureaus could bring a reduction of up to 30 percent in
the economic bureaucracy.
   The reforms, which take effect next Jan. 1, were passed after a
yearlong debate. During the rest of this year, companies that
account for 30 percent of industrial production will be involved in
an experiment that gives them greater control of production
decisions.
   Czechoslovak officials gave few details on plans for economic
reform, which they approach with caution. Decentralization of
management will not go as far as in the Soviet Union and will not
take full effect until 1991.
   Premier Lubomir Strougal acknowledged in May that the economy
had not improved under his government. He said the number of
committees and bureaus between enterprises and ministries will be
reduced and the direct responsibilities of ministers increased.
   The once-efficient economy is plagued by low productivity, a
poor industrial structure, unbalanced supply and demand, and growth
of unsold inventory.
   Jaroslav Matejka, an architect of the reforms, told a news
conference last month only 48 percent of companies had applied for
the new status that brings more independence. He said some feared
being put out of business.
   Managers will be elected by secret ballot in the plant,
according to the new law, but the government retains the right to
nominate candidates for the jobs.
   New trade legislation will allow companies to make contracts of
cooperation with others inside the Soviet-led Comecon trading group
without first seeking government permission, CTK said.
   Some enterprises will be allowed to deal directly with Western
companies, bypassing foreign trade offices that now act as
middlemen.
   A new law on cooperative enterprises, which employ 1.5 million
people, affects those in both agricultural and housing and could
increase their efficiency, the agency reported.
   Housing cooperatives alleviate the chronic housing shortage in a
country where thousands of people have waited years years for new
apartments.
   Agriculture subsidies now cost $3 billion a year.
   Miroslav Toman, the agriculture minister, raised the possibility
of people being allowed to buy land.
   ``There is a situation ... when the new law allows transfer of
land not suitable for socialist large-scale production ... to other
... socialist and social organizations and individuals,'' Toman
told the daily Lidova Demokracie. He gave no details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
