<DOCNO> AP880616-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 2155EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Soviet     06-16 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Soviet,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Union Calls For Expanded U.N. Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir F.
Petrovsky on Thursday called for an expanded U.N. role, including a
naval force, a space agency under United Nations auspices and a
body to monitor disarmament pacts.
   ``This is a revolutionary change in our attitude toward the
United Nations,'' Petrovsky, deputy head of the Soviet delegation
to the current disarmament session, told a news conference.
   For years, the Soviet government has been wary of the 159-member
world body, but recently it has sought to strengthen it and develop
a comprehensive U.N. security system, a vague concept opposed by
the United States as unrealistic.
   The Soviet Union has been playing a major role in the current
General Assembly session on disarmament. It has also paid its U.N.
budget debts and increased the number of Soviet citizens on
permanent assignment as civil servants at the United Nations.
   The United States owes more than $240 million in U.N. dues. It
is cool toward most Soviet proposals regarding the United Nations
and does not wish to see an expanded U.N. role that could infringe
on national prerogative.
   Petrovsky said the Soviet Union was ``delivering our U.N. policy
from dogmas and subjective approaches, but ... we have every right
to expect similar self-criticism, responsibility and reason from
other states, too.''
   The United Nations, he said, should become ``a unique center for
harmonizing actions of states in our interdependent world.''
   Petrovsky said all nations should disclose to the United Nations
information on their troops abroad and their foreign military
bases. But, asked if the Soviet Union would make the first step and
disclose its military information, Petrovsky said:
   ``This is not a one-actor theater, but the world stage. We are
ready to participate in the exchange of data if other countries,
the United States and NATO, do the same.''
   In its month-long session on disarmament, the General Assembly
is expected to adopt resolutions and a final document setting out a
realistic agenda for disarmament and arms control. Western
diplomats have indicated that if the documents are unacceptable,
there will be no consensus and there could be divisive votes.
   The Soviet proposals include:
   _Creation of a U.N. naval force aimed at maintaning freedom of
navigation, and holding a joint trial exercise with fleets of the
permanent members of the Security Council _ the United States,
Britain, China, France and the Soviet Union.
   _U.N. supervision of troop withdrawal from foreign territories
and the expansion of U.N. peacekeeping forces. The Soviet Union has
proposed elimination of foreign military presence and military
bases in foreign territories by the year 2,000.
   _Creation of an international monitoring and verification
agency, covering both disarmament and political settlement of
conflicts and crises.
   _Creation of a world space organization under U.N. auspices to
ensure safeguards in making outer space strictly for peaceful
purposes.
   The United States regards many of the proposals as infringements
upon its ability to behave unilaterally in its own interests and
pursue, for example, its space-based anti-missile defense
initiative, known as ``Star Wars.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 2200EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-OffshoreDrilling     06-16 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Offshore Drilling,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Offshore Drilling Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee approved prohibitions
Thursday on oil and gas drilling for another year in federal waters
off Florida, California and New England.
   The bans were contained in the $9.7 billion appropriations bill
for the Interior Department and related agencies that the
Appropriations Committee sent to the House floor.
   Earlier in the day, Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel announced
a delay of at least six months in the planned lease offering for
New England waters to try negotiations with affected New England
governors. The sale originally had been scheduled for next February.
   Hodel also split the offering for Florida Gulf Coast waters into
two parts, with the 44-million-acre non-controversial section to be
offered in November as scheduled. An offering on other gulf waters
will be delayed at least six months while two federal-state task
forces conduct additional studies on oil spill trajectories and the
effects of any spills on the southwest Florida coast.
   Last week, Hodel similarly delayed the offering of leases off
northern California until next October.
   The committee's provisions, if upheld by Congress, will apply
until Sept. 30, 1989.
   There have been several previous bars to drilling enacted
similarly as riders to appropriations bills, and most of the
argument Thursday covered ground familiar to the members.
   Hodel's California provision was enacted without discussion.
   The Florida question is complicated by the presence of 73
previously awarded leases that were suspended for three years for
special environmental studies recently completed.
   An amendment by Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio, to delete the 73
tracts from the 16 million acres of prohibited area south of about
Naples down to the Keys was defeated.
   ``The very modest amendment offered by Mr. Regula here today is
simply to say the United States will live by its commitments,''
said Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La. Regula himself argued that the
issue was, ``Can we take back the rights that people have paid for,
namely $220 million?''
   More generally though, Regula argued that ``To year after year
place a moratorium on (drilling) doesn't address the problem.'' The
issue really belongs before the Energy and Commerce Committee, he
said.
   The New England provisions expand the prohibited area
substantially from what it has been in past years by barring
drilling in waters less than 400 meters deep (1,312 feet), compared
to 60 meters (197 feet) previously.
   Regula offered an amendment to make the New England area conform
to what was prohibited in previous years, but was defeated on a
voice vote.
   New England opponents of offshore drilling say the prohibition
is needed to protect the rich, shallow Georges Bank fishing grounds
off Cape Cod, and the 400-meter provision was chosen to conform to
provisions of a 12-year Canadian moratorium in adjacent waters
adopted earlier this year.
   The action closes about 3.5 million acres to drilling and leaves
about 2 million acres available for offering in a February auction.
   Opposing the committee proposals, Hodel said there might be no
bids if promising shallow-water areas were ruled off limits off New
England.
   Lisa Speer, staff attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council and long-time opponent of offshore drilling, said after the
vote: ``This is a major victory. This takes the pressure off and
will allow the next administration to take a look at the offshore
program.''
   The American Petroleum Institute said the action if upheld
``would mean the abandonment of any meaningful effort to find new
supplies of oil and natural gas offshore, and is a severe blow to
the nation's future energy security. ... The record of oil company
offshore operations clearly shows that oil and gas is being
extracted without harm to the environment, to economic activity,
tourism, fishing or wildlife.''
</TEXT>
