<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Tagger     06-16 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Tagger ,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Painter Ziona Tagger Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ziona Tagger, one of Israel's first native
artists who was known for her depictions of the old port city of
Jaffa, died Thursday in Tel Aviv, the national Itim news agency
reported. She was 88.
   The Itim report said Ms. Tagger died at her home but did not
give a cause of death.
   Ms. Tagger studied painting at the Bezalel School of Art in
Jerusalem and at the Andre Lot Academy in Paris. She was one of the
founders of the Israeli Artists and Sculptors Association and was
awarded Israel's prestigious Dizengoff Prize for artists in 1937.
   She lived in Tel Aviv most of her life, capturing scenes of
Jaffa, where she was born, and the emerging new town of Tel Aviv in
her impressionistic style.
   Her art work has been displayed in one-person shows in Israel,
France and Egypt as well as in group exhibitions in Italy, South
Africa and the United States.
   She is survived by her son, Avraham Katz-Oz, who is Israel's
deputy agriculture minister and a member of the centrist Labor
party.
</TEXT>
