<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PlantClosings     06-16 0116</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Closings,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Metzenbaum Offers New Plant-Closing Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, introduced a
free-standing bill Thursday that would require all but the smallest
companies to provide workers 60 days' advance notice of plant
shutdowns or mass layoffs.
   Metzenbaum's mandatory-notice proposal was one of the provisions
in an omnibus trade bill that prompted President Reagan to veto it.
The Senate upheld that veto.
   Nancy Coffey, a Metzenbaum aide, said the senator hopes Congress
will pass the plant-closing bill before any restructured trade bill
comes to the floor and that there will be enough votes to override
any presidential veto of his measure.
   The legislation would concern companies with 100 or more
employees.
</TEXT>
