<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HeatRdp     06-16 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heat Rdp,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Continues in New England, Mid-Atlantic States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AM-Weatherpage Weather</NOTE>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   That hum of air conditioners pulled power demand to peak levels
as New Englanders kept fighting the heat Thursday, while cooler
weather prevailed for parts of the Plains and thunderstorms hit
numerous regions of the nation.
   The New England Power Pool, a consortium of 95 utilities which
coordinates electrical power for the region, recorded a record
demand Thursday and another utility, Boston Edison Co., had record
power demand for the second time in two days for the 40 communities
it serves around Boston.
   Some Massachusetts workers called the state Department of Public
Health to see if a state law allowed them to go home once the
temperatures reached a certain high. The icy answer: No.
   Readings were into the low to mid-90s from the lower Mississippi
and Tennessee valleys through central parts of Virginia and
northern New Jersey.
   Record high temperatures for the date were set in Asheville,
N.C., 91; and Portland, Ore., 93.
   Temperatures were more comfortable from the northern Plains into
the upper Great Lakes. Readings were in the 70s across much of the
region with temperatures in the 50s and 60s across northern
Minnesota and Michigan.
   The low for the nation Thursday morning was 35 at Alamosa, Colo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Marquette, Mich., and Crescent City, Calif., to 108
degrees at Goodyear, Ariz.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from western New England
through the lower Ohio Valley into the southern Plains, but they
brought little relief to the Ohio Valley where only a quarter-inch
of rainfall has been reported.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed across the Cumberland
Plateau in the Tennessee Valley, where rainfall is eight to 13
inches below normal for the year.
   Heavy rain and small hail were reported Thursday afternoon as
storms moved across extreme southeast Pennsylvania and southwest
New Jersey.
   Thunderstorms were scattered early Thursday afternoon across
northern parts of Oklahoma and western parts of Arkansas. Showers
and thunderstorms were rapidly developing across parts of Texas and
along the front range of the Colorado Rockies.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered across central
and southern Florida and over a small part of northwest California
and southwest Oregon.
   The National Weather Service forecast showers and thunderstorms
Friday from New England through the Middle Atlantic States into the
Tennessee Valley, and afternoon and evening thunderstorms along the
front range of the Colorado Rockies.
   The rest of the nation was expected to have mostly sunny skies,
with high temperatures in the 80s or 90s; in the 70s for the
extreme northern Pacific Coast, the California coast, and across
the Great Lakes region into New England. Predicted highs were 100
to 110 degrees in the desert southwest.
</TEXT>
