<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BlackMayors     06-16 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Mayors,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conference Addresses Black Mayors' Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The leading presidential candidates must address
black Americans' concerns or face losing the support of ``a sizable
number of people,'' the head of the National Conference of Black
Mayors said Thursday.
   ``Those folks who want to go into office _ Gov. (Michael)
Dukakis and George Bush _ and don't take those populations that we
represent seriously, then we will not take them seriously,'' said
John H. Smith, mayor of Prichard, Ala.
   ``Whatever it takes for us to send that signal to them by not
voting for them or voting for folks who share our views, we'll do
that,'' Smith said.
   Republican Bush, Democrat Dukakis and Democrat Jesse Jackson
were invited to attend the conference, but only Jackson has
confirmed that he will speak Saturday, Smith said.
   ``We want to caution those folks who tend to ignore these
meetings and who are running for various offices who don't spend
time discussing our agenda,'' said Smith, a Republican.
   ``If they don't show up here, we have decided at this conference
to organize our populations ... and say to those folks who are
running for office what we want to do,'' said Smith, joined at a
news conference by Philadelphia Mayor W. Wilson Goode and about 20
of the 200 mayors attending the four-day conference.
   Smith said he doubts Jackson will be selected as Dukakis'
running mate because of the ``further continuation of the attitude
of the Democratic party in its liberal traditions of looking at
black folks simply as appendages, as followers rather than
leaders.''
   Goode, a Jackson supporter, said Dukakis and Jackson should sit
down and resolve the issue.
   ``He's earned the right to be considered,'' Goode said. ``He's
earned the right to be respected as one of the leading leaders of
our party.
   ``If he's not granted that respect, then I think there's going
to some very difficult times in front of us as a party.''
   Goode, vice chairman of Pennsylvania's delegation to the
Democratic Convention in Atlanta, criticized party rules that force
him to go as a Dukakis delegate.
   Goode said he plans to vote for Jackson on the first ballot,
even though rules require him to vote for Dukakis.
   ``As far as I know, slavery ended a long time ago,'' he said.
``I will do it.''
   Economic, racial and health problems have emerged as other major
concerns of those attending the 14th annual convention, which runs
through Saturday.
</TEXT>
