<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BullinChinaShop     06-16 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bull in China Shop,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Zealand Shopowner Puts Cliche to a Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ever wonder what would happen if
you really let a bull loose in a china shop? So did Grant Burnett.
So much, in fact, that he put the cliche to a test in his own store
on Thursday.
   Nothing happened.
   ``I'm pretty relieved,'' Burnett admitted after fulfilling what
he said was a lifelong ambition _ letting a 2,400-pound bull roam
through his store for three hours.
   ``We managed to get him out of the shop before anything
happened,'' Burnett said.
   Not that there weren't tense moments. Burnett said $60,000 worth
of china was at stake during the romp by the bull, nicknamed ``The
Colonel.''
   Burnett said he attempted the feat at his shop in Palmerston
North, near Wellington, after constantly being egged on by
customers familiar with bull-in-a-china-shop cliche.
   While ``The Colonel'' shopped around, Burnett said, he got a
call from a radio station in Stoke-on-Trent, Britain, known as the
home of bone china. Representatives of the Guinness Book of World
Records as well as the international media also turned up to watch
the stunt.
   Burnett took some precautions. Before the event, he said, he
insured his china at an undisclosed premium. Just in case.
</TEXT>
