<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     06-16 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqis Claim They Recapture Peak In North</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi forces recaptured an Iranian-held
mountain peak in Sulimaniyah province in northern Iraq on Thursday,
the army said.
   Senior army spokesman Abdul Jabar Muhsen told reporters the
Iraqi 1st Army Corps took the strategic Ahmad Romi mountaintop in a
major offensive launched Thursday.
   The mountain, more than 6,500 feet high, overlooks an entire
Iraqi valley. It is just over four miles from the Iraq-Iran border
and about 25 miles northeast of Sulimaniyah, Iraq's largest
northern city and the provincial capital of the Kurdish region.
   The Iranians captured the peak and the adjacent town of Mawet in
fierce fighting last summer.
   Muhsen gave no battle details, but the official Iraqi News
Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said the air force flew 221 combat
missions on Thursday with all aircraft returning safely. INA said
helicopter gunships completed 115 of the missions.
   Heavy use of helicopter gunships is usually an indication that
Iraq is trying to counter ground assaults by Iran. The Iraqi
communique reported fighting a several points along the
730-mile-long border between the two countries.
   An Iranian news report Thursday said a rebuilt F-14 fighter jet
successfully completed test flights at an air base in Isfahan. The
television report, monitored in Nicosia, said the fighter's
electrical system caught fire 11 months ago.
   Iran has had difficulty obtaining high-tech spare parts for its
air force, purchased in large part by the late Shah's government
from the United States, due to a longstanding American arms embargo.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980.
   Their battle claims can rarely be verified independently since
neither country as a rule allows foreign journalists into the war
zones.
</TEXT>
