<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Kohl     06-16 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Kohl,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>German Chancellor Covers Farm Subsidies, East-West in Address</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family farm in Europe must remain viable and
subsidies cannot be rolled back overnight, Chancellor Helmut Kohl
of West Germany told the Canadian Parliament on Thursday.
   Kohl, the first West German head of government to address
Canada's legislature, acknowledged criticism of Europe's Common
Agricultural Policy and the $300 billion global farm-subsidy war.
   He said he opposed permanent subsidies in principle but added:
``When developments have taken a long course over 20 years, you
cannot remedy the situation overnight ... the family farm must
remain viable in Europe's future.''
   The United States has proposed phasing out agricultural
subsidies by the year 2000, and Canadian officials had hoped for a
compromise at the seven-nation Economic Summit which starts Sunday
in Toronto.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney said in welcoming Kohl that summit
nations ``must come to grips with the acute problem.''
   But the 12-nation European Community has been reluctant to
dismantle subsidies to small farmers because of the political
outcry that would follow.
   In a wide-ranging, 55-minute address, Kohl likened the new
U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement to European Community plans to
create a unified market for goods by 1992.
   That uniform market of 320 million consumers will remain
accessible to other countries, Kohl said, and he counted on Canada
to ensure the same will be true of North America under free trade.
   ``We trust the assurances of our Canadian friends that European
companies, too, will be able to use the new opportunities to
increase trade.''
   The U.S.-Canada treaty, due to take effect Jan. 1 if ratified,
would eliminate all tariffs over a 10-year period and dismantle
other barriers.
   Kohl arrived Wednesday night for his first official visit to
Canada, prior to the Economic Summit. Japanese Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita arrived in Vancouver on Thursday to tour the west
coast province.
   Kohl said his government's central goal is to overcome the
division of Germany and the rest of Europe, ``to make the frontiers
more permeable, to reunite separated families, facilitate human
contact and develop a lasting and equitable, peaceful border.''
   He thanked Canada for stationing 7,000 troops among NATO forces
in his country and said allied solidarity had contributed to recent
arms control breakthroughs by the superpowers.
   He said the Warsaw Pact's superiority in conventional weapons
and capacity for surprise attack are now the basic problem in
European security.
   ``Eliminating these capabilities must be the objective of future
negotiations,'' which he hoped would begin this year, Kohl said.
   The chancellor concluded by recalling the aid his country
received after World War II. ``We were half-starved. I felt at that
time what it means for a country to receive help ... and we haven't
forgotten that.''
   He said it was a moral duty to extend similar aid now to the
Third World, declaring, ``I'm one of those who believe that in the
first quarter of the 21st century, the hazards and challenges of
the North-South conflict (industrialized nations and developing
nations) will overshadow East-West problems.''
</TEXT>
