<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-American     06-16 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-American,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador Condemns Killing of Agronomists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. ambassador condemned as ``vile and
horrendous'' Thursday the rebel killings of an U.S. agricultural
adviser and his Peruvian colleague and another U.S. official said
such workers may be withdrawn from danger areas.
   ``Constantine Gregory and Gustavo Rojas were men who dedicated
their lives to helping Peruvian campesinos (peasants),'' Ambassador
Alexander Watson said in referring to the attack Monday on an
isolated road near Huancayo, 125 miles east of Lima.
   Officials said Gregory, 25, of Los Angeles, and Rojas, 27, were
shot by leftist Shining Path guerrillas in a highland insurgency
zone near Aramachay, a mountain hamlet 15 miles north of Huancayo.
   The words ``This is the way the lackeys of Yankee imperialism
die'' and a hammer and sickle were scrawled in red ink in Gregory's
notebook, according to reporters at the scene.
   The Shining Path, an 8-year-old Maoist insurgency, has
frequently assassinated development workers in Peru's impoverished
highlands in an effort to spawn economic chaos.
   The victims were working on a project funded by the U.S. Agency
for International Development, which spends more than $50 million
yearly in Peru on farm, health and food relief programs, agency
officials said.
   The officials refused to say if the attack would prompt the
agency to alter or limit its Peruvian operations. AIDhas about 20
American agents here and dozens of U.S. and Peruvian technicians
work under special contracts.
   But a U.S. official who supervises a research program funded by
the agency said meetings were planned to discuss withdrawing
workers from potentially dangerous rural areas.
   The official, who spoke on condition he not be identified, said
the U.S. Embassy sent investigators to find out if Gregory's
killing was circumstantial or represented a decision by Shining
Path leaders to target Americans.
   Gregory was ``just a kid wanting some experience'' before
returning to the United States for graduate school in August, one
U.S. development official said on Wednesday, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   Following an autopsy Thursday near Huancayo, the bodies of the
men were taken to Lima, the embassy said. Officials said the
families, including Gregory's American wife, Maria Dolores, will
travel to the Peruvian capital Friday.
   The guerrillas shot each man in the back of the head after
halting the four-wheel-drive vehicle they were driving, police said.
   The attackers then dynamited the vehicle and fled in a truck,
the police said, adding that 100 people were arrested in sweeps of
the area after the killings.
   Gregory, a graduate of the University of California at Santa
Cruz, was the second American to die in the Shining Path's
eight-year insurgency to impose Marxist rule. Dozens of Peruvian
development workers have been among more than 10,000 people killed
in the violence.
   A Texas woman was one of seven passengers killed in a Shining
Path bombing of a tourist train in June 1986.
</TEXT>
