<HEAD>Copeland Named as Ambassador to Niger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan intends to nominate Carl
Copeland Cundiff, a career Foreign Service officer, to be
ambassador to the Republic of Niger, the White House announced
Thursday.
   Cundiff, 47, entered the service in 1965. From 1966-68 he was
assigned to the American Embassy in Singapore. He was an economist
for the Agency for International Development in Saigon from
1968-69; the U.S. Mission to the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development in Paris from 1970-73; and the monetary
affairs bureau of the State Department from 1974-77.
   Since 1986, Cundiff has been office director in the office of
food and policy programs for the economic bureau of the State
Department.
   Cundiff, a New Orleans native, graduated from the University of
the South in 1963, Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy in 1964 and
Harvard Kennedy School of Government in 1974.
