<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bagpipes-Hearing     06-16 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bagpipes-Hearing,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Playing Bagpipes Can Damage Hearing, Study Suggests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High noise levels from bagpipes can knock a
Scotsman's hearing out of kilter _ and even cause permanent hearing
loss, a neurologist and amateur bagpiper said Thursday.
   Dr. Stephen M. Brittain of Rutland, Vt., and audiologist Robert
W. Hartenstein measured noise levels produced by the bagpipes and
reported their findings in a letter in the June issue of the
Archives of Otolaryngology-Head and Neck Surgery.
   Indoor and outdoor levels at the player's left ear reached up to
105 decibels, they wrote.
   Noting that federal noise exposure maximums are 105 decibels for
one hour and 115 decibels for 15 minutes, they said it would be
fairly easy for pipers to meet or exceed these limits ``with
steady, dedicated practice.''
   Good quality foam ear plugs can sharply cut noise levels, they
said.
   Brittain, who said he had been playing the pipes about three
years, became concerned when he found playing the pipes was almost
a painful experience at first.
   He said he started wearing earplugs, but believes few pipers are
aware of the risks of permanent hearing loss and few probably wear
ear protection.
   He said the ear protection he wears reduces the sound level
about 25 decibels and does not interfere with hearing and
evaluating his own playing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 2229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Singleton     06-16 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singleton,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mutilation Rapist Offered Money to Get Out of Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mutilation rapist Larry Singleton was offered
$10,000, living expenses and a one-way ticket out of Florida on
Thursday by a car dealer and a radio station anxious to get him out
of town.
   In a full-page newspaper ad, Bradenton car dealer Tom Stimus
offered $5,000 and volunteered to pay rent and utilities for six
months _ at a non-Florida address _ for the 60-year-old former
merchant seaman.
   Stimus, 49, previously has offered rewards for the assassination
of Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi and Iran's Ayatollah Khomeini,
with no takers.
   St. Petersburg's WQYK-FM matched Stimus' $5,000 offer after 99
percent of hundreds of listeners responding to an on-air poll said
they wanted Singleton to leave, said station spokeswoman Diana
Thomas.
   Singleton served eight years of a 14-year sentence in California
for raping a 15-year-old hitchhiker, chopping off her forearms with
an ax and leaving her for dead in a ditch near San Francisco in
1978.
   He finished parole in April and recently moved back to Florida
where he has family. He grew up in the Tampa Bay area.
   Singleton registered with state authorities Monday to comply
with Florida law that any felon moving into the state must list his
address. He gave his brother Walter's address in the Forest Hills
area.
   When they found out Singleton was their neighbor, residents of
the quiet, middle-class area said they were angry and afraid. More
than 40 of them met Wednesday night and started a petition drive
demanding that he move out.
   ``We are being asked to change our life styles because of one
lunatic,'' said Dick Sells, 42.
   Several residents said they would no longer allow their children
to go out alone.
   One resident said, however, that Singleton's relatives said
Singleton isn't living in Forest Hills, but is using his brother's
address while living 2{ hours away from Tampa.
   Some residents expressed fears not only of Singleton, but also
of misguided vigilantism. Lester Heitlinger, 66, has a gray beard _
as does Singleton.
   ``Anybody with a gray beard that walks by is a suspect,'' he
said.
   California officials seeking to place Singleton during his
parole were met by community protests, and local law enforcement
officials said they feared they could not guarantee his safety.
   Singleton finally served his parole time while living in a
mobile home within the gates of San Quentin state prison.
</TEXT>
