<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SpaceStation 1stLd-Writethru a0798 06-16 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Station, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0798,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Slashes Funds for Space Station</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf bgng, `In the,' to include dropped word
`million'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel voted Thursday to slash
spending for the space station to $200 million, a move officials
said will strangle the program unless the appropriation is
increased dramatically.
   The Reagan administration had requested $967 million for the
space station in the next fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1.
Officials say at least $900 million is needed to keep the space
station on schedule for a completion in the late 1990s.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said $200 million ``provides only
enough for the slow strangulation of the space station'' and that
President Reagan's personal intervention will be needed to rescue
the program.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said he would ask Reagan to veto the
spending bill that includes funds for the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration if not enough money is set aside to sustain
the space station.
   The NASA money is part of a spending bill that also includes
funds for the Veterans Administration, the Department of Housing
and Urban Development and other agencies.
   ``I am hopeful that we may yet in the Senate do something to
correct this situation, but it is an uphill battle,'' Gramm said.
   Gramm called the Senate action, as well as the House version of
the space station bill earlier this week, ``totally irresponsible.''
   ``In this election year, Congress is clearly looking at the next
election and not the next generation,'' Gramm said.
   The Senate committee's space station bill calls on the next
administration to review the project in January and if the new
president wants it to continue, he would have to ask Congress for
additional funds. NASA has estimated the project could cost more
than $20 billion to complete.
   In the House version, the Appropriations Committee voted this
week to spend $387 million on research and development on the space
station. Another $65.4 million would be held in an account, and
should the next president decide not to continue with the program,
those funds would be used to shut down the program.
   Additionally, $450 million would be held through April 15. If
the president decides to continue with the program, the money would
go to the space station. If not, $150 million would be transferred
to space flight control and data communications at NASA, and the
remaining $300 million would be rescinded.
   ``The House approach _ to fence part of money and wait to see if
new president wants to have a viable space program _ is passing the
buck, to say the least,'' Gramm said.
   ``Our problem clearly is that there are other programs with
large numbers of constitutents more appealing politically than
programs such as space and science. And we've been seeing this over
and over for the last three years,'' Gramm said.
   Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said construction of the space station
could begin next year if it stays on schedule. The space station is
planned to be in orbit around Earth and occupied by astronauts by
the end of 1996.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0209 </DOCNO>
