<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua     06-16 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Charge Contras With Cease-Fire Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Ministry said Thursday
that rebels attacked a military unit in violation of a cease-fire
and kidnapped six civilians.
   A ministry statement said two soldiers were killed and three
wounded when rebels ambushed three Sandinista army trucks in
northern Jinotega province Wednesday.
   It said six civilians were kidnapped in various parts of the
country.
   The U.S.-supported rebels, known as Contras, and the leftist
Sandinista government agreed to suspend offensive military
operations on March 21, when talks began which led to an agreement
to seek a definitive cease-fire in the civil war. The two sides
have made little progress since then.
   The Contras have accused the Sandinistas of violating the truce.
   Defense Minister Humberto Ortega accused the rebels of
``flagrant violations of the cease-fire'' in a letter sent Thursday
to Joao Baena Soares, secretary-general of the Organization of
American States, and Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo,
the archbishop of Managua.
   Soares and Obando y Bravo served as witnesses to the
Sandinista-Contra peace talks and are responsible for verifying the
cease-fire accords.
   Ortega, brother of President Daniel Ortega and head of the
government negotiating team, also noted that Contra leaders were
seeking renewed military aid from the United States in violation of
the agreements.
   In Washington, Alfredo Cesar, a member of the Contra
directorate, told reporters Thursday the Reagan administration
agreed to seek a new aid package for the rebels, who have been
fighting the Sandinistas for six years.
   Ortega asked Soares and Obando y Bravo to investigate the
civilian kidnappings. The government claims the Contras have
kidnapped more than 1,000 Nicaraguans. The rebels have acknowledged
holding 66.
   Ortega also criticized a rebel proposal to include President
Oscar Arias of Costa Rica in future peace talks.
   Arias received the Nobel Peace Prize last year for being the
author of a regional peace plan signed by five Central American
presidents last August.
</TEXT>
