<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-SouthAfrica     06-16 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-South Africa,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary-General Appeals For Clemency for Sharpeville Six</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
appealed to South Africa on Thursday, the 12th anniversary of the
Soweto riots there, to grant clemency to six blacks awaiting
execution.
   The Pretoria government's determination to hang the
``Sharpeville Six,'' who were convicted of taking part in a 1984
riot in which a black Sharpeville town councilor was killed, has
provoked worldwide appeals to spare their lives.
   ``In view of the decision by the South African judiciary to
extend the stay of execution to July 19 but not to reopen the
trial, the secretary-general appeals once again on humanitarian
grounds to President (P.W.) Botha to grant clemency to these young
people,'' said Francois Giuliani, spokesman for Perez de Cuellar.
   The U.N. chief first asked Botha on March 15 to grant clemency.
   President Reagan and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain
were among other world leaders who protested the hangings, which
were postponed in March just 15 hours before the scheduled
execution.
   The Sharpeville Six, ranging in age from 24 to 36, were not
proven to have physically attacked the official, but were convicted
of having ``common purpose'' with the slayers.
   U.N. officials devoted Thursday to special observances of Soweto
Day, commemorating July 16, 1976, when police attacked
schoolchildren in the black township of Soweto, near Johannesburg,
who were marching to demand edicational reform.
   Ten marchers, including two students, died in the attack. The
incident set off a nationwide rampage in which hundreds of South
African blacks were killed.
   Perez de Cuellar spoke before the U.N. Special Committee Against
Apartheid on Thursday to condemn South Africa's legal system of
racial segregation: ``Apartheid is not a system that can be
reformed _ it must be ended,'' he said.
   General Assembly President Peter Florin of East Germany told the
committee that ``all those who still argue that apartheid could be
removed by way of reforms should at last have been taught
otherwise. ... Apartheid can only be eradicated.''
</TEXT>
