<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0829EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-TV-Wiseman Adv17   06-16 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV-Wiseman, Adv 17,0575</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, June 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-AP on TV-Deaf and Blind</HEAD>
<HEAD>From `Titicut Follies' to Alabama Institute for Deaf and Blind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Alabama Institute
for Deaf and Blind hopes a four-part documentary by filmmaker
Frederick Wiseman will inspire change to benefit the handicapped
everywhere.
   ``I think it will sensitize many Americans to the uniqueness of
the disabled, the frustrations and challenges of the deaf and
blind,'' said Jack Hawkins, president of the institute.
   ``Over the longer term,'' he said, ``the film may make a major
contribution in the professional perception of those who choose to
work in these fields.''
   The series, which has been seen only at film festivals and at
theaters in the New York and Boston area, reaches a national
audience for the first time tonight with the opening installment,
``Blind,'' on public television.
   Wiseman's stark look inside a Massachusetts mental hospital two
decades ago helped transform the care of the nation's mentally ill.
This look inside the institute at Talladega is part of a series of
documentaries on American institutions.
   When he told a friend he wanted to do a film on the disabled as
part of that series, Wiseman explained in a telephone interview, he
was told the Alabama institute was ``one of the best schools in the
country.''
   He filmed for about six weeks at the Talladega complex, which
was founded in 1858 and has grown into a multi-purpose program that
provides kindergarten through 12th-grade academics, competitive
athletics, vocational training as well as special skills training
for the deaf, blind and multi-handicapped of all ages.
   Wiseman said he received ``complete cooperation'' from the
institute and its staff as his camera recorded the anguishing
difficulties and daily personal heroism of the handicapped and
their teachers.
   ``I was impressed by the kindness and compassion,'' said Wiseman.
   In 1967, Wiseman's film ``Titicut Follies'' reported graphically
on the degrading living conditions and dehumanizing treatment of
the mentally ill at a Massachusetts state hospital. The widely
acclaimed film helped draw attention to what amounted to a national
problem as litigation to reform mental health care spread to many
states, including Alabama.
   Wiseman disagees with those who view his work as cause-oriented
filming aiming only to expose one problem or another.
   ``I think that was a bum rap,'' said Wiseman. ``I report on the
experience I had in making the film.''
   He said ``Titicut Follies'' turned out to be ``quite extreme.''
In contrast, he said, the experience at the Alabama institute was
good.
   ``I report on what I find,'' he said.
   Hawkins said he was not aware of the controversial nature of
``Titicut Follies'' when he opened the doors of the Alabama
institute to Wiseman. But even after learning about the filmmaker's
previous work, he said, ``we felt comfortable that our program
could withstand his scrutiny.''
   Hawkins said Wiseman and his crew seemed to become part of the
normal environment. ``They were the most unassuming, unintrusive
and unimposing people I've ever seen,'' he said.
   Wiseman ``recorded the human drama and the boredom of life
itself,'' Hawkins said. ``He did a great job of capturing what
deafness and blindness are all about. We just happened to be the
vehicle for him to use.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, June 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
