<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1455EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-AIDS-EmptyChairs Adv19-2Takes   06-16 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AIDS-Empty Chairs, Adv 19-2 Takes,0784</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Educator's Struggle to End Parish's Denial, Begin Christian Caring</BYLINE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. cardinals meet this month to renew debate
over what to teach Catholics about AIDS. But if the struggles of a
trailblazing religious education director in an affluent Chicago
parish are any indication, the debate goes deeper than the
much-publicized condom furor. AIDS is shaking ordinary
parishioners' deepest religious convictions and raising a central
question: is the church fundamentally about love or judgment?
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTHBROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Ann Clemens _ nurse, hospital
chaplain, mother of five and Catholic educator _ once wrote a verse
about trying to teach her unusual gospel of AIDS in this affluent
Chicago suburb.
   ``Behold,
   ``The empty chairs and
   ``the quickened pace to run.
   ``Away from me who waits to
   ``Reveal love over judgment,
   ``Knowledge over ignorance,
   ``Healing through reconciliation.
   ``AIDS ministers embrace an EXILED station.
   ``Behold, the empty chairs.''
   For six years, Mrs. Clemens has been director of religious
education at Our Lady of The Brook, a church set on 11 acres of
lush lawns and generous parking lots.
   To most in Northbrook, AIDS is as vague and distant as a foreign
war on the evening news. But in 1986, a friend of Mrs. Clemens
revealed his homosexuality and began drinking heavily because he
feared getting AIDS. Later, she heard from some parents that their
children were trying ``alternative life-styles,'' including
homosexuality.
   Mrs. Clemens came to believe that this conservative, sheltered
parish could no longer ignore the disease.
   She spent 16 months writing an AIDS curriculum expressly for
Catholic parents, ``From Fr-AIDS to Faith: Let Us Talk About
AIDS.'' Told in story form, blending gospel with realism about sex,
drugs and AIDS, it was designed to help parents explain the disease
to their children.
   For fourth- through sixth-graders, for example, there is a
graphic discussion of bodily fluids, how AIDS is and is not spread,
sex and marriage.
   Suddenly this past school year, sleepy suburban Northbrook found
itself an improbable beacon of AIDS education.
   Her parish priest, Sunday school teachers and parents use words
like ``pioneer,'' ``visionary,'' even ``prophet,'' to describe Mrs.
Clemens, who argues that AIDS is a cataclysmic ethical and medical
event that raises centuries-old questions over whether the essence
of Roman Catholicism is love or judgment.
   Despite the outward adulation, however, her AIDS gospel has been
largely ignored. She sent her curriculum to about 400 families in
her parish, but only three accepted her offer for discussions.
   ``Our homophobia is making us deny that the disease belongs to
all of us,'' she said.
   She got brief national attention when she spoke about her
curriculum at the National Catholic Education Association's
convention in New York in April. She was subsequently invited to
address other Chicago-area parishes, but attracted only tiny
audiences.
   The problems she and fellow teachers have found within the
church, in some ways as intractable as the HIV virus itself, are
denial and indifference among parishioners and ambiguity and
division in church policy.
   This month, she decided to leave her parish post to devote all
her time to AIDS missionary work.
   The story of what happened when Mary Ann Clemens tried to get
AIDS discussed in Northbrook tells much about the confusion and
moral contradictions the disease presents for Catholic educators
everywhere.
   ``AIDS,'' said Mrs. Clemens, echoing the sentiments of many
church members, ``is creating havoc for the Catholic church.''
   In one sense, her parish was fertile ground for trailblazing.
The Chicago archdiocese, led by Cardinal Joseph Bernardin, is
comparatively liberal. Last December, when U.S. Catholic bishops
issued a landmark statement on AIDS education that included mention
of condoms, Bernardin was a chief proponent.
   The statement drew fire from traditionalists led by New York
Cardinal John J. O'Connor. The nation's 300 bishops have agreed to
meet in Collegeville, Minn., June 24-27 to discuss the issue again.
   Mrs. Clemens, though often critical of what she considers the
church's lack of realism about AIDS, never ran afoul of the
archdiocese. Sister Anne Leonard, director of Catholic Services of
the Chicago archdiocese, and others in the hierarchy have praised
her and her curriculum.
   Her pronouncements have sometimes challenged the bounds of
acceptable dogma, as when she told a gathering of nuns, priests and
lay religious teachers at the convention: ``If a kid tells me he's
sexually active, I give condom information. I'll tell him how to
put it on.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880616-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1456EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-AIDS-EmptyChairs Adv19-1stAdd   06-16 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AIDS-Empty Chairs, Adv 19-1st Add,0777</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>NORTHBROOK: it on.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The heart of her AIDS message, however, is not condoms but the
Good Samaritan parable, Luke 10:25-37, directing Christians not to
judge their suffering neighbors but to care for them.
   ``Let God do the judging,'' said Mrs. Clemens.
   Meanwhile, Northbrook parishioners were getting mixed signals
from their pastor. Father Robert Herne, who has generally supported
Mrs. Clemens' AIDS mission and who agrees the church should be
compassionate, says it nevertheless should not shrink from calling
a sin a sin.
   Herne wrote some verse of his own in a church bulletin:
   ``What used to be called chastity is now called neurotic
inhibition ... What used to be called perversion is now called
alternative lifestyle. What used to be called depravity is now
called creative self-expression.''
   ``She says God is love,'' Herne said of Mrs. Clemens. ``I say
amen to that. But everything people do is not OK.''
   Herne said he agreed with Mrs. Clemens that the church should
soften its finger-wagging image and the perception it does not
welcome homosexuals who contract AIDS.
   ``We're not against homosexuals,'' said Herne. ``But we seem to
be on the moral side, and less on the compassionate and
understanding side.''
   Mrs. Clemens' work comes as Catholic educators scramble to
devise lessons about AIDS.
   The NCEA has until August to complete an AIDS curriculum for
parochial schools to use in the new school year. It is likely to
discuss, but not condone, condom use.
   The Chicago archdiocese devised its own AIDS curriculum, which
will be introduced this fall. Led by Sister Leonard, the
archdiocese enlisted experts from Northwestern University and
elsewhere to help train parochial teachers.
   Mrs. Clemens contends that Catholic educators hold an untapped
advantage over public schools in their ability to imbue AIDS
lessons with religion.
   ``Jesus tells us a story in Luke that helps us know how to treat
persons who are sick, especially persons with AIDS,'' says her
curriculum, referring to the Good Samaritan story and using
language that would be beyond constitutional bounds in public
schools.
   In talking to children in her parish she discovered it was these
matters of the heart that puzzled them most.
   ``They would ask me, `Why does the school nurse wear rubber
gloves now?' or `What if somebody falls down at school and bleeds.
Can I still help them?'''
   But to most Northbrook youngsters, AIDS remains remote.
   ``I told my kids, `When you go to college next year, how are you
going to know who you're with?''' said Maureen Dondlinger, who
teaches religious classes for teens at Our Lady of the Brook. ``But
the trouble is, AIDS is not here. The kids have a real hard time
connecting to it.''
   Did Mrs. Clemens really expect to succeed?
   ``It wasn't a matter of whether I believed parents would use
it,'' she said. ``I wanted to give them the tools. I feel much
better that parents do the teaching.''
   At least as worrisome as the laity's denial of AIDS, said Mrs.
Clemens, is the lack of thought toward moral and emotional
preparation for parochial teachers being called upon to teach about
AIDS.
   ``You're going to be giving a curriculum to a whole bunch of
volunteer teachers who haven't thought out where they're coming
from,'' she said.
   ``Not every educator should be doing this. If you do not have
the heart for this, please be free enough not to do it. Students
don't want a one-shot filmstrip.
   ``Parents are hungry for a workable sexual theology. The
hierarchy wants to do that, but they are writing from a male
celibate perspective. That's not a criticism. That's a fact,'' she
said.
   John Sloan, who attended Mrs. Clemens' AIDS lessons with his
10-year-old son, Kirk, said he was glad of any help he could get in
explaining AIDS and sexuality.
   ``It's good to have the Church involved in something like
this,'' he said.
   ``I, like other parents, was hesitant to bring up AIDS with my
kids,'' said another parent, Joey Buck. ``Mary Ann took a little
pressure off us.''
   How does Mrs. Clemens feel about the church as she prepares to
leave her parish post?
   ``Love-hate. Sometimes it frustrates me,'' she said. ``The
institution teaches me patience. It teaches me damage control. But
I have hit an institutional wall not only in this parish, but in
this church.
   ``On the AIDS issue, I needed the freedom to speak.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
