<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-16 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0557</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deficit in the broadest measure of U.S.
foreign trade widened in the first quarter to $39.75 billion as the
first deficit in investment earnings in 30 years offset a sharp
improvement in the merchandise trade balance, the government has
reported.
   The quarterly imbalance in the country's current account balance
surged 18.6 percent from the fourth quarter's $33.5 billion, the
Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
   The current account is the most important trade statistic,
because it covers not only merchandise trade but also trade in the
services category, which reflects primarily the flow of investment
earnings between countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales grew a lackluster 0.1 percent in
May, the government said in a report analysts predicted should help
ease fears of inflationary pressures in the economy.
   On Wednesday, the Commerce Department said sales by retailers,
which represent about one-third of U.S. economic activity, edged up
a scant 0.1 percent in May to $131.9 billion, after a 0.4 percent
drop in April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boom in the manufacture of business
equipment and a pickup at auto plants helped boost U.S. industrial
production by a moderate 0.4 percent in May, the government says.
   It was the eighth month in a row without a decline in an index
measuring output at the nation's factories, mines and utilities,
and a further sign of the resurgence of U.S. manufacturing.
   The Federal Reserve said Wednesday the May advance followed an
April gain of 0.6 percent, revised slightly from a previous
estimate of 0.7 percent.
   Overall industrial production now stands 6.1 percent higher than
a year ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The working mother has made the transition
from novelty to national norm, with more than half of new mothers
remaining in the job market for the first time, the Census Bureau
reported Wednesday.
   The labor force participation rate for new mothers climbed to
50.8 percent last year from 49.8 percent in 1986, marking the first
time a majority of women reported they were working or actively
seeking employment within a year of giving birth.
   Only 31 percent of new mothers were counted in the labor force
in 1976, the first year the Census Bureau sought to calculate this
rate.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Iowa cattle farmers mowed roadside ditches for feed as the
drought in the nation's midsection pushed prices skyward on
commodity exchanges.
   About 750 barges were stranded on the Mississippi River due to
low water, and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers said twice as many
could be stranded by the weekend.
   Rain fell in Kansas, Missouri and Illinois, but the National
Weather Service said Wednesday it wouldn't be enough to make up for
weeks of dry weather. Temperatures remained in the high 80s and 90s
across much of the nation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said Japan has
gained the status of an economic power, and it is his
responsibility to assert that role at next week's economic summit
in Toronto.
   Takeshita said Wednesday his goals at the summit are to discuss
cooperation on trade, resolving the problems of international debt
and restoring self-sustained growth to developing countries.
</TEXT>
