<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0516</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co. has sweetened its offer for
rival Irving Bank Corp., slightly raising the stock portion of the
bid and adding other shareholder incentives, including a special
cash dividend.
   But some banking analysts on Wednesday predicted Irving
management would continue snubbing its persistent suitor in favor
of a friendly merger with Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's
second-largest bank.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady valued the revised bid for
all of Irving's 18.5 million shares outstanding at around $1.4
billion, about 25 percent higher than the existing hostile $1.1
billion tender offer which remains in place.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An increasing number of insurance companies
are offering substantial premium discounts to the owners of cars
equipped with air bags, the Transportation Department says.
   Discounts for personal injury or medical premiums at 12 auto
insurance companies range from 15 percent to 60 percent on cars in
which air bags protect the driver in a collision, the department
said Wednesday.
   It cautioned, however, that the discounts are not available in
Hawaii, Massachusetts, North Carolina, Texas, Illinois and Kentucky.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. is
expected to launch a major new family of mid-sized computers next
week, and its nearest rival is preparing for a long, hard fight for
customers.
   Digital Equipment Corp., the world's No. 2 computer maker, sent
executives to meet the press Wednesday and prepare the groundwork
for a response to the IBM computer family code-named Silverlake.
   The skirmishing indicated the importance of next Tuesday's
announcement to the vast midsection of the computer industry, the
machines that fit in between personal computers and giant
mainframes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. says it is getting out of the
specialty retailing business altogether and plans to sell the
profitable Ann Taylor division of its Allied Stores Corp.
   ``We intend to focus our efforts and attention on the future of
our department store franchises,'' Allied chairman John W. Burden
III stated Wednesday.
   Campeau did not announce an asking price for the chain.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KOUROU, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Space Agency has sent
three satellites into orbit on the first Ariane 4, a powerful new
rocket it hopes will provide a competitive edge in the race to
commercialize space.
   Officials of Arianespace, the agency's commercial arm,
proclaimed Wednesday's inaugural launch ``a complete success.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished higher Wednesday, solidifying sharp
gains posted in the previous session. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials, which jumped 25 points Tuesday, rose another 6.93
points to close at 2,131.40, its second post-crash high in as many
days.
   Bond prices declined on profit taking following a rally Tuesday.
   The dollar closed narrowly mixed.
   Grain and soybean prices shot up the daily maximum, while
livestock and meat futures fell their limits as the drought
continued weighing heavily on the nation's commodities markets.
</TEXT>
