<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-16 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Optimism about OPEC's extension of its
production-limiting pact proved fleeting in the futures market, as
a one-day rally fizzled.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, lost 30 cents to
settle at $16.53 per barrel on Wednesday.
   The contract had gained 40 cents Tuesday in response to the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' decision to extend
its current production quotas for six months.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline
dropped 0.30 cent a gallon to 49.23 cents and home heating oil
declined 0.90 cent to close at 43.42 cents a gallon. Both contracts
had advanced along with crude in the previous session.
   ``A lot of questions remain about a rollover agreement (on OPEC
quotas), when the basic agreement wasn't being maintained,'' said
Bob Baker of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Concerns about cheating among OPEC producers resurfaced quickly
in the market when traders failed to follow through on Tuesday's
rally, Baker explained.
   Members of the 13-nation cartel ended their mid-year meeting in
Vienna, Austria, on Tuesday. Their agreement extends what had been
regarded as a nearly meaningless quota system, which limits 12 of
the producers to 15.06 million barrels a day.
   Iraq has refused to sign the accord because it wants a quota
equal to that of its war enemy, Iran.
   Actual daily OPEC production is estimated at 18.5 million
barrels.
   Expectations of tight supplies through the summer helped keep
gasoline prices from losing as much ground as other products in
Wednesday's trading, analysts said.
</TEXT>
