<DOCNO> AP880616-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-06-16-88 0042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TradeDeficit Bjt   06-16 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade Deficit, Bjt,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Is Shrinking, Latest Statistic Notwithstanding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economists say the nation's trade deficit is
shrinking decisively, in spite of a government report indicating
that the broadest measure of trade worsened in the first three
months of the year.
   At first, Wednesday's negative report on the current account
imbalance seemed to contradict the report of a day earlier that the
merchandise trade deficit fell in April to its lowest point since
December 1984.
   But economists said the bad news was old news. In truth, they
said, the United States is well on the way to closing the gap
between exports and imports.
   ``The trade deficit is on the mend in a fairly substantial
way,'' said Thomas F. Carpenter, director of economics for ASB
Capital Management in Washington.
   The Commerce Department sparked a strong rally in the financial
markets Tuesday when it announced that the April merchandise trade
deficit shrank to $9.89 billion, far smaller than expectations.
   On Wednesday, the news seemed to sour when the department said
the deficit in the broadest measure of trade, the current account,
widened in the January-March period to $39.75 billion, up 18.6
percent from $33.5 billion in the last quarter of 1987.
   But financial markets shrugged off the negative report, which
referred to trade news from early in the year that was superseded
by the strong April results.
   Nevertheless, bewilderment over the seeming contradiction
between the numbers was understandable, said Stuart Hoffman, senior
economist of PNC Financial Corp. in Pittsburgh.
   ``It's confusing to economists. The rest of the people must be
that much more confused,'' he said.
   The one dark spot in Wednesday's current account report was that
the United States ran its first deficit in investment income in 30
years during the first quarter.
   The red ink in investment income was the result of foreigners'
accumulations of huge holdings of U.S. assets in recent years. For
the first time, Americans had to pay out more in interest,
dividends and rents to foreigners than they received on their
holdings abroad.
   But the deficit on investment income did not disturb financial
markets, because it was a predictable outcome of the persistent
merchandise trade deficits.
   The investment income deficit is certain to get bigger in coming
months because foreigners will continue adding to their holdings of
U.S. assets as long as they run trade surpluses with the United
States.
   ``We're making progress on the trade front. But because we have
such a large deficit, we're still piling up claims against us at a
very rapid rate,'' said Robert G. Dederick, executive vice
president and chief economist of Northern Trust Co. in Chicago.
   The deterioration in the investment income account will not end
until the United States starts running surpluses in merchandise
trade.
   That is likely to happen around the middle of the 1990s, said
Roger Kubarych, an economist at the consulting firm of Henry
Kaufman & Co.
   Carpenter of ASB Capital Management thinks it could happen far
sooner than that. ``We will start having monthly surpluses within
12 to 15 months,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
