<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Campeau-AnnTaylor Bjt   06-16 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campeau-Ann Taylor, Bjt,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campeau Selling Ann Taylor, Getting Out of Specialty Retailing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp.'s plans to sell its profitable Ann
Taylor clothing chain will sever Campeau's ties to the specialty
retailing business, and continue the asset sales needed to help pay
for its recent acquisitions.
   Campeau decided to sell the chain because it has ``different
customers, a different real estate base, a different buying
structure'' than Campeau's nine department store divisions, Joele
Frank, a Campeau spokeswoman, said Wednesday.
   Ann Taylor, with 103 upscale women's clothing stores across the
country, was the last specialty division remaining in Allied Stores
Corp., which Campeau acquired at the end of 1986.
   Last month, Campeau sold Allied's Brooks Brothers chain to help
finance the purchase of Federated Department Stores Inc.
   A source close to Campeau said Allied already has received
interest in Ann Taylor, which had 1987 sales of $249 million.
Campeau did not announce an asking price for the chain.
   Wednesday's announcement came less than a week after Campeau
said it was selling Federated's Filene's Basement specialty store
division. Campeau chairman Robert Campeau also plans to sell two
other Federated specialty chains, Children's Place and Main Street,
as well as its Gold Circle discount store chain.
   Thomas Tashjian, a retail industry analyst with Seidler Amdec
Securities Inc. in Los Angeles, said of Ann Taylor, ``It's actually
a gem.''
   ``It's very unfortunate that he's deleting it from his
portfolio,'' Tashjian said, ``but I can understand from the higher
(real estate) asset value from department stores that he would want
to preserve those and develop that area rather than the
lease-oriented Ann Taylor chain.''
   Analysts have said Campeau, a real estate developer, was
interested in Allied and Federated mainly because of their real
estate holdings. Ann Taylor generally leases its retail space.
   The sale of Ann Taylor leaves Allied with four department store
chains: Stern's, Jordan Marsh, the Bon and Maas Brothers. Most of
Allied's store divisions were sold after Campeau took it over, and
the Brook's Brothers specialty chain was sold after Campeau took
control of Federated.
   Proceeds from the previous sales were use to retire debt from
the $3.4 billion Allied purchase, while funds from the sale of
Brooks Brothers went toward the total $8.8 billion Campeau is
spending for Federated.
   In its announcement Wednesday, Campeau said some of the proceeds
from an Ann Taylor sale also would be used to retire bank loans.
Allied would use the remainder of the money to purchase shares in
Federated, which in turn would use the funds to further reduce its
own debt.
   Allied and Federated will be operated under the same management
but will remain separate legal entities, Campeau said.
   Campeau has said it expects to retain Federated's
Bloomingdale's, Goldsmith's, Lazarus, Burdine's, Abraham and Straus
and Rich's department store chains, as well as its Ralphs
supermarkets division in California.
   Goldsmith's and Rich's have been merged into a single division.
</TEXT>
