<2ND_LINE>BC-Bank Merger,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Centerre Accepts Boatmen's Buyout Offer Of $467 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Centerre Bancorporation has accepted a $60 a
share stock swap merger offer worth about $467 million from
Boatmen's Bancshares Inc., Missouri's biggest bank holding company,
the companies announced Wednesday.
   Centerre, which in April had announced a $37 a share stock swap
merger agreement with Mercantile Bancorporation Inc., in May
received a counter-offer of $50 a share, or a total of about $390,
from Boatmen's.
   Boatmen's later that month raised its offer to $55 a share.
   ``Our board carefully considered various merger and acquisition
alternatives and concluded that Boatmen's offer was in the best
interest of Centerre shareholders,'' said Clarence C. Barksdale,
Centerre's chairman and chief executive officer.
   All three bank holding companies are based in St. Louis.
   If the acquisition is completed, the statement said, Boatmen's
will become the nation's 41st largest bank-holding company, with
assets of about $14.7 billion and a trust business worth $33
billion.
   The proposed acquisition is subject to approval by the
shareholders of both companies and by the appropriate regulatory
authorities.
   Barksdale and John Peters MacCarthy, president of Centerre, will
become vice chairmen of Boatmen's, the statement said. Centerre
Trust Co. will continue to operate as a separate subsidiary as
Boatmen's Trust Co. with the ultimate objective of consolidating
all trust functions, it said.
   As of March 31, Boatmen's had assets of $9.59 billion and
Centerre, the state's fourth largest bank-holding company, had
assets of $5.12 billion.
</TEXT>
