<2ND_LINE>AM-UAW-General Dynamics, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0285,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Settles With General Dynamics Division, Averting Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with settlement, editing to conform.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bargainers for the United Auto Workers and
General Dynamics Corp.'s Land Systems Division reached a three-year
contract settlement late Wednesday night, averting a midnight
strike at the defense contractor.
   The two sides put the finishing touches on a settlement covering
6,000 workers that includes a drug testing program UAW Vice
President Marc Stepp said would be mutually satisfying to the union
and the company.
   Details of the tentative agreement were not immediately
released, although Stepp said it included a substantial pay
increase and a ratification bonus, along with improvements in
health and safety provisions.
   ``Overall we were very happy,'' Stepp told a late night news
conference. ``We dealt with the substance abuse matter. Our members
will agree to that I'm quite sure.''
   Stepp said the contract would be explained to the workers
represented by the UAW at the Land Systems Division, a tank-making
operation that General Dynamics bought from Chrysler Corp. in 1982.
The division has plants in the Detroit suburbs of Sterling Heights
and Warren and at Scranton, Pa., and Lima, Ohio.
   About 1,000 of the division's workers are on layoff.
   A ratification vote will take place in another seven to 10 days,
the union said.
   The union had sought a 3 percent-per-year increase in the
$13-an-hour base wage at General Dynamics and increased union
representation to help workers with benefit questions, Stepp said.
   Stepp said the company sought to reduce the number of job
classifications, or strict definitions of individual jobs, and more
flexibility in its use of workers.
   Stepp said earlier that drug abuse was not a widespread problem
in General Dynamics plants.
   General Dynamics and the union have a pilot Employee Assistance
Program at the Detroit Tank Plant in Warren. Like similar programs
at General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler, the
professionally administered program uses counseling and education
to help workers with drug and other problems.
   Stepp said the union wants the EAP expanded to other Land
Systems Division plants.
   General Dynamics was required to accept Chrysler's UAW contract
when it purchased the Land Systems Division, and a contract
negotiated in 1985 closely resembled Big Three auto contracts.
   Talks on a new three-year contract began April 11, Stepp said.
</TEXT>
