<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AlleghenyInternational     06-16 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Allegheny International,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Way Cleared For Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has given Allegheny
International Inc. approval to file a bankruptcy reorganization
plan.
   The 3rd Circuit Court of Appeals in Philadelphia also said that
management may count votes cast at a shareholders meeting next week
and announce the results immediately.
   The court, which handed down its ruling Tuesday, previously had
said the appliance maker could do none of those things without
court permission.
   Allegheny International spokesman Edward Romanoff said
management plans to file a reorganization plan by the end of the
month, but he declined to specify whether the filing would precede
a shareholders' meeting June 20, when votes are to be cast for
board seats.
   ``The sooner the company emerges from Chapter 11, the stronger
it will be,'' Chairman Oliver S. Travers said Wednesday.
   Under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws, a company is
protected from its creditors while it reorganizes.
   Management and a shareholders group, led by the New York
investment firm Spear, Leeds & Kellogg, are fueding over how to
allocate the company's resources in satisfying its obligations.
   The dissident shareholders group is also challenging management
for control of the board. Seven seats, a majority, are open.
   Irwin L. Jacobs, the company's largest shareholder, said
Wednesday that he is siding with the investment banking company in
its bid to take control of the board. The previously uncommitted
Jacobs heads an investor group that owns 9 percent of Allegheny
International's 10.8 million common shares.
   Separately, Victor Kiam, chairman of Remington Products Inc.,
said Wednesday he told Spear, Leeds & Kellogg he would be
interested in helping them form a reorganization plan for Allegheny
International.
   Kiam, who has been involved in reorganizations of several
consumer products companies, said he would meet with Allegheny
International's management if invited, said Remington spokesman
William Cavior.
   Allegheny International owns Sunbeam, Oster and other appliance
and leisure products companies.
