<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UAW-GeneralDynamics     06-16 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UAW-General Dynamics,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW, General Dynamics Contract Contains Drug Testing Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative settlement reached between the
United Auto Workers union and General Dynamics' Land Systems
Division is one of the first major labor contracts to contain a
drug-testing policy, a union official says.
   The settlement, covering 6,000 workers at Land Systems Division
plants in the Detroit suburbs of Sterling Heights and Warren, and
at Scranton, Pa., and Lima, Ohio, was announced less than 20
minutes before Wednesday's midnight strike deadline.
   ``We dealt with the substance abuse matter in a manner that is
satisfactory to us. Our members will agree to that I'm quite
sure,'' UAW Vice President Marc Stepp told a news conference. ``All
in all we are very happy.''
   Stepp said the contract's approach, one of the first of its
kind, ``deals with the rehabilitation aspects'' of drug abuse and
will not mean that any workers will have to submit to random or
mandatory drug testing.
   Earlier Wednesday, Stepp said the union would not agree with the
company's demand for random, mandatory drug testing. He said
details of the program have to be worked out, then explained to
workers along with the rest of the contract. He said members would
vote within the next seven to 10 days.
   Company officials were equally as pleased with the agreement on
drug testing.
   ``As we all know, it's a national problem,'' said Arch Rambeau,
corporate vice president for human resources. ``It is involved in
every community where we live. It's in every work place. We need to
start with education and rehabilitation programs.''
   General Dynamics and the union have a pilot drug program at the
Warren plant, which uses counseling and education to help workers
with drug problems.
   Other parts of the contract include a substantial pay increase
over the three years of the contract, along with a ratification
bonus and improved health and safety provisions, Stepp said.
   About 1,000 of the workers covered by the tentative agreement
are on layoff, including 800 of the 2,700 Detroit-area workers.
Stepp and Rambeau declined to discuss specifics of how the contract
will impact those workers, if at all, and also said they could not
provide other specifics until union members are informed.
   Rambeau, however, said lump sum wage increases are included in
the contract, as the company had wanted, but he would not elaborate.
   The union sought a 3 percent pay increase for the base wage of
$13 an hour in each year of the pact. It also sought increased
union representation to help workers with benefits questions, Stepp
said.
</TEXT>
