<DOCNO> AP880616-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 0852EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-EconomicSummit     06-16 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Economic Summit,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delors Says Farm Policy Dispute Could Spoil Toronto Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-European dispute over farm
policy reform may ``spoil the atmosphere'' of next week's
seven-nation economic summit, a senior European official said
Thursday.
   Jacques Delors, chief executive of the European Economic
Community, said a ``divergence of views'' remained between
Washington and the EEC over how to reduce government support for
agriculture.
   ``This ... could well spoil the atmosphere'' of the summit that
starts Sunday in Toronto, Delors told a news conference at EEC
headquarters.
   Delors and other senior officials of the EEC executive
Commission will represent the 12-nation trade bloc at the Toronto
meeting, which will be attended by the heads of government or state
of the United States, Canada, Britain, France, West Germany, Italy
and Japan.
   Delors said he expected no major new initiatives to emerge from
the meeting.
   At last year's seven-nation economic summit President Reagan
unveiled a proposal for phasing out government subsidies to farmers
by the end of the century. The EEC has rejected the idea, saying it
supports coordinated cuts in subsidies but that some government aid
will always be necessary to properly manage farm markets.
   Last fall the EEC proposed what it called ``short term''
measures aimed at easing immediate problems of overproduction of
sugar, grain and other crops. The United States has criticized this
approach.
   Farm reform is a central theme of the current Uruguay Round of
international trade liberalization negotiations being held under
the auspices of the 93-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade.
   Delors also said discussions of key economic and trade issues at
Toronto would be made more difficult by the fact that Reagan will
soon leave office and the U.S. presidential election contest is
heating up.
   ``This will make discussion of the outlook for the world economy
in 1989 and 1990 a little bit more difficult,'' Delors said, adding
that it also would hamper discussion of the GATT trade
liberalization talks.
   Delors said he would be explaining to his summit partners the
EEC's new protocol agreement with the Soviet-led economic bloc, the
Council for Mutual Economic Assistance. The protocol, in which the
East bloc group extends formal recognition to the EEC for the first
time, is to be signed by leaders of both organizations on June 25.
</TEXT>
