<1ST_LINE>r f BC-TimberStrike     06-16 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Timber Strike,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weyerhaeuser Co. Rejects Union Contract Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weyerhaeuser Co. has rejected a union
contract proposal in the midst of a strike against three other
Northwest timber companies, according to a union official.
   A Weyerhaeuser counterproposal was inadequate, Bill Hubbell,
president of the International Woodworkers of America, said
Wednesday.
   Hubbell said no further talks were scheduled with the Tacoma,
Wash.-based company, but negotiating subcommittees will meet in the
next few days to discuss proposed changes in Weyerhaeuser's
profit-sharing plan.
   Weyerhaeuser has about 7,500 union employees.
   About 4,500 union workers have been on strike since June 6
against Willamette Industries Inc., Champion International Corp.
and DAW Forest Products Co. in Oregon, Washington and Montana.
   The woodworkers' union and the Western Council of Industrial
Workers called the strike after the companies rejected a contract
accepted earlier by Eugene-based Bohemia Inc.
   The Bohemia contract reportedly provides a 5 percent raise in
the first year and 4 percent in each of the following three years
of the contract.
   The Weyerhaeuser counterproposal calls for a 4 percent increase
in base pay over four years, Hubbell said. The company also offered
improvements in its profit-sharing plan.
   ``We're absolutely miles apart on base rates as it relates to
the Bohemia settlement,'' Hubbell said.
   Company spokesman Lee Bjorklund declined to comment on details
of Wednesday's negotiations, but described them as constructive.
``Both parties acknowledged the need for considerable discussion of
detailed issues,'' he said.
</TEXT>
