<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Chrysler-ACars     06-16 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-A Cars,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Temporarily Closes Delaware Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. says it will close its Newark,
Del., assembly plant for about 16 weeks to perform major
renovations that will lead to the production of four-door Dodge and
Plymouth sedans.
   The changeover, scheduled to begin Friday, is the final phase of
a $536 million program to begin production of A-body cars, Chrysler
said Wednesday.
   The plant, which made the K-body Plymouth Reliants and Dodge
Aries, employs about 2,000 hourly workers. About 400 people will
work during the changeover, while the remaining 1,600 will
participate in training sessions on robotics, programmable
controllers and several computer systems, Chrysler said.
   The majority of the workers will be gradually phased back into
their jobs as the plant progresses toward full production, Chrysler
spokesman Doug Nicoll said.
   The 36-year-old Newark plant is the seventh Chrysler assembly
plant to undergo extensive modernization and conversion to
state-of-the-art, high-technology manufacturing since the 1984
model year.
   K-car production will continue at the company's Jefferson
Assembly Plant in Detroit before it is moved to Mexico at year's
end.
</TEXT>
