<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Drought-Barges 1stLd-Writethru f0018 06-16 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Barges, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0018,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Brings Traffic To Crawl On Ole Man River</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 3rd pvs, bgng `Nobody knows...' with
Army Corps of Engineers spokesman saying they had discovered a
secondary channel that may let smaller tows pass. Pickup 4th graf,
`While tugboat...'; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time runs slow on Ole Man River these
days but the money's running out fast, as the 50 towboats in
position to nudge 750 barges up the Mississippi sit stranded in
record-low water levels caused by drought.
   Officials fear that up to 1,500 barges could become stranded by
the weekend, equaling ``a traffic jam of semi-trucks bumper to
bumper from New Orleans to Philadelphia (Pa.),'' Michael Logue,
spokesman for the Vicksburg District of the Army Corps of Engineers.
   ``Nobody knows for a fact how long we will be here,'' said James
Burkett, a pilot with the towboat Charles F. Detmar, Jr., stuck
near this Mississippi Delta town. ``Some of the boats have been
here for three days _ at least three days.''
   The low river levels have created bottlenecks in places such as
Vaucluse Landing, Ark., about three miles north of the Greenville
Bridge, where the river is down to nine feet.
   Prospects of ending that bottleneck brightened today.
   ``Late yesterday afternoon, our navigation people were able to
mark a secondary channel at Greenville that we didn't know
existed,'' Michael Logue, a spokesman for the Army Corps of
Engineers in Vicksburg, said today.
   ``Since we found the secondary channel, it looks like the small
tows will be able to go ahead and pass. The larger tows will have
to wait,'' he said.
   While tugboat owners are losing an estimated $10,000 a day in
expenses, their crews are spending the time painting, performing
light maintenance and even fishing.
   ``There's plenty of work, there's always something to do,'' said
Steve Southern, a first mate on the John M. Donnelly, a northbound
towboat pushing 30 barges north.
   The continuing drought throughout the Midwest and Southeast has
brought the Mississippi to its lowest levels for this time of year
since Mark Twain chronicled life on the Big Muddy and officials
began chronicling river levels in 1872.
   The low water has forced barges to operate only during daylight
and to lighten their loads, said Jeffrey Smith, vice president of
the American Waterways Operators in Arlington, Va.
   ``Low water _ since the days of Mark Twain _ has been an
occupational hazard, and they know how to deal with it. Things are
somewhat restricted, but cargo is still moving,'' Smith said
Wednesday.
   Mississippi River barges carry such cargo as grain, petroleum,
chemicals, iron and steel, he said.
   Barges with light loads wait here to be escorted one by one by a
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers channel patrol boat. In all, about 50
towboats were stranded Wednesday along with their charges,
approximately 750 barges, officials said.
   The towboats, which displace more than 9 feet of water, were
stranded in about 9 feet or less as they waited for the corps
dredge Jadwin to arrive today to widen the channel.
   The Jadwin will take at least a day, and possibly two, to dredge
the channel to a depth of 16-20 feet and allow the barges through,
officials said.
   The drought has been good news for some, however.
   Waterways Marine, which takes orders by radio and delivers
supplies to towboats passing by, has been doing a brisk business
since the boats became stranded, said the company's general
manager, James Ashmore.
   In addition to food and housekeeping supplies, Ashmore said, he
is also selling a lot of fuel because many boats are keeping their
engines running.
   Towboat owners are losing money because, in addition to food,
fuel and salary expenses, they get paid per ton-mile, and every
lost day is lost tonnage that could be delivered, Ashmore said.
   The river gauge at Vicksburg, about 70 miles south of
Greenville, read 2.5 feet Tuesday. The lowest level ever recorded
was minus 7 feet in February 1940, when much of the upper river was
frozen, said Ron Goldman, chief of water control management for the
corps district.
   Ashmore said some pilots are resorting to ingenious methods to
try and get through what has become an increasingly narrow and
shallow channel near Greenville.
   One pilot radioed Ashmore to ask if he could unload most of the
fuel from his tanks to make his boat light enough to get through.
Ashmore, however, said he wasn't able to help the pilot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
