<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-88 1206EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-16 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Limit-Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
sharply higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with corn
prices for near-term delivery rocketing up the daily trading limit
for the third consecutive day on dry-weather fears.
   The exchange expanded corn price limits from 10 cents to 15
cents a bushel on Wednesday _ the second day of limit gains _ in
accordance with its rules. The higher limit will remain in effect
at least through Monday.
   Most oat futures also opened up their daily limit of 10 cents a
bushel. Some soybean contracts surged their 30-cents-a-bushel limit
at the opening, but prices fell back on reports that the Reagan
administration would consider limiting soybean exports if the
drought in the Grain Belt continues.
   ``That goes without saying _ they're going to have to reduce
exports if we have a smaller crop,'' said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   Scattered showers brought relief to isolated sections of
Missouri, Illinois and Indiana on Wednesday, and there is a chance
of rain in the Midwest this weekend. But the National Weather
Service on Wednesday predicted below-normal rainfall for the region
in the middle and latter portions of next week.
   In early trading, wheat was 2} cents to 8 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.91 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
to 15 cents higher with July at $2.94{ a bushel; oats were 5 cents
to 10 cents higher with July at $2.89\ a bushel; soybeans were 8
cents to 24 cents higher with July at $9.44 a bushel.
   Most cattle futures were lower while pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .50 cent lower to .25 cent higher with June at
69.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were 1.50 cents lower across the
board with August at 70.27 cents a pound; hogs were .70 cent lower
to .80 cent higher with June at 48.45 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .72 cent lower to 1.78 cents higher with July at 43.75
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed sharply lower on Wednesday.
