<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Bonds     06-16 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bonds,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Plunge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates headed higher as bonds plunged in
value in early trading today, reflecting widespread concerns about
possible hikes in rates overseas, a weak dollar and inflation.
   Long-term issues took the biggest hit. The yield on the
Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond jumped to 8.94 percent from
8.83 percent late Wednesday, while it fell 1\ point in price, or
$12.50 per $1,000 in face amount.
   Prices of U.S. securities started out lower overseas and that
carried over into domestic trading following an unconfirmed report
from a West German newspaper indicating that country's central bank
might be tightening monetary policy.
   The report said the Bundesbank would raise its securities
repurchase rate, a key interest rate, one-quarter percentage point
to 3.5 percent.
   ``It is possible,'' said Robert A. Brusca, chief economist for
Nikko Securities Co. International in New York.
   He noted that a high-ranking Bundesbank official recently
indicated that his country was concerned about inflation due to
better-than-expected economic growth in West Germany and a rise in
money supply. At the same time, the West German mark has been weak
against the dollar in foreign exchange, and the Bundesbank has
intervened on several occasions by selling dollars to buy marks.
   Tightening credit through a hike in interest rates would keep
West German inflation in check and also support the mark, Brusca
said.
   Carol Stone, a senior economist at Nomura Securities
International Inc., said U.S. bond traders were concerned that
Japan might also be tightening policies, especially as its economy
continues to grow, and that could carry over to the United States.
   Adding a negative tone to the U.S. markets today was a decline
in the dollar in foreign exchange and another rise in commodity
prices, both of which heighten concerns about inflation, Ms. Stone
said.
   Inflation erodes the value of fixed-income securities, such as
bonds and notes.
   By midday today in the secondary market for Treasury bonds,
prices of short-term government issues fell between \ point and ]
point, intermediate maturities ranged from { point to } point lower
and long-term issues declined between 1 3-16 point and 1\ point,
according to figures provided by Telerate Inc., a
business-information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, fell 0.65 to 110.03. The Shearson Lehman Hutton
Daily Treasury Bond Index, which makes a similar measurement, stood
at 1,152.22, down 6.71.
   In corporate trading, industrials and utilities fell nearly a
point in light trading, according to the investment firm of Salomon
Brothers Inc.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, lost 1.21 to 283.93.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were up 2 basis points to
6.35 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
Six-month bills rose 6 basis points to 6.60 percent and one-year
bills were up 8 basis points at 6.91 percent.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 7 7-16 percent, down from 8\ percent late
Wednesday. The key rate had risen in Wednesday's session on
technical factors.
</TEXT>
