<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Declines, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar declined against the major
currencies in European trading Thursday, mainly because of
uncertainty over why the West German central bank was selling
dollars. Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the Deutsche Bundesbank sold about
$210 million Wednesday and Thursday. They said there were rumors
the bank will increase money market interest rates next week,
making the West German currency more attractive.
   In London trading, British pounds were more expensive for buyers
at $1.7900 dollars, up from $1.7848 late Wednesday.
   Other late rates in Europe compared with Wednesday's late rates,
included: 1.7505 West German marks, down from 1.7535; 1.4580 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4675; 5.9005 French francs, down from 5.9137;
1.9650 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9690; 1,299.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,300.62; and 1.2160 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2170.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 125.98 Japanese yen, down
from 126.32 late Wednesday. In London late Thursday, the dollar
traded at 125.65 yen and dealers said the dollar's fall against the
German mark was the main reason for the decline.
   Gold bullion prices were mixed, moving higher in London and
lower in Zurich.
   Traders said their market was nervous and prices fluctuated
throughout the day in a narrow range, underpinned by rising
commodity prices in the United States because of drought but
weakened by lower oil prices.
   Gold closed in London at a bid price of $452.80 a troy ounce, up
from Wednesday's late $452.60. The closing price in Zurich was
$452.50 bid, down from $453.
   After the gold market in Hong Kong was shut for a holiday
Wednesday, gold closed there Thursday at $454.52, up from $452.58
Tuesday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $7.21 a troy
ounce, up from $7.14.
</TEXT>
