<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0033,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Share Prices Drop</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later trading activity; No
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell Thursday on the London Stock
Exchange as equities followed Wall Street lower, giving market
players an opportunity to sell and take some profits.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was down 7.4 points, or 0.40 percent, at 1,861.9.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down
20.09 points at 2,111.31 as the London trading session drew to a
close, after opening about 12 points lower.
   London dealers said their market moved into negative territory
during the afternoon as it became evident that Wall Street was
heading lower, pressured by a swift decline in U.S. bond prices.
   Analysts said it was not suprising to see such a technical
correction in bond prices after their sharp gains over the past
several weeks.
   Dealers said major market players were resuming their cautious
stance, as inflationary fears were thought to be creeping back into
the market.
   One equity analyst with London stockbrokerage Barclays de Zoete
Wedd Ltd. said the market still is not convinced that it is on a
stable footing.
   ``It's far too early after the (U.S. April) trade figures to say
we've seen the bottom of the bear market and there are plenty more
factors for Wall Street to take account of,'' he said.
   A barrage of British economic data unsettled the market, raising
fears that the economy may be growing too quickly for its own good,
analysts said.
   The British Treasury reported that the public sector borrowing
requirement, the most widely used measure of Britain's government
deficit or surplus, showed a surplus of 624 million pounds in May,
down from a revised surplus of 1.129 billion pounds in April.
</TEXT>
