<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Germany-Rates     06-16 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Rates,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Bundesbank to Raise Key Interest Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German financial newspaper
reported Thursday that the Bundesbank planned to raise a key
interest rate next week, although the central bank had no comment
on the report.
   The article in the daily Handelsblatt disturbed the U.S.
financial markets, where stock and bond prices fell sharply on
fears that American interest rates would rise also.
   The newspaper said the Bundesbank decided at its Wednesday
policymaking meeting to increase the securities repurchase rate,
which is the rate the central bank pays to trade in securities in
the open market, a quarter percentage point to 3.25 percent.
   The West German central bank has kept the rate constant at 3.25
percent since Nov. 24 of last year as an indication of its policy
of stable interest rates and ample money-market liquidity.
   A Bundesbank spokesman said he could neither confirm nor deny
the rate hike report.
   However, a top West German banking official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said several developments have made the
situation ripe for an increase.
   He listed those developments as a rise in interest rates in the
United States and other countries, a widening gap between German
long-term and short-term rates, a climbing dollar, and a weakening
West German mark.
   Another official, Deutsche Bank economist Martin Huefner, said
the Bundesbank's hike in the ``repo rate,'' if implemented next
week, wouldn't necessarily cause criticism from its partners in
Europe or overseas.
   To brake the dollar's recent rise, either the United States has
to lower its interest rates or West German interest rates have to
go up, Huefner said.
</TEXT>
