<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-16 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Close Higher While Wheat Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of corn, oats and soybeans closed
sharply higher Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade while wheat
futures plunged on fears of a reduction in export sales.
   The three corn contracts for 1988 delivery advanced the limit
for daily trading for the third consecutive session as dry
conditions prevailed in the parched Corn Belt. The Board of Trade
expanded its daily price limit for corn from 10 to 15 cents a
bushel Thursday following two days of 10-cent advances.
   But profit-taking limited the gains in soybean prices, analysts
said.
   ``I think this demonstrates the more serious concern about
potential damage to corn than to the other crops,'' said Dale
Gustafson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   The sell-off in wheat futures was prompted by U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton Yeutter's statement early Thursday that
export subsidy programs may be reviewed if the drought continues,
analysts said.
   Traders sold wheat futures heavily despite Agriculture Secretary
Richard Lyng's denial of any plans to reduce subsidized exports.
   At the close, wheat was 8{ cents to 16 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.78 a bushel; corn was 6{ cents
to 15 cents higher with July at $2.94{ a bushel; oats were 4{ cents
to 10 cents higher with July at $2.89 a bushel; soybeans were 6{
cents lower to 22 cents higher with July at $9.42 a bushel.
</TEXT>
