<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Nymex-Comex     06-16 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nymex-Comex,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY Merc To Pursue Consolidation With Comex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Mercantile Exchange said Thursday
that its board favors consolidating some of the exchange's
operations with those of the Commodities Exchange.
   Chairman William M. Brandt said Mercantile Exchange officials
planned to discuss a ``new plan'' with Comex officials early next
week, but gave no details of what it involved. He declined further
comment.
   A spokeswoman for the Comex, Avery Hunt, said the exchange would
have no comment until after the meeting. She said top Comex
officials were in Europe.
   The two exchanges have periodically discussed the possibility of
consolidating some of their operations for the past decade, but
their talks have intensified in the past year.
   The Mercantile Exchange, established in 1882 , offers trading in
oil, palladium and platinum futures. Volume totaled 25.7 million
contracts last year. The exchange has about 750 members and employs
about 300 people.
   The Commodities Exchange began operating in 1933 and offers
trading in gold, silver and copper futures and options and in
aluminum futures. Its volume amounted to 21.5 million contracts in
1987. The exchange has 772 full members and employs about 400
people.
   A report by a private consulting firm recommended last year that
the exchanges consolidate non-operating functions, such as the
legal and the administrative staffs, while keeping trading
operations separate.
   The Comex board endorsed the consultant's recommendations late
last year, but the Mercantile Exchange took no action on it.
   In its statement Thursday, the Mercantile Exchange said its
board adopted a resolution Wednesday night saying it ``intends to
pursue the consolidation of appropriate operational and
administrative functions.''
   It said consolidation would maximize efficiency and productivity
and achieve economies of scale.
   The Mercantile Exchange's board asked committees of both
exchanges to ``develop specific plans to consolidate operations''
with the Comex.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
