<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     06-16 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Fell $2.45 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 429 money market mutual
funds fell $2.45 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The decline, to $264.80 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $1.73 billion drop in the funds' assets the
previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade
group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 214 general purpose funds fell $1.63 billion to $81.31
billion, assets of 97 broker-dealer funds dropped $371.5 million to
$113.33 billion, and assets of 118 institutional funds declined
$450.3 million to $70.16 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 6.50 percent from 6.42 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 6.39 percent from 6.33 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
unchanged at 37 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts was 5.73
percent as of Wednesday, unchanged from a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.13 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.11
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 7.10 the
previous week. Yields were 7.44 percent on 1-year CDs, unchanged;
7.82 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 7.84 percent; and 8.25
percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.27 percent.
</TEXT>
