<HEAD>Drought Stunting King-Size Vegetable Growth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The assault of the monster tomatoes is being
beaten back by the drought, causing competitive vegetable growers
to worry about prospective entries at the Michigan State Fair.
   Pasquale Sciortino, a St. Clair Shores, Mich., resident who last
year had the largest tomato at the state fair at 2 pounds, 7
ounces, is worried about retaining his crown.
   ``I try to put the water hose in there, but it doesn't do no
good,'' he said.
   The drought also is affecting other king-size growers.
   ``We're watering with a hose, but it's just not like Mother
Nature's rain,'' Roy Schwark of Macomb Township, Mich., said.
   Last year, the Schwarks had the largest watermelon at 43 pounds
and the tallest cornstalk at 14 feet. This year, the corn is only 4
inches tall and the watermelon plants aren't sending out vines.
</TEXT>
