<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PhonyJuice Bjt   06-16 0886</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phony Juice, Bjt,0915</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Beech-Nut Executives Receive 1-Year Prison Terms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former top executives of Beech-Nut
Nutritional Corp. were sentenced Thursday to a year and a day in
prison for distributing phony apple juice intended for babies.
   The case, one of the largest consumer fraud prosecutions of its
kind, involved the intentional shipment of adulterated and
misbranded juice to 20 states, Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands and
five foreign countries between 1978 and 1982.
   ``The fraud was too extensive and too involved to go
unpunished,'' said U.S. District Judge Thomas Platt of Brooklyn,
N.Y., who also levied $100,000 fines against the defendants, Neils
Hoyvald, 54, the former president and chief executive officer of
the company, and John Lavery, 56, a former vice president.
   Platt ordered both to pay court costs, which authorities
estimated would run into the tens of thousands of dollars, as well
as a special assessment of $50 for each of the hundreds of counts
on which they were convicted.
   Beech-Nut, a subsidary of Nestle S.A. of Switzerland, is the
nation's second-largest baby food maker after Gerber Products Co.
Beech-Nut is based in Fort Washington, Pa.
   Prior to sentencing, Hoyvald begged the judge to spare him a
prison term. His voice was thick with emotion and at one point he
wiped a tear from his eye.
   ``It would be so much easier to endure the torment if I had been
alone without a family. ... I cannot bear to look at them. I see in
their eyes disappointment, hurt, disgust and fear for the future
because of my condition,'' Hoyvald said. ``I ask for them and
myself, please don't send me to jail.''
   Hoyvald and Lavery, who are free on bail pending appeal, have
been on full paid leave from Beech-Nut, according to a company
spokesman. Court documents show that Hoyvald received an annual
salary of $165,000 and Lavery was paid $82,000.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas Roche, in his presentencing
statement, asked that the defendants receive substantial prison
terms because they had ``perpetrated a massive fraud on American
and foreign consumers.''
   Customers were ``deprived of the choice of what to feed their
babies,'' Roche said. ``They betrayed the sacred trust accepted by
anyone who undertakes to provide nutrition to infants.''
   Platt said the details of the case pertaining to economic fraud
were ``pretty extraordinary.''
   ``I have no alternative than to do what I am going to do,'' he
said before imposing the sentences.
   The two executives, along with Beech-Nut and two suppliers, were
charged in the phony juice scheme.
   The juice, labeled 100 percent apple juice for babies, was
actually made from a flavored concentrate that had little or no
apple juice, prosecutors charged. No evidence was presented that
the phony juice caused any health problems.
   Beech-Nut, as a corporation, pleaded guilty in November to 215
counts of violating federal food and drug laws and agreed to pay a
$2 million fine.
   After a three-month trial that ended in February, a jury
convicted Hoyvald, of Lebanon, N.J., of 358 counts of violating the
Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act. Each count carried a maximum sentence
of three years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
   Lavery, of Schenectady, N.Y., who oversaw the upstate New York
manufacturing plant where the juice was made, was convicted of
conspiracy, 18 counts of mail fraud and 429 counts of violating
federal food and drug laws.
   Conspiracy and mail fraud carry maximum sentences of five years
in prison.
   At the trial, the government introduced evidence to show that
Beech-Nut bought adulterated and misbranded apple juice concentrate
from two suppliers, who also pleaded guilty, and used this
concentrate in apple juice and mixed apple products.
   Prosecutors said that Lavery knew of the purchase of the bogus
concentrate as early as 1978 and that Hoyvald, who became president
in April 1981, knew of its use the previous January while he was
still senior vice president in charge of marketing.
   Both defense attorneys, Brendan Sullivan Jr. for Hoyvald and
Steve Kimelman for Lavery, had urged Platt to sentence their
clients to probation and community service or home detention.
   Sullivan said Hoyvald had been punished by the loss of his
position and loss of presitige brought about by extensive media
coverage of the case.
   ``Alternative sentencing can achieve the desire of the system to
punish,'' Kimelman said. Lavery declined to comment before
sentencing.
   Andrew Maloney, the U.S. attorney for the Eastern District of
New York, said he was satisfied that the sentences were a
``sufficient deterrent'' to other executives.
   He said economic fraud cases would continue to be a high
priority, adding that ``a great effort went into fighting this
major corporation with all its megabucks.''
   Dr. Richard C. Theurer, the current Beech-Nut president, said in
a written statement said the company had invested $10 million in
the last five years to ensure the quality of their products.
   ``Our products on the supermarket shelves today are pure,''
Theurer said. ``We know this because we test them every day.''
   In May 1987, Beech-Nut settled a class-action suit involving the
phony juice that was filed in federal court in Philadelphia.
   The company agreed to set up a $5 million cash fund for
consumers and to provide $2.5 million in Beech-Nut and affiliated
products to retailers.
</TEXT>
