<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 2ndLd-Writethru   06-16 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0631</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS down to up in 4th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market tumbled Thursday, mirroring a
plunge in bond prices and eradicating gains in the previous two
sessions that had put the Dow Jones average at a post-crash high.
   The key index of 30 industrial stocks, which climbed 32 points
in the prior two trading days, plummeted 37.16 points to close at
2,094.24.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 5-to-2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 435 issues up, 1,089
down and 425 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 161.55 million shares,
up from 150.26 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
186.038 million shares.
   Analysts had said there was a natural tendency for some
profit-taking to set in following the Dow average's impressive
advance of late.
   But the day's decline was exacerbated by disarray in the credit
markets, which were reacting to an unsubstantiated report in a West
Germany newspaper that indicated the central Bundesbank might be
tightening monetary policy.
   ``There are some indications that Japan might be doing the same,
and that says effectively that if the Federal Reserve wants to keep
the dollar stable, it will not give interest rates much room to
decline,'' said Hugh Johnson, senior vice president at First Albany
Corp.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year issue finished off 1| points,
or down more than $16 per $1,000 in face value.
   ``There was profit-taking as expected, but investors were given
a shove by the suggestion that monetary policy might be tightening
in Germany and Japan,'' Johnson said.
   Further pressuring the markets was a government report that
showed operating rates at American factories, mines and utilities
rose to 82.9 percent in May, the highest level in more than eight
years.
   The report, well above market expectations, was interpreted as a
sign that inflation may be lurking.
   Analysts fear a crack in investors' confidence, which has been
building gradually, and described the drop as jolting. ``It just
points out what thin ice we're on,'' Johnson said.
   The Dow fell through the psychologically important 2,100-point
level, a mark analysts had hoped would serve as a floor for a
further advance.
   But lower stock prices also could bring out some bargain hunters.
   ``We would use any weakness as a buying opportunity,'' one
trader said.
   Among actively traded issues, Texaco was down ] at 49{. The oil
company, which will face Carl Icahn it its annual shareholders
meeting Friday, announced a joint venture with a Saudi Arabian oil
company.
   General Electric was off \ at 43\. The company said it will
acquire Borg-Warner's chemical division for $2.31 billion in cash.
   Intermedics jumped 7 to 42\. The company agreed to be acquired
by Swiss-based Sulzer Brothers for $43 a share, or about $800
million.
   Elsewhere, IBM fell 1| to 117[, Deere fell 2 at 46}, Philip
Morris fell 1[ to 83, and Smithkline Beckman was off 9\ at 45}. The
pharmaceutical company predicted 1988 operating earnings will be
below last year's levels.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market decreased in value by $35.833
billion, or 1.31 percent, from Wednesday.
   The NYSE index fell 2.23 to 152.44.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials fell 5.40 to 311.96,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index fell 4.68 to 269.77.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 1.71
to 307.07. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 387.10, off 1.98.
</TEXT>
