<2ND_LINE>AM-Paisley-United Technologies, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0289,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Week After Leaving Pentagon, Paisley Took Consulting Job</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf bgng, `Paisley began,' to
UPDATE with report on former Navy Secretary Webb's comments on
Paisley, including that he was a central figure in the probe</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Within a week of his departure from the
Pentagon, Melvyn Paisley went to work for United Technologies Corp.
as a consultant to help the firm get defense contracts, sources
said Thursday.
   On Tuesday, FBI agents seized records pertaining to Paisley when
they searched United Technologies' Washington offices as part of a
massive fraud and bribery probe involving alleged corruption at the
Pentagon, said the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The investigation involves court-authorized phone taps and bugs
at Paisley's consulting office after he left the Pentagon, said
other sources.
   The FBI agents also took from United Technologies' Washington
office documents relating to the 404 and T-406 engines which Pratt
& Whitney, a United Technologies' unit, builds for the Navy.
   Paisley began working as a United Technologies consultant within
a week after he left his Pentagon job last year, according to the
sources. Paisley was the assistant secretary of the Navy for
research, and engineering and systems. He had been recruited for
the position in 1981 by John Lehman, the secretary of the Navy and
Paisley's boss.
   Former Navy Secretary James H. Webb Jr. told The Washington Post
that he was briefed about the fraud and bribery probe last fall and
as a result of his briefings, ``It was clear that Paisley was one
of the central figures'' in the investigation.
   In addition, Webb said that 10 days before Paisley left the
Pentagon in March 1987, he had persuaded Navy officials to give him
a contract as a consultant to the office he was leaving and he won
approval to maintain his security clearance for access to
information involving the military's most secret ``black programs.''
   Webb told the Post for a story in Friday's editions that he
canceled Paisley's contract within days after taking office in
April 1987 because ``it appeared to be a conflict of interest,''
and that Paisley received no fees for it.
   Paisley, 63, a native of Portland, Ore., went to the Pentagon
from the Boeing Co., where he was manager for international
operations in the company's space and information division.
   Paisley is still a consultant for United Technologies and the
sources said his work involves lobbying efforts on behalf of
engines built by the company's Pratt & Whitney engine division.
   The 404 is being built for the Navy's F@A-18 jet airplane, and
the T-406 engine, a smaller engine which is being built for the
V-22 Osprey, a vertical take-off jet that is being developed for
both the Marines and the Air Force.
   The Pentagon has awarded $316 million worth of 404 engine
contracts to Pratt & Whitney in the past two years.
   General Electric originally had the chief contract to provide
engines for the F-18, but the Navy, seeking to drive down costs,
approached Pratt & Whitney two years ago and asked if the company
could build engines for the plane.
   Larry Bingman, a spokesman for United Technologies, refused to
confirm or deny Paisley's status as a consultant. ``We, as a matter
of policy, do not confirm who consults with United Technologies,''
Bingman said in answer to questions.
   While he was in the Pentagon, Paisley was a key figure in the
Reagan administration's naval build-up, which in turn was a
centerpiece of the large increases in defense spending that Reagan
won during his first term after his 1980 campaign pledge to
``re-arm America.''
   Paisley and Lehman worked with Everett Pyatt, assistant Navy
secretary for shipbuilding.
   ``Everything on the Navy's procurement side went through those
three,'' said one congressional source Thursday, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
